ps://www.jstor.org/stable/27702439 online]\n* Tindall, George B. \"The significance of Howard W. Odum to Southern history: A preliminary estimate.\" ''Journal of Southern History'' 24.3 (1958): 285-307.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Odum,+Howard+W.}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Howard Washington Odum}}\n* [http://www.lib.unc.edu/mss/inv/o/Odum,Howard_Washington.html Inventory of the Howard Washington Odum Papers, 1908\u20131982], in the [[Southern Historical Collection]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|UNC-Chapel Hill]]\n\n{{American Sociological Association presidents|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odum, Howard W}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:American sociologists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill faculty]]\n[[Category:Emory University alumni]]\n[[Category:Clark University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Sociological Association]]\n[[Category:People from Barrow County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_W._Odum"}
{"title_page": "Indochinese lutung", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Indochinese lutung<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Groves|pages=176|id=12100719}}</ref>\n| image = SAIGON ZOO VIETNAM JAN 2012 (7009538995).jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = Nadler, T. | author2 = Timmins, R. J. | author3 = Richardson, M. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Trachypithecus germaini'' | volume = 2008 | page = e.T39874A10278272 | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T39874A10278272.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Trachypithecus\n| parent = Trachypithecus cristatus group\n| species = germaini\n| authority = ([[Henri Milne-Edwards|Milne-Edwards]], 1876)\n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n| range_map = Indochinese Lutung area.png\n| range_map_caption = Indochinese lutung range\n}}\n\nThe '''Indochinese lutung''' (''Trachypithecus germaini'') is a [[lutung]] native to [[Thailand]], [[Burma]], [[Cambodia]], [[Laos]] and [[Vietnam]].<ref name=msw3/><ref name=iucn/> The [[Old World monkey]] was previously included in ''[[Trachypithecus cristatus]]''<ref name=msw3/> and ''[[Trachypithecus villosus]]''.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nTwo subspecies are recognized:<ref name=msw3/>\n*''Trachypithecus germaini germaini''\n*''Trachypithecus germaini caudalis''\n\n== Taxonomy and Evolutionary History ==\nThe Indochinese lutung is part of the silvered langur subfamily [[Colobinae]], which is comprised of six distinct species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Supanuam|first=Praween|last2=Tanomtong|first2=Alongklod|last3=Khunsook|first3=Sumpars|last4=Khrueanet|first4=Wilailuk|last5=Pinthong|first5=Krit|last6=Wonkaonoi|first6=Weeranuch|date=2015|title=The First Report on Standardized Karyotype and Idiogram of Indochinese Silvered Langur, Trachypithecus germaini germaini (Primates, Colobinae) in Thailand|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cytologia/80/2/80_183/_article|journal=CYTOLOGIA|language=en|volume=80|issue=2|pages=183\u2013192|doi=10.1508/cytologia.80.183|issn=0011-4545}}</ref> Two subspecies of the Indochinese lutung are recognized: ''Trachypithecus germaini germaini'' and ''Trachypithecus germaini caudalis.''<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Parr|first=John W. K.|title=A Guide to the Large Mammals of Thailand|publisher=Sarakadee Press|year=2003|isbn=9744840404|location=Bangkok|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Francis, Charles M.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/45914721|title=A photographic guide to mammals of Thailand & South-East Asia|date=2001|publisher=Asia Books|oclc=45914721}}</ref> However, the classification of the Indochinese lutung has been contested, with ''T. germaini'' being grouped with other species in its subfamily.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Timmins|first=R. J.|last2=Steinmetz|first2=R.|last3=Poulsen|first3=M. K.|last4=Evans|first4=T. D.|last5=Duckworth|first5=J. W.|last6=Boonratana|first6=R.|date=2013|title=The Indochinese Silvered Leaf Monkey Trachypithecus germaini ( Sensu lato ) in Lao PDR|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1896/052.026.0112|journal=Primate Conservation|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=75\u201387|doi=10.1896/052.026.0112|issn=0898-6207|via=}}</ref> ''T. germaini'' and ''T. margarita'' were considered to be a single species, ''T. villosus,'' but morphological and genetic evidence has shown that they are distinct.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''T. germaini'' has also been grouped with ''[[Silvery lutung|T. cristatus]]'' until recent reclassifications.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''T. germaini'' goes by several common names such as the Indochinese lutung, Germain\u2019s langur, Germain\u2019s silver langur, Indochinese leaf monkey, and Indochinese silvered langur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://checklist.cites.org/#/en/search/output_layout=alphabetical&level_of_listing=0&show_synonyms=1&show_author=1&show_english=1&show_spanish=1&show_french=1&scientific_name=Trachypithecus%20germaini&page=1&per_page=20|title=Checklist of CITES species|website=checklist.cites.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe Indochinese lutung has black colouration on its hands and feet, as well as the upper part of its body which fades into paler grey on its underparts.<ref name=\":0\" /> They have long grey tails and white hairs on its round face.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their young have bright orange fur. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Distribution and Habitat ==\nThe limits of the distribution of Indochinese lutung are not well known, but they are currently found in [[Asia]], specifically [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]], [[Laos|Lao PDR]], [[Myanmar]], and [[Thailand]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Populations in Vietnam are severely reduced, with few sightings in the last 50 years.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> In [[Laos|Lao PDR]], the species has no continuous range, rather multiple patches of higher relative abundance.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Duckworth, William (1964-). Compilation. Salter, Richard Edward. Compilation. Khamkhoun Khounboline. Compilation.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/799695132|title=Wildlife in Lao PDR : 1999 status report|date=1999|publisher=World Conservation Union|year=|isbn=2-8317-0483-9|location=|pages=|oclc=799695132}}</ref> Its distribution in [[Cambodia]] is widespread, but its abundance will vary from common to rare.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> In [[Thailand]], the species is common, with many protected areas supporting large populations.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> The Indochinese lutung is a terrestrial [[Arboreal locomotion|arboreal]] species, often found in lowlands.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> They prefer [[evergreen]] and [[semi-evergreen]], [[riverine]], [[Mixed deciduous forest|mixed deciduous]], and [[Gallery forest|galley forests]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> They are not commonly found at high elevations or hilly areas.<ref name=\"iucn\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\nThe diet of the Indochinese lutung is [[folivorous]] consisting of leaves, shoots, and fruits.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=de Groot|first=Brenda|last2=Nekaris|first2=Anna|date=2016|title=Ecology of the Germain's Langur Trachypithecus germaini in a Pre-release Environment and the Implications for its conservation|url=|journal=Asian Primates Journal|volume=6|issue=1|pages=|via=Research Gate}}</ref> This diet dictates a resting period, in which they can undergo the process of [[Ruminant|rumination]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Korstjens|first=Amanda H.|last2=Lehmann|first2=Julia|last3=Dunbar|first3=R.I.M.|date=2010|title=Resting time as an ecological constraint on primate biogeography|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.012|journal=Animal Behaviour|volume=79|issue=2|pages=361\u2013374|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.012|issn=0003-3472|via=}}</ref> ''\u00a0\u00a0'' \n\n''T. germaini,'' and other Asian colobines, are unsocial [[Primate|primates]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>Kirkpatrick, R.C. 2011. The Asian colobines: diversity among leaf-eating monkeys. In: Primates in Perspective, C.J. Campbell, A. Fuentes, K.C. MacKinnon and M. Panger (eds.), pp. 189\u2013202. Oxford University Press, Oxford, UK.<br /></ref> They have a lower affinity to social behaviour in comparison to feeding and resting which makes up the majority of their day.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, ''T. germaini'' is often found in troops of 10 to 50 individuals in close social proximity.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Predators and Threats ==\nPredators of lutungs, including the Indochinese lutung, include [[Leopard|leopards]], [[Tiger|tigers]], [[Dhole|dholes]], and large [[Snake|snakes]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Harding|first=Lee E.|date=2010-01-25|title=Trachypithecus cristatus (Primates: Cercopithecidae)|url=https://academic.oup.com/mspecies/article-lookup/doi/10.1644/862.1|journal=Mammalian Species|language=en|volume=42|pages=149\u2013165|doi=10.1644/862.1|issn=0076-3519}}</ref> A variety of small [[Carnivore|carnivores]] will feed on lutung young.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nPrevalent threats to the Indochinese lutung include [[hunting]], [[Pet trade|exotic pet trading]], and habitat loss due to [[agricultural expansion]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> \n\n== Status and Conservation ==\n''T. germaini'' is considered endangered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]], with a greater than 50% decline in the past three generations.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> It is listed under [[CITES]] Appendix II, meaning that trade of the species must be controlled to avoid endangerment.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cites.org/eng/disc/how.php|title=How CITES works {{!}} CITES|website=www.cites.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nLittle conservation efforts have been made, despite the species designation.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Several [[Protected area|protected areas]] have been established across its range which aids in the conservation of the species. The species has been recorded in numerous protected areas in [[Vietnam]] and [[Thailand]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> In [[Vietnam]], their populations have increased in two protected areas, [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c National Park]] and [[Ki\u00ean L\u01b0\u01a1ng District|Ki\u00ean L\u01b0\u01a1ng Karst Area]], demonstrating the importance conservation efforts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Tran|first=Bang|last2=Nguyen|first2=Minh Anh|last3=Nguyen|first3=Dat Quoc|last4=Truong|first4=Quan Bich Thi|last5=Ang|first5=Andie|last6=Covert|first6=Herbert H.|last7=Hoang|first7=Duc Minh|date=2017|title=Current conservation status of Germain\u2019s langur (Trachypithecus germaini) in Vietnam|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10329-017-0610-2|journal=Primates|language=en|volume=58|issue=3|pages=435\u2013440|doi=10.1007/s10329-017-0610-2|issn=0032-8332|via=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{C.Colobinae nav}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1202908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:lutung, Indochinese}}\n[[Category:Trachypithecus|Indochinese lutung]]\n[[Category:Primates of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Laos]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Endangered fauna of Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1876|Indochinese lutung]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Indochinese lutung<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Groves|pages=176|id=12100719}}</ref>\n| image = SAIGON ZOO VIETNAM JAN 2012 (7009538995).jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = Nadler, T. | author2 = Timmins, R. J. | author3 = Richardson, M. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Trachypithecus germaini'' | volume = 2008 | page = e.T39874A10278272 | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T39874A10278272.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Trachypithecus\n| parent = Trachypithecus cristatus group\n| species = germaini\n| authority = ([[Henri Milne-Edwards|Milne-Edwards]], 1876)\n| synonyms = \n| synonyms_ref = \n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n| range_map = Indochinese Lutung area.png\n| range_map_caption = Indochinese lutung range\n}}\n\nThe '''Indochinese lutung''' (''Trachypithecus germaini'') is a [[lutung]] native to [[Thailand]], [[Burma]], [[Cambodia]], [[Laos]] and [[Vietnam]].<ref name=msw3/><ref name=iucn/> The [[Old World monkey]] was previously included in ''[[Trachypithecus cristatus]]''<ref name=msw3/> and ''[[Trachypithecus villosus]]''.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nTwo subspecies are recognized:<ref name=msw3/>\n*''Trachypithecus germaini germaini''\n*''Trachypithecus germaini caudalis''\n\n== Taxonomy and Evolutionary History ==\nThe Indochinese lutung is part of the silvered langur subfamily [[Colobinae]], which is comprised of six distinct species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Supanuam|first=Praween|last2=Tanomtong|first2=Alongklod|last3=Khunsook|first3=Sumpars|last4=Khrueanet|first4=Wilailuk|last5=Pinthong|first5=Krit|last6=Wonkaonoi|first6=Weeranuch|date=2015|title=The First Report on Standardized Karyotype and Idiogram of Indochinese Silvered Langur, Trachypithecus germaini germaini (Primates, Colobinae) in Thailand|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cytologia/80/2/80_183/_article|journal=CYTOLOGIA|language=en|volume=80|issue=2|pages=183\u2013192|doi=10.1508/cytologia.80.183|issn=0011-4545}}</ref> Two subspecies of the Indochinese lutung are recognized: ''Trachypithecus germaini germaini'' and ''Trachypithecus germaini caudalis.''<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Parr|first=John W. K.|title=A Guide to the Large Mammals of Thailand|publisher=Sarakadee Press|year=2003|isbn=9744840404|location=Bangkok|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Francis, Charles M.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/45914721|title=A photographic guide to mammals of Thailand & South-East Asia|date=2001|publisher=Asia Books|oclc=45914721}}</ref> However, the classification of the Indochinese lutung has been contested, with ''T. germaini'' being grouped with other species in its subfamily.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Timmins|first=R. J.|last2=Steinmetz|first2=R.|last3=Poulsen|first3=M. K.|last4=Evans|first4=T. D.|last5=Duckworth|first5=J. W.|last6=Boonratana|first6=R.|date=2013|title=The Indochinese Silvered Leaf Monkey Trachypithecus germaini ( Sensu lato ) in Lao PDR|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1896/052.026.0112|journal=Primate Conservation|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=75\u201387|doi=10.1896/052.026.0112|issn=0898-6207|via=}}</ref> ''T. germaini'' and ''T. margarita'' were considered to be a single species, ''T. villosus,'' but morphological and genetic evidence has shown that they are distinct.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''T. germaini'' has also been grouped with ''[[Silvery lutung|T. cristatus]]'' until recent reclassifications.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''T. germaini'' goes by several common names such as the Indochinese lutung, Germain\u2019s langur, Germain\u2019s silver langur, Indochinese leaf monkey, and Indochinese silvered langur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://checklist.cites.org/#/en/search/output_layout=alphabetical&level_of_listing=0&show_synonyms=1&show_author=1&show_english=1&show_spanish=1&show_french=1&scientific_name=Trachypithecus%20germaini&page=1&per_page=20|title=Checklist of CITES species|website=checklist.cites.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe Indochinese lutung has black colouration on its hands and feet, as well as the upper part of its body which fades into paler grey on its underparts.<ref name=\":0\" /> They have long grey tails and white hairs on its round face.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their young have bright orange fur. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Distribution and Habitat ==\nThe limits of the distribution of Indochinese lutung are not well known, but they are currently found in [[Asia]], specifically [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]], [[Laos|Lao PDR]], [[Myanmar]], and [[Thailand]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Populations in Vietnam are severely reduced, with few sightings in the last 50 years.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> In [[Laos|Lao PDR]], the species has no continuous range, rather multiple patches of higher relative abundance.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Duckworth, William (1964-). Compilation. Salter, Richard Edward. Compilation. Khamkhoun Khounboline. Compilation.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/799695132|title=Wildlife in Lao PDR : 1999 status report|date=1999|publisher=World Conservation Union|year=|isbn=2-8317-0483-9|location=|pages=|oclc=799695132}}</ref> Its distribution in [[Cambodia]] is widespread, but its abundance will vary from common to rare.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> In [[Thailand]], the species is common, with many protected areas supporting large populations.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> The Indochinese lutung is a terrestrial [[Arboreal locomotion|arboreal]] species, often found in lowlands.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> They prefer [[evergreen]] and [[semi-evergreen]], [[riverine]], [[Mixed deciduous forest|mixed deciduous]], and [[Gallery forest|galley forests]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> They are not commonly found at high elevations or hilly areas.<ref name=\"iucn\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\nThe diet of the Indochinese lutung is [[folivorous]] consisting of leaves, shoots, and fruits.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=de Groot|first=Brenda|last2=Nekaris|first2=Anna|date=2016|title=Ecology of the Germain's Langur Trachypithecus germaini in a Pre-release Environment and the Implications for its conservation|url=|journal=Asian Primates Journal|volume=6|issue=1|pages=|via=Research Gate}}</ref> This diet dictates a resting period, in which they can undergo the process of [[Ruminant|rumination]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Korstjens|first=Amanda H.|last2=Lehmann|first2=Julia|last3=Dunbar|first3=R.I.M.|date=2010|title=Resting time as an ecological constraint on primate biogeography|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.012|journal=Animal Behaviour|volume=79|issue=2|pages=361\u2013374|doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2009.11.012|issn=0003-3472|via=}}</ref> ''\u00a0\u00a0'' \n\n''T. germaini,'' and other Asian colobines, are unsocial [[Primate|primates]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>Kirkpatrick, R.C. 2011. The Asian colobines: diversity among leaf-eating monkeys. In: Primates in Perspective, C.J. Campbell, A. Fuentes, K.C. MacKinnon and M. Panger (eds.), pp. 189\u2013202. Oxford University Press, Oxford, UK.<br /></ref> They have a lower affinity to social behaviour in comparison to feeding and resting which makes up the majority of their day.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, ''T. germaini'' is often found in troops of 10 to 50 individuals in close social proximity.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Predators and Threats ==\nPredators of lutungs, including the Indochinese lutung, include [[Leopard|leopards]], [[Tiger|tigers]], [[Dhole|dholes]], and large [[Snake|snakes]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Harding|first=Lee E.|date=2010-01-25|title=Trachypithecus cristatus (Primates: Cercopithecidae)|url=https://academic.oup.com/mspecies/article-lookup/doi/10.1644/862.1|journal=Mammalian Species|language=en|volume=42|pages=149\u2013165|doi=10.1644/862.1|issn=0076-3519}}</ref> A variety of small [[Carnivore|carnivores]] will feed on lutung young.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nPrevalent threats to the Indochinese lutung include [[hunting]], [[Pet trade|exotic pet trading]], and habitat loss due to [[agricultural expansion]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> \n\n== Status and Conservation ==\n''T. germaini'' is considered endangered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]], with a greater than 50% decline in the past three generations.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> It is listed under [[CITES]] Appendix II, meaning that trade of the species must be controlled to avoid endangerment.<ref name=\"iucn\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cites.org/eng/disc/how.php|title=How CITES works {{!}} CITES|website=www.cites.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nLittle conservation efforts have been made, despite the species designation.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Several [[Protected area|protected areas]] have been established across its range which aids in the conservation of the species. The species has been recorded in numerous protected areas in [[Vietnam]] and [[Thailand]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> In [[Vietnam]], their populations have increased in two protected areas, [[Ph\u00fa Qu\u1ed1c National Park]] and [[Ki\u00ean L\u01b0\u01a1ng District|Ki\u00ean L\u01b0\u01a1ng Karst Area]], demonstrating the importance conservation efforts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Tran|first=Bang|last2=Nguyen|first2=Minh Anh|last3=Nguyen|first3=Dat Quoc|last4=Truong|first4=Quan Bich Thi|last5=Ang|first5=Andie|last6=Covert|first6=Herbert H.|last7=Hoang|first7=Duc Minh|date=2017|title=Current conservation status of Germain\u2019s langur (Trachypithecus germaini) in Vietnam|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s10329-017-0610-2|journal=Primates|language=en|volume=58|issue=3|pages=435\u2013440|doi=10.1007/s10329-017-0610-2|issn=0032-8332|via=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{C.Colobinae nav}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1202908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:lutung, Indochinese}}\n[[Category:Trachypithecus|Indochinese lutung]]\n[[Category:Primates of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Laos]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Endangered fauna of Asia]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1876|Indochinese lutung]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference list duplication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indochinese_lutung"}
{"title_page": "Sunshine Skyway Bridge", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Sunshine Bridge}}\n{{Short description|Bridge over Tampa Bay, Florida, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| image               = SunshineSkywayBridge-4SC 6643-15.jpg\n| image_upright       = 1.3\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|27.625|-82.65833|display=inline}}\n| carries             = 4 lanes of {{Jct|state=FL|I|275|US|19}}\n| crosses             = [[Tampa Bay]]\n| locale              = South of [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] and north of [[Terra Ceia, Florida]]\n| official_name       = Bob Graham Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| other_name          = The Skyway\n| named_for           = [[Bob Graham]]\n| owner               = \n| maint               = [[Florida Department of Transportation]]\n| heritage            = \n| id                  = 150189\n| website             = \n| design              = [[Cable-stayed bridge|Cable-stayed]]\n| material            = \n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|4.14|mi|km|1}}\n| width               = {{convert|94|ft|m|0}}\n| height              = {{convert|430|ft|m|0}}<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20140816/ARTICLE/140819777 |title= If Skyway Run Gets Approval, Appeal Could Be Widespread |last= Bergen |first= Katy |date= August 16, 2014 |work= [[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |access-date= May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = {{convert|1200|ft|m|0}}\n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = <!-- clearance above is unlimited as none of the tower structure goes over the roadway on the 1987 cable-stayed bridge -->\n| clearance_below     = {{convert|180.5|ft|m|0}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tampabaypilots.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Sunshine-Skyway-Bridge-Vertical-Clearance.pdf |title= Port Community Information Bulletin # 04-11: Sunshine Skyway Vertical Clearance |last= Dickinson |first= S.L. |date= March 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418052116/http://tampabaypilots.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Sunshine-Skyway-Bridge-Vertical-Clearance.pdf |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |access-date=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n| lanes               = 4\n| life                = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = \n| engineering         = Figg & Muller Engineering Group\n| builder             = [[American Bridge Company]]\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = June 1982<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greenbenchmonthly.com/st-petersburg-history/history-of-the-sunshine-skyway/|title=History Of the Sunshine Skyway|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109071424/https://greenbenchmonthly.com/st-petersburg-history/history-of-the-sunshine-skyway/|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaroads.com/florida/sunshine-skyway/|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge - AA Roads|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109072417/https://www.aaroads.com/florida/sunshine-skyway/|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><!--For simplicity, this infobox will be for the 1987 current bridge. -->\n| complete            = \n| cost                = $244 million\n| open                = {{start date and age|1987|04|20}}\n| inaugurated         = \n| rebuilt             = \n| collapsed           = <!--For current bridge-->\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = 59,178 (2018)<ref name=\"FDOT\">{{cite web|title=Florida Bridge Information \u2013 2019 1st Quarter|url=https://fdotwww.blob.core.windows.net/sitefinity/docs/default-source/maintenance/str/bi/florida-bridge-information-jan-2019.pdf?sfvrsn=dd1492ae_4|website=[[Florida Department of Transportation]]|date=January 2, 2019|access-date=February 14, 2019|page=216|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| toll                = $1.50 for passenger cars or $1.07 with [[SunPass]]\n| map_type            = USA Florida\n| map_relief          = yes\n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = \n| map_size            = 284\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name        = (Former) Sunshine Skyway Bridge<!--This infobox is for the bridge preceding the 1980 collapse with the same name-->\n| image       = Sunshine_Skyway_Bridge_3.JPG\n| image_upright = 1.3\n| carries     = 4 lanes of {{Jct|state=FL|US|19}} (as two separate 2-lane bridges for each direction) <!--I-275 did not exist in this region until around 1982 --> \n| crosses     = [[Tampa Bay]]\n| locale      = South of [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] and north of [[Terra Ceia, Florida]]\n| design      = [[Cantilever bridge]]\n| material    = Steel\n| material1   = Steel\n| material2   = Reinforced concrete\n| length      = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| width       = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| height      = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| mainspan    = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| below       = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| begin       = 1950 (original bridge, later converted to northbound only traffic)<br/>1967 (southbound span)\n| inaugurated = {{Start date|1954|09|06}}\n| complete    = 1954 (northbound span)<br/> 1971 (southbound span)\n| replaces    = Bee Line Ferry\n| replaced_by = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| open        = {{Start date and age|1954|09|06}} (original bridge)\n| collapsed   = {{end date and age|1980|05|09}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Bob Graham Sunshine Skyway Bridge''', often referred to as the '''Sunshine Skyway Bridge''' or simply '''the Skyway,''' is a [[cable-stayed bridge|cable-stayed]] bridge spanning the [[Tampa Bay|Lower Tampa Bay]] connecting [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], [[Florida]] to [[Terra Ceia, Florida|Terra Ceia]]. The current Sunshine Skyway opened in 1987 and is the second bridge of that name on the site. It was designed by the Figg & Muller Engineering Group and built by the [[American Bridge Company]] and is considered a symbol of Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Greatest American Bridges (& What We Can Learn from Them)|url=https://bridgemastersinc.com/greatest-american-bridges/|date=September 30, 2016|website=Bridge Masters|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe four-lane bridge carries [[Interstate 275 (Florida)|Interstate 275]] and [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|U.S. Route 19]], passing through [[Pinellas County, Florida|Pinellas County]], [[Hillsborough County, Florida|Hillsborough County]], and [[Manatee County, Florida|Manatee County]]. It is a [[toll road]], with a $1.50 toll assessed on two-axle vehicles traveling in either direction and collected via cash or the state's [[SunPass]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Henson |first1=Chuck |title=SunPass confusion clogs Sunshine Skyway tolls |url=https://www.baynews9.com/fl/tampa/traffic/2018/04/30/sunpass-sunshine-skyway-bridge |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=www.baynews9.com |publisher=Spectrum News / Bay News 9 |date=April 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe original bridge opened in 1954 and was the site of two major maritime disasters within a few months in 1980. In January 1980, the [[United States Coast Guard]] Cutter {{USCGC|Blackthorn|WLB-391|2}} collided with the tanker ''Capricorn'' near the bridge, resulting in the sinking of the cutter and the loss of 23 crew members. In May 1980, the freighter ''[[MV Summit Venture]]'' collided with a bridge support during a sudden [[squall]], resulting in the structural collapse of the southbound span and the deaths of 35 people when vehicles plunged into Tampa Bay.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nunez |first1=Judy Kay |title=28 January 1980, Blackthorn and Capricorn: Collision with History in Tampa Bay |url=http://diginole.lib.fsu.edu/islandora/object/fsu:180688/datastream/PDF/view |publisher=Florida State University Libraries |accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref> Within a few years, the damaged span was demolished, the surviving span was partially demolished and converted into a long [[fishing pier]], and the current bridge was built.\n\n==History==\n===Original bridge===\nThe original two-lane bridge was built by the Virginia Bridge Company and opened to traffic on September 6, 1954,<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Zt4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72 |title= Tampa Bay Crossing Spans 14 Miles of Tidewater |magazine= [[Popular Mechanics]] |date= August 1954 |pages= 72\u201373 |via= [[Google Books]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=September 7, 1954 |title=Thousands cross Sunshine Skyway Span |page=1 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S5kcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1GQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4161%2C1128738 |via= [[Google Books]]}}</ref> with a similar structure built parallel and to the west of it in 1969 to make it a four-lane bridge and bring it to [[Interstate Highway standards]]. Opening of the newer span was delayed until 1971 for reinforcing of the south main pier, which had cracked due to insufficient [[Deep foundation|supporting pile]] depth.<ref name=\"fbs\">http://interstate275florida.blogspot.com/2009/07/old-sunshine-skyway-bridge.html{{sps|certain=y|date=May 2016}}</ref> The second span was used for all southbound traffic, while the original span was converted to carry northbound traffic.\n\nThe old bridge replaced a [[ferry]] from [[Pinellas County, Florida|Point Pinellas]] to [[Pinellas County, Florida#Spanish and British Florida|Piney Point]]. [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|US&nbsp;19]] was extended from [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] to its current end north.\n\n=== 1980 collapse ===\n\n[[File:Skywayaccident.jpg|thumb|220px|right|The collapsed original bridge on May 9, 1980, after the ''Summit Venture'' collision. Photo by ''[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]'']]\n[[File:Skyway Bridge 1.jpg|thumb|220px|right|The current bridge (top) and the old bridges. The piers of the current bridge are protected by [[Dolphin (structure)|structural dolphins]]. The collapsed bridge is under demolition.]]\nThe southbound span (opened in 1971) of the original bridge was destroyed at 7:33&nbsp;a.m. on May 9, 1980, when the freighter [[MV Summit Venture|MV ''Summit Venture'']] collided with a pier (support column) during a sudden [[squall]], sending over {{convert|1200|ft|m}} of the bridge plummeting into Tampa Bay. The collision caused six cars, a truck, and a [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] bus to fall {{convert|150|ft|m}} into the water, killing 35 people.<ref>{{cite news |title= A Blinding Squall, then Death |work= St. Petersburg Times |url= http://www2.sptimes.com/Weather/SW.2.html |access-date= February 1, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Day Skyway Fell: May 9, 1980 |work= St. Petersburg Times |first= Jean |last= Heller |date=May 7, 2000 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/050700/TampaBay/Horrific_accident_cre.shtml |accessdate=July 4, 2007}}</ref> One man, Wesley MacIntire, survived when his [[Ford Courier]] pickup truck landed on the deck of the ''Summit Venture'' before falling into the bay. He sued the company that owned the ship, and settled in 1984 for $175,000 (${{Inflation|US|175000|1984|r=-3|fmt=c}} today).<ref>{{cite news |title=Suit in Bridge Fall Settlement |work= [[The New York Times]] |date=May 6, 1984 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9902E0DE1138F935A35756C0A962948260 |accessdate=February 1, 2007}}</ref> Several other drivers - including former major league baseball player [[Granny Hamner]] - were able to stop their vehicles before reaching the gap in the roadway.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Conlin |first1=Bill |title=A Date with Fate Hamner Once Survived Collapse of Bridge over Troubled Waters |url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1P2-32827664/a-date-with-fate-hamner-once-survived-collapse-of |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=15 September 1993}}</ref>\n\nJohn Lerro, the [[harbor pilot]] who had been steering the ship, was later cleared of wrongdoing by both a state [[grand jury]] and a [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] investigation. A [[microburst]] had suddenly hit the freighter with torrential rains and {{convert|70|mph|abbr=on}} winds as it was in the middle of a turn in the shipping channel nearing the bridge, cutting visibility to near zero and temporarily rendering the ship's radar useless.<ref>{{cite news |title=Memories Stay with Man at Command of the Ship |work= St. Petersburg Times |first= Jean |last= Heller |date= May 7, 2000 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/050700/TampaBay/Memories_stay_with_ma.shtml |accessdate=July 4, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=OLIVER |first1=MYRNA |title=John Lerro, 59; Harbor Pilot Haunted by Role in Deadly Bridge Accident |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/09/local/me-lerro9 |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=9 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Thalji |first1=Jamal |title=The Sunshine Skyway Bridge plunged into Tampa Bay 38 years ago |url=http://www.tampabay.com/photos/2018/05/09/the-sunshine-skyway-bridge-plunged-into-tampa-bay-38-years-ago/ |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Lerro put the ship's engines into full reverse and ordered the emergency dropping of the anchor as soon as he realized that the freighter was out of the channel, but the bow still hit two support piers with enough force to cause a portion of the roadway to collapse.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sussingham |first1=Robin |title=Remembering the Sunshine Skyway Bridge Collapse |url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/remembering-sunshine-skyway-bridge-collapse |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu |issue=May 8, 2015 |publisher=WUSF-FM |language=en}}</ref> The south main pier withstood the ship strike without significant damage, but a secondary pier to the south was not designed to withstand such an impact and failed catastrophically.<ref name=\"fbs\" />\n\n====Aftermath====\nAfter the ''Summit Venture'' disaster, the southbound span was used as a temporary fishing pier and the northbound span was converted back to carry one lane in either direction until the current bridge opened. Before the old bridge was demolished and hauled away in barges, MacIntire (the only survivor in the collapse) was the last person to drive over it. He was accompanied by his wife, and when they reached the top of the bridge, they dropped 35 white carnations into the water, one for each person who died in the disaster.<ref name=Wright2006>{{cite book |last= Wright |first= E. Lynne |year= 2006 |title= Disasters and Heroic Rescues of Florida |page= 111 |publisher= Morris Book Publishing | isbn = 978-0-7627-3984-4}}</ref> Both the main spans of both the intact northbound bridge and the damaged southbound bridge were demolished in 1993 and the approaches for both old spans were made into the [[Skyway Fishing Pier State Park]]. These approaches sit {{convert|1/2|mi|m}} to the south and west of the current bridge. The approaches of the 1950s span were demolished in 2008.\n\nGov. Graham's idea for the design of the current bridge won out over other proposals, including a tunnel (deemed impractical due to Florida's high [[water table]]) and a simple reconstruction of the broken section of the old bridge that would not have improved shipping conditions. The new bridge's main span is 50% wider than the old bridge. The piers of the main span and the approaches for {{convert|1/4|mi|m}} in either direction are surrounded by large concrete barriers, called \"[[dolphin (structure)|dolphins]]\", that can protect the bridge piers from collisions by ships larger than the ''Summit Venture'' like tankers, container ships, and cruise ships.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/buildingbig/wonder/structure/sunshine_skyway.html |title=Building big: Databank: Sunshine Skyway Bridge |accessdate=July 4, 2007 |publisher=PBS Online}}</ref>\n\n=== Demolition of former bridge ===\nIn 1990 FDOT awarded the winning bid to Hardaway Company to demolish all steel and concrete sections of the older Sunshine Skyway Bridge.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=July 29, 2019 |title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge |website=Controlled Demolition, Inc. |url=http://www.controlled-demolition.com/sunshine-skyway-bridge}}</ref> The scope of the project required that all underwater piles and piers, and surface roadway, girders, and beams be dismantled. Special care had to be taken in removing underwater bridge elements near the shipping channel. Additionally, the concrete material, deck sections, pilings and steel girders were to be collected in order to be placed offshore and along the remaining bridge approaches to become artificial reefs for the new planned state fishing park. The main bridge span had to be removed in one piece in order not to block the main shipping canal leading to the Port of Tampa.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 7, 2020|title=Demolition day nears for old Skyway|url=https://tampabay.com/archive/1991/09/08/demolition-day-nears-for-old-skyway/|website=Tampa Bay Times|date=September 8, 1991|last1=Meinheardt|first1=Jane}}</ref>\n\nDuring the disassembly work of the bridges\u2019 structural steel members, several difficult engineering challenges had to be resolved: the order of disassembly, a safe method for detonating charges on concrete and steel members in a publicly open and difficult to control area such as the Tampa Bay, and the development of a safe methodology for the removal in one piece of the bridge\u2019s main span and concrete piers.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nAfter extensive research, the engineering team developed a 4 \u00d7 1:16 ratio pulley system where each of the four corners of the span was connected to two 25-ton<!--which kind of ton?--> winches (bolted to the pavement of the deck). These winches controlled the descent of the main {{convert|360|ft|m|adj=on}}, 608-ton span to a barge anchored {{convert|150|ft|m}} below. As part of the project design, the engineering team developed a real-time, computerized, synchronized descent calculator and control program to help each of the two winch management teams ensure that all winches were synchronized at the same {{convert|30|ft|m}} per minute descent rate. The operation was executed successfully in {{frac|2|1|2}} hours despite adverse weather conditions.<ref name=\"Bradenton\">{{cite news | last = King | first =Robert |work= The Bradenton Herald | title = Chunk of Old Skyway Dismantled |page= 1B |date= September 25, 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Issues==\n===Suicides ===\nAccording to compilations from various media reports as of 2009, at least 207 people have committed suicide by jumping from the center span into the waters of Tampa Bay since the opening of the current bridge in 1987 and an estimated 34 others have tried but survived.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/article1021477.ece |title=Bradenton Man's Unlikely Catch Under Sunshine Skyway Bridge Is a Lifesaver |journal=St. Petersburg Times |first=Kim |last=Wilmath |date=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727085444/http://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/article1021477.ece |archive-date=July 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Another 51 people ended their lives from the old Sunshine Skyway from 1954 to 1987. Several other missing persons are suspected of having jumped from the bridge but their deaths could not be confirmed as no bodies were recovered.\n\nIn response to the high number of suicide attempts from the bridge, the state of Florida installed six crisis hotline phones along the center span in 1999, and began 24-hour patrols. {{asof|2003}}, the call center at the Crisis Center of Tampa Bay received 18 calls from potential jumpers, all of whom survived, according to a 2003 ''St. Petersburg Times'' report.<ref>{{cite news |first = Jamie |last = Jones |title=Skyway Safeguards Don't Deter Jumpers |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 6, 2003 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/10/06/Tampabay/Skyway_safeguards_don.shtml |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328103120/http://www.sptimes.com/2003/10/06/Tampabay/Skyway_safeguards_don.shtml |archivedate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a feature film ''[[Loren Cass]]'' was released, which depicted a suicide jump off the Sunshine Skyway.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Wilson |title=Movie will have its first local viewing |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 11, 2006 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/10/11/Neighborhoodtimes/Movie_will_have_its_f.shtml |accessdate = May 28, 2007}}</ref> Two years later, a second filmmaker, Sean Michael Davis of Rhino Productions, was inspired by his haunting experience witnessing a woman jump off the bridge so quickly that no one could intervene, to create a not-for-profit film titled ''Skyway Down''. His objectives: to deter other potential jumpers by \" 'punch[ing] them in the face' with interviews with survivors and family members\",<ref name=\"Katie Sanders, Times Staff Writer\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1101741.ece|title=Filmmaker haunted by Sunshine Skyway bridge suicide hopes documentary will deter others|work=The New York Times|first=Katie|last=Sanders|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=September 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106234128/http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1101741.ece|archive-date=November 6, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  to give them \"hope and to try to de-glorify the romanticism of the bridge\",<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.skywayjumper.com/| title=Skyway Down: A Permanent Solution to a Temporary Problem; A Film Project|accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref> in part by informing those who have \"mulled a leap to know about the bloody, battered aftermath.\"<ref name=\"Katie Sanders, Times Staff Writer\"/>\n\nIn January 2020, FDOT announced they will install the Skyway Vertical Net, a vertical barrier in an effort to deter suicide attempts.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 28, 2020|title=FDOT to install suicide prevention barrier on Sunshine Skyway Bridge|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/sunshine-skyway-bridge-to-get-suicide-prevention-barrier/67-e96ea0c8-576d-4fbe-9d7d-b6df29986e8b|website=[[WTSP]]|first1=Chelsea|last1=Tatham|date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> Construction for the project is expected to begin sometime in summer 2020. The vertical barrier will be placed on the outside walls of the bridge and extend vertically {{convert|8|ft}} from the side barriers. It will span each side of the bridge for about {{convert|1.5|miles}}.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 28, 2020|title=I-275 Skyway Bridge Vertical Net|url=http://www.fdottampabay.com/project/601/445399-1-52-01|website=FDOT Tampa Bay}}</ref>\n\nAs part of any Florida [[controlled-access highway]], pedestrians and bicycles are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Statutes, Section 316.130: Pedestrians; traffic regulations |publisher=Florida Legislature |year=2019 |url=http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0300-0399/0316/Sections/0316.130.html |quote=Subsection 18: No pedestrian shall walk upon a limited access facility or a ramp connecting a limited access facility to any other street or highway; however, this subsection does not apply to maintenance personnel of any governmental subdivision.}}</ref> Stopping on the bridge for any non-emergency, including sightseeing, is prohibited. Traffic on the bridge is monitored by the [[Florida Highway Patrol]], and a stopped vehicle, bicyclist, or pedestrian will elicit a police dispatch.\n\n===Corrosion===\nA major problem with the Sunshine Skyway Bridge is corrosion of the steel in the precast concrete segmental columns on the high level approaches. Because the segments are hollow, workers were able to enter the bridge superstructure in 2003 and 2004 to reinforce the corroded sections of the bridge, ensuring its future safety.<ref name=\"Garcia\">{{cite web |first= Jose |last= Garcia |title= The Skyway Bridge: Yesterday, Today & Tomorrow |publisher= Florida Department of Transportation |url= http://www.dot.state.fl.us/Structures/DesignConf2006/Presentations/session20/Final-20Garcia.pdf |access-date= March 18, 2007}}</ref> Another problem arose around 2005\u201306 when several news bureaus reported paint discolorations on the bridge's cables. These paint splotches and patches were a result of touch-ups that were performed sometime in 1998 but began to show through as a result of using newer, environmentally-safe paint. The change in the paint's composition caused it to fade faster than expected. \n\nFrom 2006 to 2008, [[Florida Department of Transportation]] (FDOT) hired a contractor to perform the first full repainting of the bridge since it opened in 1987. The work included repainting the bridge's 42 steel cables one consistent shade of yellow and rehabilitating the lighting system at the summit of the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/07/14/Tampabay/Soon__a_mellow_yellow.shtml |last1=Ave |first1=Melanie |date=July 14, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717062538/http://www.sptimes.com/2006/07/14/Tampabay/Soon__a_mellow_yellow.shtml |archive-date=July 17, 2006 |title=Soon, a mellow yellow |website=St. Petersburg Times |accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Low clearance===\nA 2014 FDOT study noted that the Skyway's low bridge clearance prevented larger vessels from using the [[Port Tampa Bay]] terminals, but made no recommendation about options as the [[air draft]] of most new cruise ships exceeds the bridge's height limit at {{convert|180|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Sara |url=http://www.bradenton.com/news/business/port-manatee/article34721970.html |title=Study offers options for Cruise Ships too tall for the Sunshine Skyway Bridge |date=July 8, 2014 |website=bradenton.com |publisher=Bradenton Herald |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic==\n===Usage and tourism===\nThe former and current bridge have been featured in various forms of media. The original Sunshine Skyway Bridge is featured in ''[[Yours Truly, Johnny Dollar]]'' and the opening credits to ''[[Superboy (TV series)|Superboy]]''. The current bridge has provided the setting for several films such as ''Loren Cass'' and ''[[The Punisher (2004 film)#Plot|The Punisher]]''. The bridge also served as plot devices to various novels such as [[Dennis Lehane]]'s 1997 novel ''[[Sacred (novel)|Sacred]]''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lehane|first1=Dennis|title=Sacred|date=2013|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=9780062224040|page=233|edition=First William Morrow Paperback}}</ref> and [[Ben Bova]]'s 2005 novel ''Powersat''.<ref>Powersat by Ben Bova, 2005: pp 56-58.  TOR Books - New York http://us.macmillan.com/books/9780765348173</ref> The bridge is also the subject of the song \"Skyway Avenue\" by [[We the Kings]].<ref>{{Citation|title=We the Kings by We the Kings|date=2007-10-02|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/we-the-kings/1221488168|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Postal Service]] featured the bridge in 2012 on a Priority Mail postage stamp. Carl T. Hermann worked on the painting and the digital illustration was created by artist Dan Cosgrove.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20111230/ARTICLE/111239973|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge to be on postage stamp|date=December 30, 2011|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=February 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, an act of the Florida Legislature officially named the current bridge the [[Bob Graham]] Sunshine Skyway Bridge, after the former [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]] and then [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] who presided over its design and most of its construction. According to sources{{which|date=February 2019}}, he was inspired to suggest the current design by a visit to France, where he saw a similar cable-stayed bridge, the [[Pont de Brotonne|Brotonne Bridge]]. The original bridge was dedicated to state engineer William E. Dean, as noted on a plaque displayed at the rest area at the south end of the bridge.\n\nIn November 2017, work began on installing decorative lighting to the Skyway's columns, main spans, and sloped spans.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Florida Department of Transportation |url=http://www.fdottampabay.com/factsheet/218 |title=I-275 (Sunshine Skyway Bridge) Lighting Factsheet |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> The $15.6 million lighting project provides a visual aesthetic while also enhancing safety and security by providing more light to the underside of the bridge from dusk to dawn. Over 1,800 [[Light-emitting diode|LED]]s were installed along {{convert|1.7|miles}} of the bridge which cycles through animated routines. The lighting project was completed in October 2019 and funded by FDOT through collected toll fees.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Thomas |last1=Becnel |accessdate=December 13, 2019 |title=Sunshine Skyway will get colorful lighting display in October |url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20190817/sunshine-skyway-will-get-colorful-lighting-display-in-october |website=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Skyway 10K===\nOn January 11, 1987, the Skyway Bridge opened-up to 10,000 runners, joggers and walkers before the bridge was opened to motor vehicle traffic the following week. Runners participated in four races that ran simultaneously across the bridge, with two races going southbound and two races directed northbound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/321432337/|title=Tampa Bay Times from St. Petersburg, Florida on January 1, 1987 \u00b7 100|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2018, in partnership with the Armed Forces Families Foundation, the Skyway Bridge was closed for the Inaugural Skyway 10K.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skyway10k.com/|title=Skyway 10K|website=SKYWAY 10K|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> In contrast to the one-time race in 1987, the Skyway 10K has been held annually since 2018.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n=== Old bridge demolition ===\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"187px\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge 3.JPG|Before demolition\nFile:Skyway Bridge 3.jpg|Demolition of steel and concrete girders. Truncated pier visible was the one struck by ''Summit Venture''\nFile:Skyway Bridge 4.jpg|Main bridge span secure on barge being towed away\nFile:Steel Blast 2.jpg|Blasting steel truss\nFile:Blasting Concrete.jpg|Blasting concrete piers\n</gallery>\n\n=== Current bridge ===\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"225px\" heights=\"225px\">\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge.jpg|The bridge at twilight\nFile:SunshineSkyway_FortDeSoto.jpg|View of bridge from Fort De Soto Park's East Beach\nFile:SunshineSkyway4.jpg|Driving on the bridge, near the peak\nFile:SunshineSkyway_ALB.jpg|View of bridge heading south\nFile:Sunshine Skyway from Tampa Bay.jpeg|As seen from the water of Tampa Bay\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge - Looking Up.JPG|View looking up while driving across Sunshine Skyway Bridge\nFile:MV Summit Venture Mayday Call.flac|MV Summit Venture Mayday Call of the collision incident\nFile:2019SunshineSkywayBridge.jpg|The bridge in 2019.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Transport}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Engineering}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Florida}}\n* [[Millau Viaduct]], bridge with similar design in France\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20003386|title=Original Sunshine Skyway Bridge}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20000263|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hNgxOwv88vk Sunshine Skyway Bridge 1986]\n*