n| caption             = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|27.625|-82.65833|display=inline}}\n| carries             = 4 lanes of {{Jct|state=FL|I|275|US|19}}\n| crosses             = [[Tampa Bay]]\n| locale              = South of [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] and north of [[Terra Ceia, Florida]]\n| official_name       = Bob Graham Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| other_name          = The Skyway\n| named_for           = [[Bob Graham]]\n| owner               = \n| maint               = [[Florida Department of Transportation]]\n| heritage            = \n| id                  = 150189\n| website             = \n| design              = [[Cable-stayed bridge|Cable-stayed]]\n| material            = \n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|4.14|mi|km|1}}\n| width               = {{convert|94|ft|m|0}}\n| height              = {{convert|430|ft|m|0}}<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20140816/ARTICLE/140819777 |title= If Skyway Run Gets Approval, Appeal Could Be Widespread |last= Bergen |first= Katy |date= August 16, 2014 |work= [[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |access-date= May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = {{convert|1200|ft|m|0}}\n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = <!-- clearance above is unlimited as none of the tower structure goes over the roadway on the 1987 cable-stayed bridge -->\n| clearance_below     = {{convert|180.5|ft|m|0}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tampabaypilots.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Sunshine-Skyway-Bridge-Vertical-Clearance.pdf |title= Port Community Information Bulletin # 04-11: Sunshine Skyway Vertical Clearance |last= Dickinson |first= S.L. |date= March 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418052116/http://tampabaypilots.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Sunshine-Skyway-Bridge-Vertical-Clearance.pdf |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |access-date=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n| lanes               = 4\n| life                = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = \n| engineering         = Figg & Muller Engineering Group\n| builder             = [[American Bridge Company]]\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = June 1982<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://greenbenchmonthly.com/st-petersburg-history/history-of-the-sunshine-skyway/|title=History Of the Sunshine Skyway|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109071424/https://greenbenchmonthly.com/st-petersburg-history/history-of-the-sunshine-skyway/|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaroads.com/florida/sunshine-skyway/|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge - AA Roads|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109072417/https://www.aaroads.com/florida/sunshine-skyway/|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref><!--For simplicity, this infobox will be for the 1987 current bridge. -->\n| complete            = \n| cost                = $244 million\n| open                = {{start date and age|1987|04|20}}\n| inaugurated         = \n| rebuilt             = \n| collapsed           = <!--For current bridge-->\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = 59,178 (2018)<ref name=\"FDOT\">{{cite web|title=Florida Bridge Information \u2013 2019 1st Quarter|url=https://fdotwww.blob.core.windows.net/sitefinity/docs/default-source/maintenance/str/bi/florida-bridge-information-jan-2019.pdf?sfvrsn=dd1492ae_4|website=[[Florida Department of Transportation]]|date=January 2, 2019|access-date=February 14, 2019|page=216|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| toll                = $1.50 for passenger cars or $1.07 with [[SunPass]]\n| map_type            = USA Florida\n| map_relief          = yes\n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = \n| map_size            = 284\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name        = (Former) Sunshine Skyway Bridge<!--This infobox is for the bridge preceding the 1980 collapse with the same name-->\n| image       = Sunshine_Skyway_Bridge_3.JPG\n| image_upright = 1.3\n| carries     = 4 lanes of {{Jct|state=FL|US|19}} (as two separate 2-lane bridges for each direction) <!--I-275 did not exist in this region until around 1982 --> \n| crosses     = [[Tampa Bay]]\n| locale      = South of [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] and north of [[Terra Ceia, Florida]]\n| design      = [[Cantilever bridge]]\n| material    = Steel\n| material1   = Steel\n| material2   = Reinforced concrete\n| length      = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| width       = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| height      = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| mainspan    = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| below       = <!--{{Convert||m|ft|0|abbr=on}}-->\n| begin       = 1950 (original bridge, later converted to northbound only traffic)<br/>1967 (southbound span)\n| inaugurated = {{Start date|1954|09|06}}\n| complete    = 1954 (northbound span)<br/> 1971 (southbound span)\n| replaces    = Bee Line Ferry\n| replaced_by = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| open        = {{Start date and age|1954|09|06}} (original bridge)\n| collapsed   = {{end date and age|1980|05|09}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Bob Graham Sunshine Skyway Bridge''', often referred to as the '''Sunshine Skyway Bridge''' or simply '''the Skyway,''' is a [[cable-stayed bridge|cable-stayed]] bridge spanning the [[Tampa Bay|Lower Tampa Bay]] connecting [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], [[Florida]] to [[Terra Ceia, Florida|Terra Ceia]]. The current Sunshine Skyway opened in 1987 and is the second bridge of that name on the site. It was designed by the Figg & Muller Engineering Group and built by the [[American Bridge Company]] and is considered a symbol of Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Greatest American Bridges (& What We Can Learn from Them)|url=https://bridgemastersinc.com/greatest-american-bridges/|date=September 30, 2016|website=Bridge Masters|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe four-lane bridge carries [[Interstate 275 (Florida)|Interstate 275]] and [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|U.S. Route 19]], passing through [[Pinellas County, Florida|Pinellas County]], [[Hillsborough County, Florida|Hillsborough County]], and [[Manatee County, Florida|Manatee County]]. It is a [[toll road]], with a $1.50 toll assessed on two-axle vehicles traveling in either direction and collected via cash or the state's [[SunPass]] system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Henson |first1=Chuck |title=SunPass confusion clogs Sunshine Skyway tolls |url=https://www.baynews9.com/fl/tampa/traffic/2018/04/30/sunpass-sunshine-skyway-bridge |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |work=www.baynews9.com |publisher=Spectrum News / Bay News 9 |date=April 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe original bridge opened in 1954 and was the site of two major maritime disasters within a few months in 1980. In January 1980, the [[United States Coast Guard]] Cutter {{USCGC|Blackthorn|WLB-391|2}} collided with the tanker ''Capricorn'' near the bridge, resulting in the sinking of the cutter and the loss of 23 crew members. In May 1980, the freighter ''[[MV Summit Venture]]'' collided with a bridge support during a sudden [[squall]], resulting in the structural collapse of the southbound span and the deaths of 35 people when vehicles plunged into Tampa Bay.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nunez |first1=Judy Kay |title=28 January 1980, Blackthorn and Capricorn: Collision with History in Tampa Bay |url=http://diginole.lib.fsu.edu/islandora/object/fsu:180688/datastream/PDF/view |publisher=Florida State University Libraries |accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref> Within a few years, the damaged span was demolished, the surviving span was partially demolished and converted into a long [[fishing pier]], and the current bridge was built.\n\n==History==\n===Original bridge===\nThe original two-lane bridge was built by the Virginia Bridge Company and opened to traffic on September 6, 1954,<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Zt4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72 |title= Tampa Bay Crossing Spans 14 Miles of Tidewater |magazine= [[Popular Mechanics]] |date= August 1954 |pages= 72\u201373 |via= [[Google Books]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=September 7, 1954 |title=Thousands cross Sunshine Skyway Span |page=1 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S5kcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1GQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4161%2C1128738 |via= [[Google Books]]}}</ref> with a similar structure built parallel and to the west of it in 1969 to make it a four-lane bridge and bring it to [[Interstate Highway standards]]. Opening of the newer span was delayed until 1971 for reinforcing of the south main pier, which had cracked due to insufficient [[Deep foundation|supporting pile]] depth.<ref name=\"fbs\">http://interstate275florida.blogspot.com/2009/07/old-sunshine-skyway-bridge.html{{sps|certain=y|date=May 2016}}</ref> The second span was used for all southbound traffic, while the original span was converted to carry northbound traffic.\n\nThe old bridge replaced a [[ferry]] from [[Pinellas County, Florida|Point Pinellas]] to [[Pinellas County, Florida#Spanish and British Florida|Piney Point]]. [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|US&nbsp;19]] was extended from [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]] to its current end north.\n\n=== 1980 collapse ===\n\n[[File:Skywayaccident.jpg|thumb|220px|right|The collapsed original bridge on May 9, 1980, after the ''Summit Venture'' collision. Photo by ''[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]'']]\n[[File:Skyway Bridge 1.jpg|thumb|220px|right|The current bridge (top) and the old bridges. The piers of the current bridge are protected by [[Dolphin (structure)|structural dolphins]]. The collapsed bridge is under demolition.]]\nThe southbound span (opened in 1971) of the original bridge was destroyed at 7:33&nbsp;a.m. on May 9, 1980, when the freighter [[MV Summit Venture|MV ''Summit Venture'']] collided with a pier (support column) during a sudden [[squall]], sending over {{convert|1200|ft|m}} of the bridge plummeting into Tampa Bay. The collision caused six cars, a truck, and a [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] bus to fall {{convert|150|ft|m}} into the water, killing 35 people.<ref>{{cite news |title= A Blinding Squall, then Death |work= St. Petersburg Times |url= http://www2.sptimes.com/Weather/SW.2.html |access-date= February 1, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Day Skyway Fell: May 9, 1980 |work= St. Petersburg Times |first= Jean |last= Heller |date=May 7, 2000 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/050700/TampaBay/Horrific_accident_cre.shtml |accessdate=July 4, 2007}}</ref> One man, Wesley MacIntire, survived when his [[Ford Courier]] pickup truck landed on the deck of the ''Summit Venture'' before falling into the bay. He sued the company that owned the ship, and settled in 1984 for $175,000 (${{Inflation|US|175000|1984|r=-3|fmt=c}} today).<ref>{{cite news |title=Suit in Bridge Fall Settlement |work= [[The New York Times]] |date=May 6, 1984 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9902E0DE1138F935A35756C0A962948260 |accessdate=February 1, 2007}}</ref> Several other drivers - including former major league baseball player [[Granny Hamner]] - were able to stop their vehicles before reaching the gap in the roadway.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Conlin |first1=Bill |title=A Date with Fate Hamner Once Survived Collapse of Bridge over Troubled Waters |url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1P2-32827664/a-date-with-fate-hamner-once-survived-collapse-of |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=15 September 1993}}</ref>\n\nJohn Lerro, the [[harbor pilot]] who had been steering the ship, was later cleared of wrongdoing by both a state [[grand jury]] and a [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] investigation. A [[microburst]] had suddenly hit the freighter with torrential rains and 70 mile per hour winds as it was in the middle of a turn in the shipping channel nearing the bridge, cutting visibility to near zero and temporarily rendering the ship's radar useless.<ref>{{cite news |title=Memories Stay with Man at Command of the Ship |work= St. Petersburg Times |first= Jean |last= Heller |date= May 7, 2000 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/050700/TampaBay/Memories_stay_with_ma.shtml |accessdate=July 4, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=OLIVER |first1=MYRNA |title=John Lerro, 59; Harbor Pilot Haunted by Role in Deadly Bridge Accident |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/09/local/me-lerro9 |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=9 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Thalji |first1=Jamal |title=The Sunshine Skyway Bridge plunged into Tampa Bay 38 years ago |url=http://www.tampabay.com/photos/2018/05/09/the-sunshine-skyway-bridge-plunged-into-tampa-bay-38-years-ago/ |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Tampa Bay Times |date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Lerro put the ship's engines into full reverse and ordered the emergency dropping of the anchor as soon as he realized that the freighter was out of the channel, but the bow still hit two support piers with enough force to cause a portion of the roadway to collapse.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sussingham |first1=Robin |title=Remembering the Sunshine Skyway Bridge Collapse |url=http://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/post/remembering-sunshine-skyway-bridge-collapse |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu |issue=May 8, 2015 |publisher=WUSF-FM |language=en}}</ref> The south main pier withstood the ship strike without significant damage, but a secondary pier to the south was not designed to withstand such an impact and failed catastrophically.<ref name=\"fbs\" />\n\n====Aftermath====\nAfter the ''Summit Venture'' disaster, the southbound span was used as a temporary fishing pier and the northbound span was converted back to carry one lane in either direction until the current bridge opened. Before the old bridge was demolished and hauled away in barges, MacIntire (the only survivor in the collapse) was the last person to drive over it. He was accompanied by his wife, and when they reached the top of the bridge, they dropped 35 white carnations into the water, one for each person who died in the disaster.<ref name=Wright2006>{{cite book |last= Wright |first= E. Lynne |year= 2006 |title= Disasters and Heroic Rescues of Florida |page= 111 |publisher= Morris Book Publishing | isbn = 978-0-7627-3984-4}}</ref> Both the main spans of both the intact northbound bridge and the damaged southbound bridge were demolished in 1993 and the approaches for both old spans were made into the [[Skyway Fishing Pier State Park]]. These approaches sit {{convert|1/2|mi|m}} to the south and west of the current bridge. The approaches of the 1950s span were demolished in 2008.\n\nGov. Graham's idea for the design of the current bridge won out over other proposals, including a tunnel (deemed impractical due to Florida's high [[water table]]) and a simple reconstruction of the broken section of the old bridge that would not have improved shipping conditions. The new bridge's main span is 50% wider than the old bridge. The piers of the main span and the approaches for {{convert|1/4|mi|m}} in either direction are surrounded by large concrete barriers, called \"[[dolphin (structure)|dolphins]]\", that can protect the bridge piers from collisions by ships larger than the ''Summit Venture'' like tankers, container ships, and cruise ships.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/buildingbig/wonder/structure/sunshine_skyway.html |title=Building big: Databank: Sunshine Skyway Bridge |accessdate=July 4, 2007 |publisher=PBS Online}}</ref>\n\n=== Demolition of former bridge ===\nIn 1990 FDOT awarded the winning bid to Hardaway Company to demolish all steel and concrete sections of the older Sunshine Skyway Bridge.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=July 29, 2019 |title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge |website=Controlled Demolition, Inc. |url=http://www.controlled-demolition.com/sunshine-skyway-bridge}}</ref> The scope of the project required that all underwater piles and piers, and surface roadway, girders, and beams be dismantled. Special care had to be taken in removing underwater bridge elements near the shipping channel. Additionally, the concrete material, deck sections, pilings and steel girders were to be collected in order to be placed offshore and along the remaining bridge approaches to become artificial reefs for the new planned state fishing park. The main bridge span had to be removed in one piece in order not to block the main shipping canal leading to the Port of Tampa.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 7, 2020|title=Demolition day nears for old Skyway|url=https://tampabay.com/archive/1991/09/08/demolition-day-nears-for-old-skyway/|website=Tampa Bay Times|date=September 8, 1991|last1=Meinheardt|first1=Jane}}</ref>\n\nDuring the disassembly work of the bridges\u2019 structural steel members, several difficult engineering challenges had to be resolved: the order of disassembly, a safe method for detonating charges on concrete and steel members in a publicly open and difficult to control area such as the Tampa Bay, and the development of a safe methodology for the removal in one piece of the bridge\u2019s main span and concrete piers.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nAfter extensive research, the engineering team developed a 4 \u00d7 1:16 ratio pulley system where each of the four corners of the span was connected to two 25-ton<!--which kind of ton?--> winches (bolted to the pavement of the deck). These winches controlled the descent of the main {{convert|360|ft|m|adj=on}}, 608-ton span to a barge anchored {{convert|150|ft|m}} below. As part of the project design, the engineering team developed a real-time, computerized, synchronized descent calculator and control program to help each of the two winch management teams ensure that all winches were synchronized at the same {{convert|30|ft|m}} per minute descent rate. The operation was executed successfully in {{frac|2|1|2}} hours despite adverse weather conditions.<ref name=\"Bradenton\">{{cite news | last = King | first =Robert |work= The Bradenton Herald | title = Chunk of Old Skyway Dismantled |page= 1B |date= September 25, 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Issues==\n===Suicides ===\nAccording to compilations from various media reports as of 2009, at least 207 people have committed suicide by jumping from the center span into the waters of Tampa Bay since the opening of the current bridge in 1987 and an estimated 34 others have tried but survived.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/article1021477.ece |title=Bradenton Man's Unlikely Catch Under Sunshine Skyway Bridge Is a Lifesaver |journal=St. Petersburg Times |first=Kim |last=Wilmath |date=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727085444/http://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/article1021477.ece |archive-date=July 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Another 51 people ended their lives from the old Sunshine Skyway from 1954 to 1987. Several other missing persons are suspected of having jumped from the bridge but their deaths could not be confirmed as no bodies were recovered.\n\nIn response to the high number of suicide attempts from the bridge, the state of Florida installed six crisis hotline phones along the center span in 1999, and began 24-hour patrols. {{asof|2003}}, the call center at the Crisis Center of Tampa Bay received 18 calls from potential jumpers, all of whom survived, according to a 2003 ''St. Petersburg Times'' report.<ref>{{cite news |first = Jamie |last = Jones |title=Skyway Safeguards Don't Deter Jumpers |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 6, 2003 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/10/06/Tampabay/Skyway_safeguards_don.shtml |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328103120/http://www.sptimes.com/2003/10/06/Tampabay/Skyway_safeguards_don.shtml |archivedate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a feature film ''[[Loren Cass]]'' was released, which depicted a suicide jump off the Sunshine Skyway.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Wilson |title=Movie will have its first local viewing |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 11, 2006 |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/10/11/Neighborhoodtimes/Movie_will_have_its_f.shtml |accessdate = May 28, 2007}}</ref> Two years later, a second filmmaker, Sean Michael Davis of Rhino Productions, was inspired by his haunting experience witnessing a woman jump off the bridge so quickly that no one could intervene, to create a not-for-profit film titled ''Skyway Down''. His objectives: to deter other potential jumpers by \" 'punch[ing] them in the face' with interviews with survivors and family members\",<ref name=\"Katie Sanders, Times Staff Writer\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1101741.ece|title=Filmmaker haunted by Sunshine Skyway bridge suicide hopes documentary will deter others|work=The New York Times|first=Katie|last=Sanders|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=September 21, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106234128/http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/article1101741.ece|archive-date=November 6, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  to give them \"hope and to try to de-glorify the romanticism of the bridge\",<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.skywayjumper.com/| title=Skyway Down: A Permanent Solution to a Temporary Problem; A Film Project|accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref> in part by informing those who have \"mulled a leap to know about the bloody, battered aftermath.\"<ref name=\"Katie Sanders, Times Staff Writer\"/>\n\nIn January 2020, FDOT announced they will install the Skyway Vertical Net, a vertical barrier in an effort to deter suicide attempts.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 28, 2020|title=FDOT to install suicide prevention barrier on Sunshine Skyway Bridge|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/sunshine-skyway-bridge-to-get-suicide-prevention-barrier/67-e96ea0c8-576d-4fbe-9d7d-b6df29986e8b|website=[[WTSP]]|first1=Chelsea|last1=Tatham|date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> Construction for the project is expected to begin sometime in summer 2020. The vertical barrier will be placed on the outside walls of the bridge and extend vertically {{convert|8|ft}} from the side barriers. It will span each side of the bridge for about {{convert|1.5|miles}}.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 28, 2020|title=I-275 Skyway Bridge Vertical Net|url=http://www.fdottampabay.com/project/601/445399-1-52-01|website=FDOT Tampa Bay}}</ref>\n\nAs part of any Florida [[controlled-access highway]], pedestrians and bicycles are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Statutes, Section 316.130: Pedestrians; traffic regulations |publisher=Florida Legislature |year=2019 |url=http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0300-0399/0316/Sections/0316.130.html |quote=Subsection 18: No pedestrian shall walk upon a limited access facility or a ramp connecting a limited access facility to any other street or highway; however, this subsection does not apply to maintenance personnel of any governmental subdivision.}}</ref> Stopping on the bridge for any non-emergency, including sightseeing, is prohibited. Traffic on the bridge is monitored by the [[Florida Highway Patrol]], and a stopped vehicle, bicyclist, or pedestrian will elicit a police dispatch.\n\n===Corrosion===\nA major problem with the Sunshine Skyway Bridge is corrosion of the steel in the precast concrete segmental columns on the high level approaches. Because the segments are hollow, workers were able to enter the bridge superstructure in 2003 and 2004 to reinforce the corroded sections of the bridge, ensuring its future safety.<ref name=\"Garcia\">{{cite web |first= Jose |last= Garcia |title= The Skyway Bridge: Yesterday, Today & Tomorrow |publisher= Florida Department of Transportation |url= http://www.dot.state.fl.us/Structures/DesignConf2006/Presentations/session20/Final-20Garcia.pdf |access-date= March 18, 2007}}</ref> Another problem arose around 2005\u201306 when several news bureaus reported paint discolorations on the bridge's cables. These paint splotches and patches were a result of touch-ups that were performed sometime in 1998 but began to show through as a result of using newer, environmentally-safe paint. The change in the paint's composition caused it to fade faster than expected. \n\nFrom 2006 to 2008, [[Florida Department of Transportation]] (FDOT) hired a contractor to perform the first full repainting of the bridge since it opened in 1987. The work included repainting the bridge's 42 steel cables one consistent shade of yellow and rehabilitating the lighting system at the summit of the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/07/14/Tampabay/Soon__a_mellow_yellow.shtml |last1=Ave |first1=Melanie |date=July 14, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717062538/http://www.sptimes.com/2006/07/14/Tampabay/Soon__a_mellow_yellow.shtml |archive-date=July 17, 2006 |title=Soon, a mellow yellow |website=St. Petersburg Times |accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Low clearance===\nA 2014 FDOT study noted that the Skyway's low bridge clearance prevented larger vessels from using the [[Port Tampa Bay]] terminals, but made no recommendation about options as the [[air draft]] of most new cruise ships exceeds the bridge's height limit at {{convert|180|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Sara |url=http://www.bradenton.com/news/business/port-manatee/article34721970.html |title=Study offers options for Cruise Ships too tall for the Sunshine Skyway Bridge |date=July 8, 2014 |website=bradenton.com |publisher=Bradenton Herald |accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic==\n===Usage and tourism===\nThe former and current bridge have been featured in various forms of media. The original Sunshine Skyway Bridge is featured in ''[[Yours Truly, Johnny Dollar]]'' and the opening credits to ''[[Superboy (TV series)|Superboy]]''. The current bridge has provided the setting for several films such as ''Loren Cass'' and ''[[The Punisher (2004 film)#Plot|The Punisher]]''. The bridge also served as plot devices to various novels such as [[Dennis Lehane]]'s 1997 novel ''[[Sacred (novel)|Sacred]]''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lehane|first1=Dennis|title=Sacred|date=2013|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=9780062224040|page=233|edition=First William Morrow Paperback}}</ref> and [[Ben Bova]]'s 2005 novel ''Powersat''.<ref>Powersat by Ben Bova, 2005: pp 56-58.  TOR Books - New York http://us.macmillan.com/books/9780765348173</ref> The bridge is also the subject of the song \"Skyway Avenue\" by [[We the Kings]].<ref>{{Citation|title=We the Kings by We the Kings|date=2007-10-02|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/we-the-kings/1221488168|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Postal Service]] featured the bridge in 2012 on a Priority Mail postage stamp. Carl T. Hermann worked on the painting and the digital illustration was created by artist Dan Cosgrove.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20111230/ARTICLE/111239973|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge to be on postage stamp|date=December 30, 2011|work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|accessdate=February 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, an act of the Florida Legislature officially named the current bridge the [[Bob Graham]] Sunshine Skyway Bridge, after the former [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]] and then [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] who presided over its design and most of its construction. According to sources{{which|date=February 2019}}, he was inspired to suggest the current design by a visit to France, where he saw a similar cable-stayed bridge, the [[Pont de Brotonne|Brotonne Bridge]]. The original bridge was dedicated to state engineer William E. Dean, as noted on a plaque displayed at the rest area at the south end of the bridge.\n\nIn November 2017, work began on installing decorative lighting to the Skyway's columns, main spans, and sloped spans.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Florida Department of Transportation |url=http://www.fdottampabay.com/factsheet/218 |title=I-275 (Sunshine Skyway Bridge) Lighting Factsheet |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> The $15.6 million lighting project provides a visual aesthetic while also enhancing safety and security by providing more light to the underside of the bridge from dusk to dawn. Over 1,800 [[Light-emitting diode|LED]]s were installed along {{convert|1.7|miles}} of the bridge which cycles through animated routines. The lighting project was completed in October 2019 and funded by FDOT through collected toll fees.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Thomas |last1=Becnel |accessdate=December 13, 2019 |title=Sunshine Skyway will get colorful lighting display in October |url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20190817/sunshine-skyway-will-get-colorful-lighting-display-in-october |website=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Skyway 10K===\nOn January 11, 1987, the Skyway Bridge opened-up to 10,000 runners, joggers and walkers before the bridge was opened to motor vehicle traffic the following week. Runners participated in four races that ran simultaneously across the bridge, with two races going southbound and two races directed northbound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/321432337/|title=Tampa Bay Times from St. Petersburg, Florida on January 1, 1987 \u00b7 100|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2018, in partnership with the Armed Forces Families Foundation, the Skyway Bridge was closed for the Inaugural Skyway 10K.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skyway10k.com/|title=Skyway 10K|website=SKYWAY 10K|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref> In contrast to the one-time race in 1987, the Skyway 10K has been held annually since 2018.\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n=== Old bridge demolition ===\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"187px\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge 3.JPG|Before demolition\nFile:Skyway Bridge 3.jpg|Demolition of steel and concrete girders. Truncated pier visible was the one struck by ''Summit Venture''\nFile:Skyway Bridge 4.jpg|Main bridge span secure on barge being towed away\nFile:Steel Blast 2.jpg|Blasting steel truss\nFile:Blasting Concrete.jpg|Blasting concrete piers\n</gallery>\n\n=== Current bridge ===\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"225px\" heights=\"225px\">\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge.jpg|The bridge at twilight\nFile:SunshineSkyway_FortDeSoto.jpg|View of bridge from Fort De Soto Park's East Beach\nFile:SunshineSkyway4.jpg|Driving on the bridge, near the peak\nFile:SunshineSkyway_ALB.jpg|View of bridge heading south\nFile:Sunshine Skyway from Tampa Bay.jpeg|As seen from the water of Tampa Bay\nFile:Sunshine Skyway Bridge - Looking Up.JPG|View looking up while driving across Sunshine Skyway Bridge\nFile:MV Summit Venture Mayday Call.flac|MV Summit Venture Mayday Call of the collision incident\nFile:2019SunshineSkywayBridge.jpg|The bridge in 2019.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Transport}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Engineering}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Florida}}\n* [[Millau Viaduct]], bridge with similar design in France\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20003386|title=Original Sunshine Skyway Bridge}}\n* {{Structurae|id=20000263|title=Sunshine Skyway Bridge}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hNgxOwv88vk Sunshine Skyway Bridge 1986]\n* [http://www.interstate275florida.com/ssb.html Sunshine Skyway Bridge page at Interstate 275 Florida]\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n| structure = Crossings\n| place = [[Tampa Bay]]\n| bridge = Sunshine Skyway Bridge\n| bridge signs = [[File:I-275.svg|25px]] [[File:US 19.svg|20px]]\n| upstream = [[Gandy Bridge]]\n| upstream signs = [[File:US 92.svg|20px]]\n| downstream = [[Gulf of Mexico]]\n| downstream signs =\n}}\n\n{{Bridges of Florida}}\n{{Fla Tpk}}\n\n<!--Spacing these categories out to show groupings.-->\n\n[[Category:Bridge disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters caused by collision]]\n[[Category:Transportation disasters in Florida]]\n[[Category:Cable-stayed bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1954]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1971]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Florida]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Pinellas County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Hillsborough County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures in Manatee County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Bridges over Tampa Bay]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Interstate 75]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 19]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the United States Numbered Highways]]\n", "name_user": "The Grid", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1980 collapse:Convert tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunshine_Skyway_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Via Giulia", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name = Via Giulia\n| image = 948RomaViaGiulia.JPG\n| image_size = 230px\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Arco Farnese across Via Giulia\n| map_type = \n| map_size =\n| location= Rome\n| quarter = [[Regola]], [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]]\n| coordinates =\n| terminus_a = Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti\n| terminus_b = Piazza dell'Oro\n| length = {{convert|950|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| completion_date = 1512\n| designer = [[Donato Bramante]]\n| inauguration_label = Denomination\n| inauguration_date = \n}}\n'''Via Giulia''' is a street in [[Rome]], Italy, that is of historical and architectural importance. The road was one of the first important urban planning projects in papal Rome and became one of the main centers of the [[Roman Renaissance|Renaissance]]. Up until the 1850s it was one of the favorite streets of the Roman nobility and it was enriched with feasts and games. After a two-century decline, from the 1950s onwards the road's fame was renewed to be one of the city's most prestigious locations.\n\n==Location==\nVia Giulia runs along the left (east) bank of the [[Tiber]] from ''Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti'', near [[Ponte Sisto]], to ''Piazza dell'Oro''. It is about 1 kilometre long and connects the [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]] [[rioni of Rome|Rioni]].\n\n==Denominations==\nThe road was named after its patron, [[Pope Julius II]] [[della Rovere]] (r. 1503-1513), who ordered its construction in 1508.<ref name=bramanteDbi/><ref name=del472>Delli (1988), p. 472</ref> It had been also called {{Lang|la|Via Magistralis}} (lit. \"master road\") because of its importance,<ref name=del472/> and {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\") because of its layout.<ref name=del473/>\n\n==History==\nThe area of the ancient {{Lang|la|[[Campus Martius]]}} developed into one of the most densely populated districts (''abitato'') of Rome since the early [[Middle Ages]]. The maze of narrow alleys was criss-crossed by three narrow thoroughfares: the {{Lang|la|Via Papalis}} (lit. \"papal road\"),<ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' - ''via del Governo Vecchio'' - ''piazza di Pasquino'' - ''piazza di S.Pantaleo''  - ''piazza d'Aracoeli'' - ''Campidoglio'' - ''Stradone di S.Giovanni''</ref> the {{Lang|la|Via Peregrinorum}} (lit. \"pilgrims' road\") <ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Vecchi'' - ''Via del Pellegrino'' - ''via dei Giubbonari''</ref> and the {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\").<ref>Today's ''[[via dei Coronari]]''</ref><ref name=tem57>Temple(2011), p. 57</ref> [[Procession]]s travelled through these streets almost daily during the [[Middle Ages]] to the [[Ponte Sant'Angelo|Angels' Bridge]]. As [[Dante Alighieri]] described in the [[Divine Comedy]], in 1300, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] (r. 1294-1303) ordered a two-way traffic system to be set up to avoid traffic jams or panic as a response to the dense crowds on Angels' Bridge.<ref>Dante Aligheri: Inferno, canto XVIII, vv. 28\u20133\u20133</ref> After [[Pope Martin V]] (r. 1417-1431) [[Western_Schism#Resolution|returned]] to Rome in 1420, the influx of pilgrims increased significantly again, especially in the [[Jubilee]] years. On 29 December 1450, the last day of the Holy Year, a [[stampede]] broke out on the bridge that killed more than 300 people.<ref name=gi9038>Gigli (1990) p. 38</ref><ref name=gi9040>Gigli (1990) p. 40</ref>\nAs a result of the catastrophe, [[Pope Nicholas V]] (r. 1447-1455) ordered the Angels' Bridge to be cleared of stalls and shops and the first urban planning measures in the area were initiated. In 1475, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484) ordered the [[Ponte Sisto]], named after him, to be built across the [[Tiber]] [[:File:Ponte Sisto Bauinschrift 1475.jpg|(inscription)]] in order to relieve the pilgrimage route across the Angels' Bridge and to connect the ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Trastevere]].<ref name=pie7982>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 82</ref> At the same time he ordered the restoration of ''Via Pelegrinorum'' and the area around the ''[[Campo de' Fiori]]'' [[:File:Via Florea Stadterneuerung.jpg|(inscription)]]. According to the chronicler [[Stefano Infessura]], however, strategic reasons aside from reducing traffic were also important for these projects.<ref>Stefano Infessura: ''Diario Rerum Romanorum''; Roma 1890 p. 79 f.: February 1475</ref> In 1497 [[Pope Alexander VI]] (r. 1492-1503) ordered the widening of ''Via Peregrinorum'' <ref>Inscription at the entrance to the Via del Pellegrino: ALEX VI PONT MAX POST INSTAURATAM ADRIANI MOLEM ANGUSTAS VRBIS VIAS AMMPLIARI IVSSIT MCCCCLXXXXVII (''Alexander VI. Pont. Max. ordered to widen the narrow streets of the town after the restoration of the Castel Sant'Angelo'')</ref> [[:File:Via del Pellegrino Inschrift Alexander VI.jpg|(Fig.)]] and the restoration of ''[[Via della Lungara]]'' on the right bank of the [[Tiber]] from [[Ponte Sisto]] to [[Old St. Peter's Basilica|St. Peter's Basilica]].\n\n===The project of Pope Julius II===\n[[File:Inschrift Julius II. Via Curato-Banchi.jpg|thumb|Inscription by Julius II, 1512]]\nIn addition to reconstructing [[St. Peter's Basilica]], Julius II implemented multiple projects in the framework of Rome's [[urban renewal]] (''Renovatio Romae'') in the [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], [[Parione]], [[Sant'Eustachio (rione of Rome)|Sant'Eustachio]] and [[Colonna (rione of Rome)|Colonna]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|rioni]]'', a task which was started forty years before by his uncle, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484).<ref name=cast378>Castagnoli (1958), pp.378</ref> One of the most important projects was the creation of two new straight streets on the left and right banks of the Tiber: the Via Giulia on the left bank, a new grand avenue through the most densely populated quarter of Rome, from the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Florentine merchant quarter on the [[Tiber]] bend,<ref name=pie798>Pietrangeli(1979) p. 8</ref> and a straight road along the right bank of the Tiber from the [[Porta Settimiana]] in [[Trastevere]] to the [[Ospedale di Santo Spirito in Sassia|Hospital of Santo Spirito]] in the [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]], the ''Via della Lungara''.<ref name=cast38081>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380-381</ref>\nBoth roads flanked the Tiber and were closely connected to it.<ref name=\"po19\"/> The Lungara had the dual aim to relieve the pilgrimage route to Saint Peter<ref name=cast38081/> and transport goods coming from the [[Via Aurelia]] and the [[Via Portuensis|via Portuense]] roads towards the centre of the city.  The Pope intended for it to reach Piazza di [[Santa Maria in Trastevere]] and the [[Port of Ripa Grande and Papal Arsenal|port of Ripa Grande]].<ref name=\"po19\"/>\n\nThe main goal behind these plans was to superimpose a regular road network with the focus given to the Tiber by medieval Rome's disorderly buildings; together with the new [[Borgo Nuovo (Rome)|Via Alessandrina]] that Alexander VI opened in the Borgo, the ''Via dei Pettinari'' that connected the [[Trastevere]] on one side and the [[Campidoglio]] on the other, the Lungara and Via Giulia created a quadrilateral network of modern roads in the city's maze of alleys.<ref name=\"po19\"/> In the original project Via Giulia was supposed to reach the Hospital of Santo Spirito in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]] via the rebuilt ''[[Pons Neronianus]]''.<ref name=del472/><ref name=cast380>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380</ref> The center of the city shifted towards the Vatican and [[Trastevere]] and away from the [[Palazzo Senatorio]] on the [[Capitoline Hill]], which was the symbol of the Roman nobility's power;<ref name=tem124/><ref name=\"po19\"/> the plan was intended to separate the papacy from the city's powerful noble families, particularly the [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families.<ref name=tem124>Temple (2011), pp. 124</ref>\n\nThese projects had a secondary, celebrative goal to promote the [[Pontiff]] as the unifier of Italy and the renewer of Rome; in 1506, after the end of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]], the Pope overthrew the powerful [[Baglioni (family)|Baglioni]] and [[Bentivoglio family|Bentivoglio]] families and conquered [[Perugia]] and [[Bologna]],<ref name=\"po19\">Portoghesi, p. 19</ref> as testified in an inscription along the ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi''.<ref>IVLIO.II.PONT:OPT:MAX:QVOD FINIB:DITIONIS.S.R.E.PROLATIS ITALIAQ:LIBERATA VRBEM ROMAM OCCVPATE SIMILIOREM QVAM DIVISE PATEFACTIS DIMENSIS Q: VIIS PRO MAIESTATE IMPERII ORNAVIT (''Julius II p.o.m. who extended the power of the Holy Roman Church and freed Italy. The city of Rome, which resembled a conquered rather than a properly planned one, he embellished for the glory of the Empire'')</ref>\n\nAside from serving as a means of communication and representation for the Church, the road was supposed to host the city's new layman's administrative center.<ref name=\"po19\"/> [[Luitpold Frommel]] discovered a drawing by [[Donato Bramante]] in the Uffizi which showed a new huge administrative complex, the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'', facing a representative square (the ''Foro Iulio'') that opened along the new street.<ref name=\"po19\"/> This forum was thought to lie between the ''Palazzo'' and the old ''[[Chancery (medieval office)|Cancelleria]]'' (today's Palazzo Sforza-Cesarini).<ref name=tem6768/> The centre was not far from the [[Apostolic Camera]] (the Pope's treasury) in [[Palazzo della Cancelleria|Palazzo Riario]] and the new ''Palazzo della Zecca'' (lit. \"papal mint\") erected by Bramante at the edge of ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' (also named ''Canale di Ponte'').<ref name=tem6768>Temple (2011), pp. 67-68</ref> By this road lay the merchants' and bankers' houses and offices, like the [[House of Altoviti|Altoviti]], Ghinucci, [[Acciaioli family|Acciaiuoli]], [[Chigi Family|Chigi]] and [[Fugger]].<ref name=cast378/> Close economic ties with Tuscan bankers like [[Agostino Chigi]] were sought and promoted.<ref name=chigiDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/agostino-chigi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=Agostino Chigi|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Francesco|last=Dante|volume=24|year=1980|language=it}}</ref>\n\nAround 1508 Bramante was asked by the Pope to start [[expropriating]] and demolishing properties in the densely populated ''[[Campus Martius|Campo Marzio]]'' to create the new street.<ref name=bramanteDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/donato-bramante_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Donato Bramante|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Arnaldo|last=Bruschi|volume=13|year=1971|language=it}}</ref>\n\n[[Giorgio Vasari]] writes:\n{{quote|''Si risolv\u00e9 il Papa di mettere in strada Giulia, da Bramante indrizzata, tutti gli uffici e le ragioni di Roma in un luogo, per la commodit\u00e0 ch\u2019a i negoziatori averia recato nelle faccende, essendo continuamente fino allora state molto scomode.''}}\n{{quote|The Pope decided to consolidate all the offices and financial centers of Rome in one place in the Via Giulia designed by Bramante. This would have made it easier for businessmen to conduct their business, which until then had been a cumbersome process.}} <ref name=vasBra>Giorgio Vasari: Vita di Donato Bramante \u2013 1568</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1511, an agreement (known as the ''Pax Romana'') between the feuding [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families was formed, which caused the ''Via Giulia'' and the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' projects to be suspended.<ref name=tem124/> Apart from a few [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] blocks between the Via del Gonfalone and the Vicolo del Cefalo, nothing remained of the palace.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===Via Giulia in the 16th and 17th century===\n[[File:G.Vasi - Collegio Ecclesiastico a Ponte Sisto.jpg|thumb|Fontana di Ponte Sisto by the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' in an [[etching]] by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] (1759)]]\nAfter the death of [[Julius II]] in 1513, his successor, [[Pope Leo X]] (r. 1513-1521) from the [[House of Medici]], continued the work.<ref name=cas382>Castagnoli (1958), p. 382</ref> Further construction was done mainly in the northern part of the road between the unfinished ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' and the banking district, which supported the Florentine merchant community.<ref name=cas382/> In this area, important artists, such as [[Raphael]] and [[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]], acquired plots of land or built palaces.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie36/> \n\nThe area south of the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] changed radically: the central part of the Via Giulia around ''Monte dei Planca Incoronati'' became a slum filled with inns, brothels, and infamous locations like ''Piazza Padella'', a venue known for duels and stabbings up to the end of 19th century and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=del504>Delli (1988), p. 504</ref> The area between ''Via del Gonfalone'', ''Via delle Carceri'', ''Via di Monserrato'', and the Tiber was a major district of ill-repute since the Middle Ages; a manuscript from 1556 reports about the quarter around the eventually demolished church of ''San Niccol\u00f2 degli Incoronati'' hosted \"... 150 houses of very simple people, whores and dubious persons ...\".<ref name=arm424>Armellini (1891), p. 424</ref>\nThe quarter starting from the church of Santa Aurea, today [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]], was called ''Castrum Senense'' in the [[Middle Ages]] because it was mainly inhabited by people from Siena.<ref name=del473>Delli (1988), p. 473</ref>  At this end of the Via Giulia, a well-defined architectural development plan was drawn up, which started with building the [[palazzo Farnese|Farnese residence]]. In 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (lit. \"Beggar's Hospice\") was built by the architect [[Domenico Fontana]] on the orders of [[Pope Sixtus V]] (r. 1585-1590) and marked the end of the ''Via Giulia''.<ref name=pie7976/> It was built to solve the begging problem in the city and was given a yearly endowment of 150,000 ''[[roman scudo|scudi]]'' which could employ 2,000 people.<ref name=cas415>Castagnoli (1988), p. 415</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 16th century it had become fashionable for the various nations and city-states to have their own churches built in Rome known as the ''chiese nazionali''.<ref name=cas392/> The ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], along the [[procession]]al and pilgrim roads, were the preferred locations. The Florentines,  the Sienese, and the Neapolitans had their churches built in Via Giulia (the [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini|San Giovanni]], the [[Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia|Santa Caterina]], and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|Santo Spirito]] respectively),<ref name=del473/><ref name=pie16/> while the Bolognese ([[Santi Giovanni Evangelista e Petronio|San Giovanni e Petronio]]), Spanish ([[Santa Maria in Monserrato degli Spagnoli|Santa Maria in Monserrato]]), English ([[San Tommaso di Canterbury]]) and Swedish ([[Santa Brigida, Rome|Santa Brigida]]) churches were built in the Regola ''rione''.<ref name=cas392>Castagnoli (1958), p. 392</ref>\n\nIn order to supply the quarter with sufficient drinking water, [[Pope Paul V]] (r. 1605-1621) had the [[Aqua Paola]] extend over the Tiber. In 1613, the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'' (lit. \"The Big Fountain of the Sistine Bridge\") was built on the [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the beggars' hospice on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7978/> It was demolished in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the [[Ponte Sisto]] in what is now ''Piazza Trilussa''.[[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"300\" heights=\"300\">\n 1645 Antonio Tempesta Via Giulia marked.svg|Via Giulia; Particular from ''Almae urbis Romae prospectus'' by [[Antonio Tempesta]] (1645)\n</gallery>\nAt the end of the 16th century Via Giulia's path was fixed; it ended by the Florentine quarter to the north and the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' to the south. It became less of a major commercial street and more a busy promenade and a place for celebrations, processions (such as that of the ''ammantate'', poor girls which were dowried by the goldsmiths of [[Sant'Eligio degli Orefici]]) and races.<ref name=pie799>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 9</ref><ref name=pie7910/> \n\nIn 1603 Tiberio Ceuli held a [[Tournament (medieval)|tournament]] at Palazzo Sacchetti,<ref name=doc>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/ldpd_7219594_000/ldpd_7219594_000_djvu.txt|title=Documenti del Barocco Romano|p=58 [c440] (1)|language=it|access-date=5 March 2020|publisher=Miscellanea della R. Societ\u00e0 Romana di Storia Patria|editor=J. A. F. Orbaan|year=1920|location=Roma}}</ref> while in 1617 [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] organized a [[Saracen]] tournament at the ''Oratorio della Compagnia della Morte'', to which he invited eight cardinals.<ref name=gig118>Gigli (1958), p. 118</ref> During the summer months the street was sometimes flooded for the pleasure of the common people and the nobility.<ref name=pie7910>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 10</ref> One of the most glamorous celebrations was held by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1638 to celebrate the birth of the French [[Dauphin of France|dauphin]], the future king [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=pie7910/> Via Giulia hosted [[Water buffalo|buffalo]] races, parades of carnival [[Float (parade)|floats]], and in 1663 the organisation of a horse race with naked hunchbacks during [[Carnival]] is handed down.<ref name=pie798/> During the carnival, Via Giulia hosted several feasts promoted by the Florentines.<ref name=pie7910/>\nIn the [[baroque]] period, other important building projects contributed to the later appearance of the street: the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]],<ref name=pie16/> the ''Carceri Nuove'' (lit. \"New Prisons\"),<ref name=pie7913/> the [[Palazzo Falconieri]] <ref name=pie7944/>, and the churches of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani and [[Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome|Santa Maria del Suffragio]].<ref name=pie56>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 56</ref> The street's character changed little despite the addition of these buildings. Via Giulia was rather left out in Rome's general [[urban development]] plan.\n\n===Development in the 18th and 19th centuries===\nIn the 18th century the Via Giulia remained primarily a place to organise feasts: in 1720 the Sienese held a festival to celebrate the promotion of [[Marc'Antonio Zondadari]] to Grand Master of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of Malta]].<ref name=pie798/> [[Fireworks]] was set off near the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'';<ref name=pie7910/> two triumphal arches were raised above the street: one in Santo Spirito and the other near Palazzo Farnese;<ref name=pie798/><ref name=pie7910/> and the Fountain of the Mascherone poured wine for the people instead of water.<ref name=pie7910/>\n\nUnder [[Pope Clement XI]]'s (r. 1720-1721) rule, the beggars housed in the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' were transferred to the [[San Michele a Ripa]].<ref name=pie7980>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 80</ref> The building was occupied by both poor unmarried girls (''zitelle'' in the [[Romanesco dialect]]) and a congregation made up of 100 priests and 20 clerics; the latter prayed for the souls of deceased priests;<ref name=pie7980/> as such, the building was nicknamed the ''Ospizio dei cento preti'' (\"Hospice of the Hundred Priests\").<ref name=pie7980/>  \n\nIn the 19th century only a few new buildings or restoration projects were realised: among them were the youth prison (Palazzo del Gonfalone) (1825-27), the renovation of the Armenian Hospice next to the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] (1830), the new fa\u00e7ade of the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]] (1853), and the [[Collegio Spagnuolo]] (1853). However, this did not stop the general decline of the street that started in the middle of the 18th century.<ref name=del474>Delli (1988), p. 474</ref> The nobility abandoned the palaces on the street to move to the new center of urban life in the [[Campo Marzio (rione of Rome)|Campo Marzio]], and in their place the road hosted artisans and became less of a centre for festivities.<ref name=ber332>Bertarelli (1925), p. 332</ref>\n\n===Via Giulia since 1870===\nAfter Rome [[Capture of Rome|became the capital]] of the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1870, the Tiber (known for flooding, particularly in ''[[Campus Martius]]'') had its banks worked on in 1873 by constructing [[Lungotevere]]s, which since 1888 were erected along the road and required the church of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani to be torn down.<ref name=pie8110>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 10</ref> The Lungoteveres completely cut off Via Giulia from the Tiber and prevented the [[loggia]]s and gardens of the palaces facing the river, such as the Palazzi Medici-Clarelli, Sacchetti, Varese, and [[Palazzo Falconieri|Falconieri]] from having a view of the river.\nSignificant building demolitions during the fascist period left a large gap between ''Via della Barchetta'' and the ''Vicolo delle Prigioni'', which to this day has only been partially filled by the new building of the ''Liceo Classico Virgilio''.<ref name=pie791822>Pietrangeli (1979), pp. 18-22</ref> The street has regained its status as one of the most prestigious streets in the city.<ref name=nyt/><ref name=pie7910/>\nNumerous events took place in 2008 during its 500th anniversary; some churches and palaces were restored and opened to visitors.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/29/travel/29globe.html|title=A Stroll in Rome With a Papal Pedigree-Via Giulia celebrates its 500th birthday this year|author=Elisabeth Rosenthal|date=29 June 2008|access-date=8 March 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks on Via Giulia==\nVia Giulia extends northwest for about one kilometre from the Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti on the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Piazza dell'Oro in front of the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]. From 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (\"Beggars' Hospice\") marked the southern end of the street.<ref name=pie7976>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 76</ref> Under Paul V's decree in 1613, a fountain that brought the [[Aqua Paola]] to the [[Regola]] ''rione''  was built against its fa\u00e7ade (see engraving by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] above).<ref name=pie7978>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 78</ref> This fountain was demolished together with the hospice in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the Ponte Sisto in what is now Piazza Trilussa [[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n[[File:Via Giulia Roma.svg|400px|center|Map of via Giulia]]\n===1 Palazzina Pateras Pescara (Via Giulia 251)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Pal Pateras Pescara (Consulat de France).jpg|thumb|100px|1 Palazzo Pateras Pescara]]\nThis last building in Via Giulia was built in 1924 by [[Marcello Piacentini]] on behalf of the Avvocato Pateras.<ref name=pie7962>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 62</ref> Today it houses the Consulate of the French Republic in Rome.<ref name=pie7962/>\n===2 Fontana del Mascherone===\n[[File:Fontana del Mascherone Via Giulia.jpg|thumb|100px|2 Fontana del Mascherone]]\nThe fountain diagonally opposite [[Palazzo Farnese]] was built around 1626 by [[Carlo Rainaldi]] and paid for by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]].<ref name=pie7956>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 56</ref> It was planned in 1570 to be a public fountain fed by the ''[[Aqua Virgo]]'' [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] to supply people with clean drinking water.<ref name=pie7956/> However, installation was only possible after Paul V ordered the water pipe to be extended over the [[Ponte Sisto]] in 1612.<ref name=pie7956/><ref name=pie7958>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 58</ref> The fountain consists of an ancient large marble mask (\"Mascherone\") on a background with [[volute]]s in marble, crowned by the symbol of the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]], a metal [[Fleur-de-lis]].<ref name=pie7956/> The fountain was moved against the wall in 1903, losing most of its charm.<ref name=pie7956/> The poet [[Wilhelm Waiblinger]] died in 1830 in the house opposite to it [[:File:Via Giulia Sterbehaus Wilhelm Waiblinger.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===3 Palazzo Farnese (Via Giulia 186)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Farnese}}\n[[File:Palazzo Farnese Gartenseite.jpg|thumb|100px|3 Palazzo Farnese]]\nThe garden fa\u00e7ade of this palace building is oriented towards the Via Giulia. In 1549 it was designed according to [[Vignola]]'s drawings and completed by [[Giacomo della Porta]] in 1589.<ref name=cal213>Callari (1932), p. 213</ref> The garden between the fa\u00e7ade and the Via Giulia was once adorned by the [[Toro Farnese|Farnese bull]] (now in the [[National Archaeological Museum, Naples|National Archaeological Museum]] in [[Naples]]) [[:File:Farnese Bull MAN Napoli Inv6002 n01.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7956/> The palace is now the French Embassy in Italy.\n===3a Camerini Farnesiani (Via Giulia 253-260)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Camerini Farnesiani.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nBehind the row of lower buildings (\"Camerini Farnesiani\") [[:File:Via Giulia 253-260 Palazzetto Farnese.jpg|(Fig.)]], which today belong to the French Embassy, lay a small palace with garden, the Palazzetto Farnese, built around 1603 by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] as his [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]],<ref name=pie7954/> also known as ''Eremo del Cardinale'' (\"Cardinal's hermitage\"). This private retreat of the Cardinal, decorated with murals by [[Giovanni Lanfranco]], was accessible from Palazzo Farnese via a terrace and the Arco Farnese.<ref name=pie7954/> The building and garden was destroyed in the Tiber regulation after 1870.\n\n===4 Arco Farnese===\n[[File:Via Giulia Farnesebogen.jpg|thumb|100px|4 Arco Farnese]]\nThe bridge connects Via Giulia to the [[Palazzo Farnese]]. It was erected in 1603,<ref name=pie7954>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 54</ref> and was used to observe festive processions, games, and horse races in Via Giulia, particularly during [[Carnival]].\n===5 Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte===\n{{Main|Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte}}\nThe church, built in 1575-76, is located in the immediate vicinity of [[Palazzo Farnese]] and belonged to the ''Compagnia della Morte'' (\"Death's Brotherhood\") founded in 1538.<ref name=pie7948>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 48</ref> The fraternity was tasked with burying the dead that were recovered from the river or found in the [[Roman Campagna|area surrounding Rome]]. The building was demolished in 1733 and rebuilt by [[Ferdinando Fuga]] in 1737.<ref name=pie7950>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 50</ref> Its cemetery on the banks of the Tiber was demolished when the river was regulated in 1886.<ref name=pie7948/>\n===6 Palazzo Falconieri also Palazzo Odescalchi Falconieri (Via Giulia 1)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Falconieri}}\n[[File:Regola - via Giulia palazzo Falconieri facciata 1180066.JPG|thumb|100px|6 Palazzo Falconieri]]\nThe original building was built in the 16th century for the Roman noble family of the Ceci and directly adjoins the church of [[Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte]]. It was sold by the Ceci in 1574 to the [[Odescalchi family]] before being passed to the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1606. Eventually the Florentine nobleman [[Orazio Falconieri]] bought it in 1638 for 16,000 scudi.<ref name=pie7944>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 44</ref> From 1646 to 1649 he commissioned the architect [[Francesco Borromini]] to extend the palace.<ref name=pie7944/> The sides of the fa\u00e7ade on Via Giulia are decorated with two [[pilaster]]s in the shape of large [[herma]]s with female breasts and falcon heads.<ref name=pie7946>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 46</ref> The fa\u00e7ade on the [[Tiber]] side features a three-arched [[loggia]] <ref name=pie7946/> dating back to 1646. From 1814 Cardinal [[Joseph Fesch]], uncle of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] lived there, and from 1815 to 1818 he hosted his stepsister [[Laetitia Ramolino]], the emperor's mother.<ref name=pie7946/> In 1927 the Kingdom of Italy ceded the palace to the [[Hungary|Hungarian State]], which established it as the seat of the Hungarian Academy (Accademia d'ungheria). Today, in addition to the Academy, the palace is home to the Hungarian Embassy and the ''Pontificium Institutum Ecclesiasticum Hungaricum in Urbe''.\n\n===7 Palazzo Baldoca-Muccioli (Via Giulia 167)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Baldoca Muccioli.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe history of the palace is closely linked to the neighbouring Palazzo Cisterna.<ref name=pie7940/> Both properties were acquired by the sculptor [[Guglielmo della Porta]].<ref name=pie7940/> In 1540 [[Pope Paul III]] (r. 1534-1549) appointed him as his court artist and entrusted him with the interior decoration of Palazzo Farnese. The sculptor gave the building to the Baldoca family and then to the Muccioli. At the beginning of the 20th century the palace served as the residence of the English ambassador in Rome, Lord Rennel of Rodd, who bought and had it restored in 1928.<ref name=pie7940/>\n===8 Palazzo Cisterna (Via Giulia 163)===\n[[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Rom).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe Palazzo Cisterna was built by [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and served as his residence.<ref name=pie7940/> Above the [[architrave]] of the windows on the first floor the inscription '''FRANCISCVS TANCREDA ET GVILELMVS D(ella) P(orta) ME(ediolanensis) - S(culptor) CI(vis) RO(manus)''' can be read [[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Roma).jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7940/> From a letter to a friend, it appears that the palace was completed in 1575. In 1600 Spanish missionaries acquired the palace and sold it to the Cisterna family at the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=pie7940/> It was sold to the Ducci family in the middle of the 20th century.\n===9 Santa Caterina da Siena in Via Giulia===\n{{Main|Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia}}\n[[File:Regola - S. Caterina da Siena.JPG|thumb|100px|9 Santa Caterina]]\nThe history of this church is closely linked to the [[republic of Siena|Sienese]] Brotherhood.<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref> A community of merchants, bankers and craftsmen from Siena had been living in what was to be Via Giulia, where at that time stood the ''castrum Senense'' since the 14th century.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1519 the Brotherhood was canonically erected by Leo X.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1526 they commissioned [[Baldassare Peruzzi]] to build the church in honour of their saints, an [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]], and a house for the clerics.<ref name=pie7936/> The funds were provided by the Sienese nobility in Rome, particularly by Cardinal [[Giovanni Piccolomini]] and the banker [[Agostino Chigi]]. Since it was in a dilapidated state, it was rebuilt between 1766 and 1768 according to [[Paolo Posi]]'s designs,<ref name=pie7938>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 38</ref> while the interior decor was completed in 1775.<ref name=pie7938/> The [[Archconfraternity]] of the Sienese still owns the building today.<ref name=pie7940>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 40</ref> During Via Giulia's 500th anniversary of the street in 2008 the altarpiece was restored by Girolamo Genga.\n===10 Palazzo Varese (Via Giulia 14-21)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (1).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe palace opposite Santa Caterina da Siena was built between 1617 and 1618 by [[Carlo Maderno]] on behalf of Monsignor Diomede Varese.<ref name=pie7934>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 34</ref> In 1788 Monsignor Giuseppe degli Atti Varese gave the building to the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith|Congregation ''Propaganda Fide'']] when his family line died out.<ref name=pie7934/> After exchanging owners several times the palace finally came into the possession of the [[Mancini family]].<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref>\nThe front consists of two upper floors and a [[mezzanine]]. On the ground floor is the main [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and above it is a balcony on [[console (architecture)|console]]s, flanked by three windows each. A portal opens into the yard with three [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s stacked on one another [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (2).jpg|(Fig.)]]. The yard originally opened to a garden by the river.\n===11 Sant'Eligio degli Orefici (Via di Sant'Eligio 9)===\n{{Main|Sant'Eligio degli Orefici}}\n[[File:Sant' Eligio degli Orefici - Au\u00dfenansicht.jpg|thumb|100px|11 Sant\u2019Eligio]]\nThe small church is off the Via Giulia and serves as the guild church of the Roman gold- and silversmiths.<ref name=pie7930>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 30</ref> Its construction is attributed to [[Raphael]], although it is possible that after the death of the artist it was finished by [[Baldassare Peruzzi]].<ref name=pie7932>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 32</ref>\n===12 Palazzo del Collegio Spagnolo (Via Giulia 151)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Collegio Spagnolo.jpg|thumb|100px|12 Collegio Spagnolo]]\nThe ''Palacio de Monserrat'' by [[Pietro Camporese the Younger|Pietro Camporese]] and [[Antonio Sarti]] was built between 1848 and 1862 and is the Spanish Centre for Higher Ecclesiastical Studies today. The Centre is attached to the Spanish National Church of [[Santa Maria di Monserrato]] on Via di Monserrato behind it. Construction on Via Giulia stopped with the completion of this building complex in the 19th century.\n===13 Liceo Statale Virgilio (Via Giulia No 35 ff.)===\nOne of the most important state school complexes in Rome was built between 1936 and 1939 <ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref> by [[Marcello Piacentini]]. The building complex between Via Giulia and the [[Lungotevere dei Tebaldi]] includes the fa\u00e7ade of [[Palazzo Ghislieri]] [[:File:Via Giulia Collegio Ghisleri.jpg|(Fig.)]], designed by [[Carlo Maderno]] (16th century), and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|church of the Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]].\n===14 Palazzo Ricci (Via Giulia 146)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe present building was originally a cluster of unconnected buildings, built at different times, opposite the Collegio Ghislieri.<ref name=pie7928>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 28</ref> The building complex was merged in 1634 and 1683. The main fa\u00e7ade facing Piazza de'Ricci shows strongly faded remains of a ''[[Graffito (drawing technique)|graffito]]'' by [[Polidoro da Caravaggio]] (16th century). On the side facing Via Giulia, a continuous fa\u00e7ade gave the complex its present uniform appearance [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===15 Santo Spirito dei Napoletani===\n{{Main|Santo Spirito dei Napoletani}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santo Spirito dei Napoletani 1.jpg|thumb|100px|15 Sto. Spirito dei Napoletani]]\nIn the [[Pius V]] catalogue this church is listed under the name of ''Santa Aura in strada Iulia''.<ref name=arm423>Armellini (1891), p. 423</ref> It was dedicated to [[Aurea of Ostia|Saint Aurea]], the patron saint of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]].<ref name=arm423/> A nunnery was attached to the church.<ref name=arm423/> In 1439 the church was restored at the expense of Cardinal [[Guillaume d'Estouteville]].<ref name=arm423/> In 1572 Cardinal Inigo d'Avalos founded in the dilapidated building the ''Confraternita dello Spirito Santo dei Napoletani'' (\"Brotherhood of the Holy Spirit of the Neapolitans\"), who bought it from the nuns in 1574.<ref name=pie7924>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 24</ref> Between 1619 and 1650 a new building was erected, with a project of [[Ottavio Mascherino]] and a fa\u00e7ade by [[Cosimo Fanzago]].<ref name=pie7924/> It was dedicated to the Holy Spirit.<ref name=pie7924/> In the following centuries it was renovated several times, at the beginning of the 18th century by [[Carlo Fontana]] <ref name=pie7924/> and in the middle of the 19th century the fa\u00e7ade was renovated by Antonio Cipolla (1853).<ref name=pie7926>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 26</ref> It was the National Church of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]. The last [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|King of Naples]] [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] and his wife [[Maria Sophie of Bavaria|Marie Sophie Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]], were buried in the church in 1942.<ref name=pie7926/><ref name=del475>Delli (1988), p. 475</ref> After a long period of restoration, the church is open to the public again since 1986. [[:File:Santo Spirito dei Napoletani (Inneres).jpg|(Fig.)]]\n===16 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia===\n[:File:Via Giulia Oratorio San Filippo Neri.jpg|(Fig.)]]\n{{Main|San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\nConstruction of the small church opposite the Carceri Nuove was sponsored by Rutilio Brandi, a glove-maker from Florence, and given to the ''Compagnia delle santissime piaghe'' around 1600. The church was originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> It was connected to a residence for unmarried girls (''zitelle'') and a hospital for sick priests.<ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The church was dedicated to [[San Filippo Neri]] after the saint's death.<ref name=pie7916/> In 1728 [[Filippo Raguzzini]] restored the church on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730).<ref name=pie7918/> The church barely escaped destruction in the early 1940s due to the construction of a large road that should have joined [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]].<ref name=pie7918/> This road was never built due to the [[World War II]].<ref name=pie7918/> It was abandoned after the war before being restored for non-religious purposes.\n\n===17 Carceri Nuove (Via Giulia 52)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove 1.jpg|thumb|100px|17 Carceri Nuove]]\nSince 1430 the [[Savelli family]] had a monopoly on prisons in the city, especially ''Corte Savella'' at 42 Via di Monserrato. The inhumane penal system in the Corte Savella caused [[Pope Innocent X]] (r. 1644-1655)) to withdraw the Savelli's monopoly on the penal system in Rome. As a sign of new ''Justitia Papalis'', he had the new penal institution, the ''Carceri Nuove'', built in Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> This new prison was built between 1652 and 1655 by the architect Antonio del Grande.<ref name=pie7913/><ref>Inscription above the portal: IUSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE SECURIORI AC MITlORI REORUM CUSTODIAE NOVUM CARCEREM INNOCENTIUS X PONT. MAX. POSUIT ANNO DOMINI MDCLV (''Innocent X. P.M. built the new prison in the year of the Lord 1655, for justice, leniency for the safe and humane custody of convicts'')</ref> The Carceri Nuove were considered a model of a humane penitentiary system in their time. The building and its purpose had a rather negative influence on the image of the magnificent street, which led to the suspension of construction in the following years and the [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] character of the street being preserved. The building acted as a prison until the opening of [[Regina Coeli]] in [[Trastevere]] <ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> in 1883, further on until 1931 as a youth prison.<ref name=pie7914/> From 1931 the palace housed the headquarters of the ''Centro di Studi Penitenziari'' (\"Research Institute for Criminal Justice\") and a specialized library.<ref name=pie7914/> Today the building houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Directorate for Anti-Mafia and Anti-Terrorism\").\n\n===17a Palazzo del Gonfalone===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Museo Criminologico.jpg|thumb|100px|17a Palazzo del Gonfalone]]\nThe building between the Vicolo della Scimia and Via del Gonfalone has no entrance from Via Giulia.<ref name=pie64/> It was built between 1825 and 1827 under [[Pope Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) according to plans by [[Giuseppe Valadier]] as a prison for the youth.<ref name=pie64>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 64</ref> Today the building houses the ''Museo Criminologico'' (lit. \"Criminological Museum\").<ref name=pie66>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 66</ref>\n===18 Santa Maria del Suffragio===\n{{Main|Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santa Maria del Suffragio.jpg|thumb|100px|18 S.M. del Suffragio]]\nIn 1592 the ''Confraternita del Suffragio'' (\"Brotherhood of Intercession\") was founded next to the church of [[San Biagio della Pagnotta]] to implore the intercession for the souls of the purgatory.<ref name=pie56/> The Brotherhood was approved by [[Pope Clement VIII]] (r. 1592-1605) in 1594 <ref name=pie56/> and was elevated to the status of ''Arciconfaternita'' (\"Archbishopric Brotherhood\") by [[Paul V]] in 1620. Thanks to several donations, in 1662 the erection of the church began as a project of architect [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie56/> The building was consecrated in 1669, and the fa\u00e7ade was finished in 1680.<ref name=pie56/> The church's interior was renovated in 1869; the frescoes inside the church are by [[Cesare Mariani]] (''[[Coronation of the Virgin]]'') and [[Giuseppe Chiari]] (''[[Nativity of Mary]]'' and ''[[Adoration of the Magi]]'').<ref name=pie58>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 58</ref>\n===19 Palazzo dei Tribunali===\n[[File:Via Giulia Sof\u00e0 (Palazzo dei Tribunali) 1.jpg|thumb|100px|19 Sof\u00e0]]\n[[Julius II]]'s most important planned project in the new street was a central administration building, in which a large part of the city's important offices and courts (\"tribunali\") were to be grouped together.<ref name=pie50/> The Pope's commission to [[Donato Bramante]] (at the time main architect of the new St. Peter's Basilica)<ref name=pie50/> was issued around 1506, and construction in the area between ''Vicolo del Cefalo'' and ''Via del Gonfalone'' began before 1508,<ref name=pie50/> but was interrupted as in 1511 by the ''Pax Romana''.<ref name=tem124/> With the [[Julius II]]'s death in 1513, construction completely stopped. [[Giorgio Vasari]] wrote:\n{{quote|''Onde Bramante diede principio al palazzo ch'a San Biagio su 'l Tevere si vede, nel quale \u00e8 ancora un tempio corinzio non finito, cosa molto rara, et il resto del principio di opera rustica bellissimo che \u00e8 stato gran danno che una s\u00ec onorata et utile e magnifica opra non si sia finita, ch\u00e9 da quelli della professione \u00e8 tenuto il pi\u00f9 bello ordine che si sia visto mai in quel genere.''}}\n{{quote|Bramante therefore began the construction of the palace, which can be seen near San Biagio on the Tiber. In it there is still an unfinished [[corinthian order|Corinthian]] temple, something very rare and the remains of the beginning in beautiful ''[[Rustication (architecture)|Opera Rustica]]''. It is a great pity that such an important, useful and great project has remained unfinished. Experts considered it to be the most beautiful building of its kind ever seen.}} <ref name=vasBra/><ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref><ref name=pie52/>\nSome remains of the mighty [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] walls, called ''sof\u00e0'' by the Roman population, between Via del Gonfalone and Vicolo del Cefalo along Via Giulia, can be seen today.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===20 San Biagio della Pagnotta (San Biagio degli Armeni)===\n{{Main|San Biagio della Pagnotta}}\n[[File:Via Giulia San Biagio della Pagnotta.jpg|thumb|100px|20 San Biagio]]\nThis church was dedicated to [[Saint Blaise]] of [[Sivas|Sebaste]] and is mentioned in the church catalogues of the Middle Ages under the name of ''San Biagio de Cantu Secuta''.<ref name=pie52>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 52</ref> The name \"della pagnotta\" is derived from the Roman word ''pagnotta'' (\"bread roll\"), which was distributed to the faithful on the 3 February (feast of St. Blaise) and thought to protect against throat illnesses.<ref name=pie54>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 54</ref> The church was attached to one of the first abbeys in Rome.<ref name=pie52/> An inscription on the interior commemorates the construction of the church by an abbot Dominicus in 1072.<ref name=arm356>Armellini (1891), p. 356</ref> According to the Bramante's plans, this church was to be included in the construction of the Palazzo dei Tribunali. From 1539 to 1835 it was a [[parish]] church.<ref name=pie54/> In 1826 [[Pope Gregory XVI]] (r. 1831-1846) assigned the church to the [[Armenian people|Armenian]] community of Santa Maria Egiziaca.<ref name=pie54/> Since then it has been called officially ''San Biagio degli Armeni''.<ref name=pie52/>\n===21 Palazzo Ricci-Donarelli (Via Giulia no. 99-105)===\nThe palace is opposite to the Palazzo Sacchetti and was originally a group of residential buildings that first belonged to the [[Ricci family|Ricci]] and later to the Donarelli family.<ref name=pie48>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 48</ref>  The complex was restructured in 1663, possibly by [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref>\n===22 Palazzo Sacchetti (Via Giulia 66)===\n[[File:Palazzo Sacchetti Via Giulia (Rom).jpg|thumb|100px|22 Palazzo Sacchetti]]\n[[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]] built the palace on land bought in 1542 by the Vatican Chapter.<ref name=pie40>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 40</ref> The fa\u00e7ade still bears the chipped [[coat of arms]] of Paul III.<ref name=pie40/> His son Orazio inherited the building and sold it in 1552 to Cardinal [[Giovanni Ricci (bishop)|Giovanni Ricci]] di [[Montepulciano]], who had the palace extended to its current dimensions by the architect [[Nanni di Baccio Bigio]].<ref name=pie40/> An inscription<ref>Inscription [[:File:Ponte - via Giulia palazzo Sacchetti - domus Antonii Sangalli architecti 1160658.JPG|(Fig.)]] on the fa\u00e7ade: DOMVS/ANTONII/SANGALLI/ARCHITECTI/MDLIII (house of the architect Antonio Sangallo 1553)</ref> in the Vicolo del Cefalo's side wall states that the palace was exempted from paying the census tax in 1555.[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Sacchetti Zensus 1555.jpg|(Fig.)]]<ref name=pie46/> The building changed hands several times.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie42>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 42</ref> In 1649 it was bought by the Florentine [[Sacchetti family]], whose name it still bears.<ref name=pie42/> The entrance to Via Giulia is made of marble and flanked on both sides by three large windows with grilles, thresholds, and cornices.<ref name=pie44>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 44</ref> In the left corner of the palace there is a small fountain [[:File:Palazzo Sacchetti Delfinbrunnen.jpg|(Fig.)]] flanked by [[caryatid]]es with two dolphins embedded in the wall;<ref name=pie44/> this refers to the later owners, the Ceuli family, whose coat of arms was chipped.<ref name=pie44/> Notable features inside include the ''Salone dei Mappamondi'' (\"Hall of World Maps\"), designed by [[Francesco de' Rossi (Il Salviati)|Francesco Salviati]],<ref name=pie46>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 46</ref> and the dining room with two [[fresco]]es designed by [[Pietro da Cortona]].<ref name=pie46/> The writer [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] lived in this palazzo in 1973 and died on 17 October 1973.\n===23 Palace with the Farnese coat of arms (Via Giulia 93)===\n[[File:Via Giulia (Rom);Palast mit den Farnese Wappen.jpg|thumb|100px|23 Palazzo with the Farnese coat of arms]]\nThe building is attributed to [[Giacomo della Porta]]. The palazzo takes its name from the three coats of arms of the [[Farnese family]], which were added to the fa\u00e7ade under Paul III. In the centre of the upper floor there is the coat of arms of [[Paul III]] with the papal [[tiara]] and the keys between two [[unicorn]]s. On the left is the coat of arms of Cardinal [[Alessandro Farnese (cardinal)|Alessandro Farnese]] and on the right the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma and Piacenza]] [[Ranuccio I Farnese]].\n===24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Via Giulia 79)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli.jpg|thumb|100px|24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli]]\nAntonio da Sangallo the Younger built this palace as a private residence around 1535-1536.<ref name=pie34>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 34</ref> After Sangallo's death in 1546 the building was owned by the Florentine Migliore Cresci.<ref name=pie34/> An inscription above the main portal [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Inschrift).jpg|(Fig.)]] immortalizes Duke [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]].<ref name=pie34/> The palace for some time belonged to the Tuscan Consulate in Rome.<ref name=pie34/> At the end of the 17th century it was acquired by the Marini Clarelli family. In the 19th century it was used as barracks before being sold to the city of Rome in 1870. The fa\u00e7ade (richly historiated at the time of Cresci) and the portal are lined with rusticated [[ashlar]]s.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> On the sides of the portal there are badly rebuilt large windows on [[Console (architecture)|consoles]].<ref name=pie36/>\n\n===25 Casa di Raffaello (via Giulia 85)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Casa di Raffaello.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThis palace, erroneously called the House of [[Raphael]], was built after 1525 for the [[Vatican Hill|Vatican]] [[Chapter (religion)|Chapter]] according to a design by the architect Bartolomeo de Ramponibus.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> Raphael originally acquired several plots of land here.<ref name=pie36/> However, he died before the building's construction began. The designs were created by Rafael and Antonio da Sangallo the Younger.<ref name=pie36/> An inscription above the windows of the first floor is dedicated to Raphael: '''POSSEDEVA RAF SANZIO NEL MDXX'''.<ref name=pie36/>\n===26 Quarter of the Florentines===\nIn 1448 Florentine merchants who resided in Rome founded the ''Compagnia della Piet\u00e0'', akin to the Florentine \"Misericordia\".<ref name=pie14>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 14</ref> Both Popes from the [[Medici family]], Leo X and [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] (r. 1523-1534), promoted the influx of Florentines. Since 1515 the Commune of Florence had its own consulate in a palace on ''Via del Consolato''  that was erected in 1541 and demolished in 1888 to build [[Corso Vittorio Emanuele]].<ref name=pie26>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 26</ref> It had its own laws, its own court, and its own prison. Some of the buildings erected towards the end of the 15th century that once belonged to Florentines [[:File:Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (0).jpg|(Fig.)]] are still preserved across from the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]:<ref name=pie24>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 24</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" \"=\"\">\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (1).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (2).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (4).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n</gallery>\n===27 San Giovanni dei Fiorentini===\n{{Main|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini}}\n[[File:San Giovanni dei Fiorentini (Roma).jpg|thumb|200px|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]\nIn 1519 the \"nation\" of the Florentines received the privilege to build a parish church in honour of [[John the Baptist]] from Leo X .<ref name=pie16>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 16</ref> The church stands at the northern end of ''Via Giulia'' in the Florentine quarter.<ref name=pie16/> The church reflects the grandeur and the political self-image of the [[Medici family]], who owned a palazzo right next to the church. It is the largest church on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie16/> It combined the efforts of three of Rome's master builders: [[Giacomo della Porta]], [[Carlo Maderno]], and [[Francesco Borromini]].<ref name=pie16/> The last two artists [[burial|interred]] in the same tomb at the church.<ref name=pie20>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 20</ref> The altarpiece, started by [[Pietro da Cortona]], was continued by Borromini and finished by [[Ciro Ferri]].<ref name=pie20/>\n\n==Trivia==\n[[\u00c9mile Zola]], who visited Rome from 1894 to 1896, gave a description of Via Giulia and Palazzo Sacchetti (Palazzo Boccanera) in his [[travel literature|travelogue]].<ref>\u00c9mile Zola: ''Les trois villes \u2013 Rome''; Volume I, Cap. 3,II; Parigi 1896</ref>\n==References==\n<references/>\n== Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giorgio Vasari\n | authorlink=Giorgio Vasari\n | title=Le vite de\u2019 pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori italiani, da Cimabue insino a' tempi nostri\n | publisher=Giunti\n | location=Firenze\n | year=1568\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giacinto Gigli\n | title = Diario romano, 1608-1670\n | location= Roma\n | publisher= Staderini\n | year= 1958\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Vittorio Bertarelli\n | publisher=Touring Club Italiano\n | location=Milano\n | year=1925\n | title=Roma e dintorni\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Callari\n | title=I Palazzi di Roma\n | publisher=Ugo Sofia-Moretti\n | location=Roma\n | year=1932\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|authorlink1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|author2=Carlo Cecchelli|author3=Gustavo Giovannoni|author4=Mario Zocca| title=Topografia e urbanistica di Roma|publisher=Cappelli|location=Bologna|year=1958|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Paolo Portoghesi\n | authorlink=Paolo Portoghesi\n | title=Roma del Rinascimento\n | publisher=Electa\n | location = Milano\n | ISSN=\n | year=1970\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Ponte (IV)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=3\n | year=1981\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n |author=Sergio Delli\n |title=Le strade di Roma\n |publisher=Newton & Compton\n |location=Roma\n |year=1988\n |language=it\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Laura Gigli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Borgo (I)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | year=1990\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Nicholas Temple\n | title=Renovatio Urbis; Architecture, urbanism and ceremony in the Rome of Julius II\n | publisher=Routledge\n | location=New York\n | year=2011\n | ISBN=978-0-203-81848-0\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Luigi Salerno|author-link=Luigi Salerno |author2=Luigi Spezzaferro |author3=Manfredo Tafuri|title=Via Giulia: una utopia urbanistica del 500|location=Rome|publisher=Staderini|year=1973}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Via Giulia (Roma)|Via Giulia}}\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/index.html#sommario Vincenzo Morelli, ''Omaggio a Via Giulia'']\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/storia.html ''La storia di Via Giulia'']\n\n{{coord|41.8942|N|12.4701|E|source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Rome|Giulia]]\n[[Category:1508 establishments in the Papal States]]\n[[Category:Renaissance architecture in Rome]]\n[[Category:Rome R. VII Regola]]\n[[Category:Rome R. V Ponte]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name = Via Giulia\n| image = 948RomaViaGiulia.JPG\n| image_size = 230px\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Arco Farnese across Via Giulia\n| map_type = \n| map_size =\n| location= Rome\n| quarter = [[Regola]], [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]]\n| coordinates =\n| terminus_a = Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti\n| terminus_b = Piazza dell'Oro\n| length = {{convert|950|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| completion_date = 1512\n| designer = [[Donato Bramante]]\n| inauguration_label = Denomination\n| inauguration_date = \n}}\n'''Via Giulia''' is a street in [[Rome]], Italy, that is of historical and architectural importance. The road was one of the first important urban planning projects in papal Rome and became one of the main centers of the [[Roman Renaissance|Renaissance]]. Up until the 1850s it was one of the favorite streets of the Roman nobility and it was enriched with feasts and games. After a two-century decline, from the 1950s onwards the road's fame was renewed to be one of the city's most prestigious locations.\n\n==Location==\nVia Giulia runs along the left (east) bank of the [[Tiber]] from ''Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti'', near [[Ponte Sisto]], to ''Piazza dell'Oro''. It is about 1 kilometre long and connects the [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]] [[rioni of Rome|Rioni]].\n\n==Denominations==\nThe road was named after its patron, [[Pope Julius II]] [[della Rovere]] (r. 1503-1513), who ordered its construction in 1508.<ref name=bramanteDbi/><ref name=del472>Delli (1988), p. 472</ref> It had been also called {{Lang|la|Via Magistralis}} (lit. \"master road\") because of its importance,<ref name=del472/> and {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\") because of its layout.<ref name=del473/>\n\n==History==\nThe area of the ancient {{Lang|la|[[Campus Martius]]}} developed into one of the most densely populated districts (''abitato'') of Rome since the early [[Middle Ages]]. The maze of narrow alleys was criss-crossed by three narrow thoroughfares: the {{Lang|la|Via Papalis}} (lit. \"papal road\"),<ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' - ''via del Governo Vecchio'' - ''piazza di Pasquino'' - ''piazza di S.Pantaleo''  - ''piazza d'Aracoeli'' - ''Campidoglio'' - ''Stradone di S.Giovanni''</ref> the {{Lang|la|Via Peregrinorum}} (lit. \"pilgrims' road\") <ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Vecchi'' - ''Via del Pellegrino'' - ''via dei Giubbonari''</ref> and the {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\").<ref>Today's ''[[via dei Coronari]]''</ref><ref name=tem57>Temple(2011), p. 57</ref> [[Procession]]s travelled through these streets almost daily during the [[Middle Ages]] to the [[Ponte Sant'Angelo|Angels' Bridge]]. As [[Dante Alighieri]] described in the [[Divine Comedy]], in 1300, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] (r. 1294-1303) ordered a two-way traffic system to be set up to avoid traffic jams or panic as a response to the dense crowds on Angels' Bridge.<ref>Dante Aligheri: Inferno, canto XVIII, vv. 28\u20133\u20133</ref> After [[Pope Martin V]] (r. 1417-1431) [[Western_Schism#Resolution|returned]] to Rome in 1420, the influx of pilgrims increased significantly again, especially in the [[Jubilee]] years. On 29 December 1450, the last day of the Holy Year, a [[stampede]] broke out on the bridge that killed more than 300 people.<ref name=gi9038>Gigli (1990) p. 38</ref><ref name=gi9040>Gigli (1990) p. 40</ref>\nAs a result of the catastrophe, [[Pope Nicholas V]] (r. 1447-1455) ordered the Angels' Bridge to be cleared of stalls and shops and the first urban planning measures in the area were initiated. In 1475, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484) ordered the [[Ponte Sisto]], named after him, to be built across the [[Tiber]] [[:File:Ponte Sisto Bauinschrift 1475.jpg|(inscription)]] in order to relieve the pilgrimage route across the Angels' Bridge and to connect the ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Trastevere]].<ref name=pie7982>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 82</ref> At the same time he ordered the restoration of ''Via Pelegrinorum'' and the area around the ''[[Campo de' Fiori]]'' [[:File:Via Florea Stadterneuerung.jpg|(inscription)]]. According to the chronicler [[Stefano Infessura]], however, strategic reasons aside from reducing traffic were also important for these projects.<ref>Stefano Infessura: ''Diario Rerum Romanorum''; Roma 1890 p. 79 f.: February 1475</ref> In 1497 [[Pope Alexander VI]] (r. 1492-1503) ordered the widening of ''Via Peregrinorum'' <ref>Inscription at the entrance to the Via del Pellegrino: ALEX VI PONT MAX POST INSTAURATAM ADRIANI MOLEM ANGUSTAS VRBIS VIAS AMMPLIARI IVSSIT MCCCCLXXXXVII (''Alexander VI. Pont. Max. ordered to widen the narrow streets of the town after the restoration of the Castel Sant'Angelo'')</ref> [[:File:Via del Pellegrino Inschrift Alexander VI.jpg|(Fig.)]] and the restoration of ''[[Via della Lungara]]'' on the right bank of the [[Tiber]] from [[Ponte Sisto]] to [[Old St. Peter's Basilica|St. Peter's Basilica]].\n\n===The project of Pope Julius II===\n[[File:Inschrift Julius II. Via Curato-Banchi.jpg|thumb|Inscription by Julius II, 1512]]\nIn addition to reconstructing [[St. Peter's Basilica]], Julius II implemented multiple projects in the framework of Rome's [[urban renewal]] (''Renovatio Romae'') in the [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], [[Parione]], [[Sant'Eustachio (rione of Rome)|Sant'Eustachio]] and [[Colonna (rione of Rome)|Colonna]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|rioni]]'', a task which was started forty years before by his uncle, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484).<ref name=cast378>Castagnoli (1958), pp.378</ref> One of the most important projects was the creation of two new straight streets on the left and right banks of the Tiber: the Via Giulia on the left bank, a new grand avenue through the most densely populated quarter of Rome, from the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Florentine merchant quarter on the [[Tiber]] bend,<ref name=pie798>Pietrangeli(1979) p. 8</ref> and a straight road along the right bank of the Tiber from the [[Porta Settimiana]] in [[Trastevere]] to the [[Ospedale di Santo Spirito in Sassia|Hospital of Santo Spirito]] in the [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]], the ''Via della Lungara''.<ref name=cast38081>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380-381</ref>\nBoth roads flanked the Tiber and were closely connected to it.<ref name=\"po19\"/> The Lungara had the dual aim to relieve the pilgrimage route to Saint Peter<ref name=cast38081/> and transport goods coming from the [[Via Aurelia]] and the [[Via Portuensis|via Portuense]] roads towards the centre of the city.  The Pope intended for it to reach Piazza di [[Santa Maria in Trastevere]] and the [[Port of Ripa Grande and Papal Arsenal|port of Ripa Grande]].<ref name=\"po19\"/>\n\nThe main goal behind these plans was to superimpose a regular road network with the focus given to the Tiber by medieval Rome's disorderly buildings; together with the new [[Borgo Nuovo (Rome)|Via Alessandrina]] that Alexander VI opened in the Borgo, the ''Via dei Pettinari'' that connected the [[Trastevere]] on one side and the [[Campidoglio]] on the other, the Lungara and Via Giulia created a quadrilateral network of modern roads in the city's maze of alleys.<ref name=\"po19\"/> In the original project Via Giulia was supposed to reach the Hospital of Santo Spirito in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]] via the rebuilt ''[[Pons Neronianus]]''.<ref name=del472/><ref name=cast380>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380</ref> The center of the city shifted towards the Vatican and [[Trastevere]] and away from the [[Palazzo Senatorio]] on the [[Capitoline Hill]], which was the symbol of the Roman nobility's power;<ref name=tem124/><ref name=\"po19\"/> the plan was intended to separate the papacy from the city's powerful noble families, particularly the [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families.<ref name=tem124>Temple (2011), pp. 124</ref>\n\nThese projects had a secondary, celebrative goal to promote the [[Pontiff]] as the unifier of Italy and the renewer of Rome; in 1506, after the end of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]], the Pope overthrew the powerful [[Baglioni (family)|Baglioni]] and [[Bentivoglio family|Bentivoglio]] families and conquered [[Perugia]] and [[Bologna]],<ref name=\"po19\">Portoghesi, p. 19</ref> as testified in an inscription along the ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi''.<ref>IVLIO.II.PONT:OPT:MAX:QVOD FINIB:DITIONIS.S.R.E.PROLATIS ITALIAQ:LIBERATA VRBEM ROMAM OCCVPATE SIMILIOREM QVAM DIVISE PATEFACTIS DIMENSIS Q: VIIS PRO MAIESTATE IMPERII ORNAVIT (''Julius II p.o.m. who extended the power of the Holy Roman Church and freed Italy. The city of Rome, which resembled a conquered rather than a properly planned one, he embellished for the glory of the Empire'')</ref>\n\nAside from serving as a means of communication and representation for the Church, the road was supposed to host the city's new layman's administrative center.<ref name=\"po19\"/> [[Luitpold Frommel]] discovered a drawing by [[Donato Bramante]] in the Uffizi which showed a new huge administrative complex, the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'', facing a representative square (the ''Foro Iulio'') that opened along the new street.<ref name=\"po19\"/> This forum was thought to lie between the ''Palazzo'' and the old ''[[Chancery (medieval office)|Cancelleria]]'' (today's Palazzo Sforza-Cesarini).<ref name=tem6768/> The centre was not far from the [[Apostolic Camera]] (the Pope's treasury) in [[Palazzo della Cancelleria|Palazzo Riario]] and the new ''Palazzo della Zecca'' (lit. \"papal mint\") erected by Bramante at the edge of ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' (also named ''Canale di Ponte'').<ref name=tem6768>Temple (2011), pp. 67-68</ref> By this road lay the merchants' and bankers' houses and offices, like the [[House of Altoviti|Altoviti]], Ghinucci, [[Acciaioli family|Acciaiuoli]], [[Chigi Family|Chigi]] and [[Fugger]].<ref name=cast378/> Close economic ties with Tuscan bankers like [[Agostino Chigi]] were sought and promoted.<ref name=chigiDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/agostino-chigi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=Agostino Chigi|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Francesco|last=Dante|volume=24|year=1980|language=it}}</ref>\n\nAround 1508 Bramante was asked by the Pope to start [[expropriating]] and demolishing properties in the densely populated ''[[Campus Martius|Campo Marzio]]'' to create the new street.<ref name=bramanteDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/donato-bramante_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Donato Bramante|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Arnaldo|last=Bruschi|volume=13|year=1971|language=it}}</ref>\n\n[[Giorgio Vasari]] writes:\n{{quote|''Si risolv\u00e9 il Papa di mettere in strada Giulia, da Bramante indrizzata, tutti gli uffici e le ragioni di Roma in un luogo, per la commodit\u00e0 ch\u2019a i negoziatori averia recato nelle faccende, essendo continuamente fino allora state molto scomode.''}}\n{{quote|The Pope decided to consolidate all the offices and financial centers of Rome in one place in the Via Giulia designed by Bramante. This would have made it easier for businessmen to conduct their business, which until then had been a cumbersome process.}} <ref name=vasBra>Giorgio Vasari: Vita di Donato Bramante \u2013 1568</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1511, an agreement (known as the ''Pax Romana'') between the feuding [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families was formed, which caused the ''Via Giulia'' and the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' projects to be suspended.<ref name=tem124/> Apart from a few [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] blocks between the Via del Gonfalone and the Vicolo del Cefalo, nothing remained of the palace.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===Via Giulia in the 16th and 17th century===\n[[File:G.Vasi - Collegio Ecclesiastico a Ponte Sisto.jpg|thumb|Fontana di Ponte Sisto by the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' in an [[etching]] by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] (1759)]]\nAfter the death of [[Julius II]] in 1513, his successor, [[Pope Leo X]] (r. 1513-1521) from the [[House of Medici]], continued the work.<ref name=cas382>Castagnoli (1958), p. 382</ref> Further construction was done mainly in the northern part of the road between the unfinished ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' and the banking district, which supported the Florentine merchant community.<ref name=cas382/> In this area, important artists, such as [[Raphael]] and [[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]], acquired plots of land or built palaces.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie36/> \n\nThe area south of the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] changed radically: the central part of the Via Giulia around ''Monte dei Planca Incoronati'' became a slum filled with inns, brothels, and infamous locations like ''Piazza Padella'', a venue known for duels and stabbings up to the end of 19th century and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=del504>Delli (1988), p. 504</ref> The area between ''Via del Gonfalone'', ''Via delle Carceri'', ''Via di Monserrato'', and the Tiber was a major district of ill-repute since the Middle Ages; a manuscript from 1556 reports about the quarter around the eventually demolished church of ''San Niccol\u00f2 degli Incoronati'' hosted \"... 150 houses of very simple people, whores and dubious persons ...\".<ref name=arm424>Armellini (1891), p. 424</ref>\nThe quarter starting from the church of Santa Aurea, today [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]], was called ''Castrum Senense'' in the [[Middle Ages]] because it was mainly inhabited by people from Siena.<ref name=del473>Delli (1988), p. 473</ref>  At this end of the Via Giulia, a well-defined architectural development plan was drawn up, which started with building the [[palazzo Farnese|Farnese residence]]. In 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (lit. \"Beggar's Hospice\") was built by the architect [[Domenico Fontana]] on the orders of [[Pope Sixtus V]] (r. 1585-1590) and marked the end of the ''Via Giulia''.<ref name=pie7976/> It was built to solve the begging problem in the city and was given a yearly endowment of 150,000 ''[[roman scudo|scudi]]'' which could employ 2,000 people.<ref name=cas415>Castagnoli (1988), p. 415</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 16th century it had become fashionable for the various nations and city-states to have their own churches built in Rome known as the ''chiese nazionali''.<ref name=cas392/> The ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], along the [[procession]]al and pilgrim roads, were the preferred locations. The Florentines,  the Sienese, and the Neapolitans had their churches built in Via Giulia (the [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini|San Giovanni]], the [[Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia|Santa Caterina]], and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|Santo Spirito]] respectively),<ref name=del473/><ref name=pie16/> while the Bolognese ([[Santi Giovanni Evangelista e Petronio|San Giovanni e Petronio]]), Spanish ([[Santa Maria in Monserrato degli Spagnoli|Santa Maria in Monserrato]]), English ([[San Tommaso di Canterbury]]) and Swedish ([[Santa Brigida, Rome|Santa Brigida]]) churches were built in the Regola ''rione''.<ref name=cas392>Castagnoli (1958), p. 392</ref>\n\nIn order to supply the quarter with sufficient drinking water, [[Pope Paul V]] (r. 1605-1621) had the [[Aqua Paola]] extend over the Tiber. In 1613, the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'' (lit. \"The Big Fountain of the Sistine Bridge\") was built on the [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the beggars' hospice on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7978/> It was demolished in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the [[Ponte Sisto]] in what is now ''Piazza Trilussa''.[[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"300\" heights=\"300\">\n 1645 Antonio Tempesta Via Giulia marked.svg|Via Giulia; Particular from ''Almae urbis Romae prospectus'' by [[Antonio Tempesta]] (1645)\n</gallery>\nAt the end of the 16th century Via Giulia's path was fixed; it ended by the Florentine quarter to the north and the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' to the south. It became less of a major commercial street and more a busy promenade and a place for celebrations, processions (such as that of the ''ammantate'', poor girls which were dowried by the goldsmiths of [[Sant'Eligio degli Orefici]]) and races.<ref name=pie799>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 9</ref><ref name=pie7910/> \n\nIn 1603 Tiberio Ceuli held a [[Tournament (medieval)|tournament]] at Palazzo Sacchetti,<ref name=doc>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/ldpd_7219594_000/ldpd_7219594_000_djvu.txt|title=Documenti del Barocco Romano|p=58 [c440] (1)|language=it|access-date=5 March 2020|publisher=Miscellanea della R. Societ\u00e0 Romana di Storia Patria|editor=J. A. F. Orbaan|year=1920|location=Roma}}</ref> while in 1617 [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] organized a [[Saracen]] tournament at the ''Oratorio della Compagnia della Morte'', to which he invited eight cardinals.<ref name=gig118>Gigli (1958), p. 118</ref> During the summer months the street was sometimes flooded for the pleasure of the common people and the nobility.<ref name=pie7910>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 10</ref> One of the most glamorous celebrations was held by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1638 to celebrate the birth of the French [[Dauphin of France|dauphin]], the future king [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=pie7910/> Via Giulia hosted [[Water buffalo|buffalo]] races, parades of carnival [[Float (parade)|floats]], and in 1663 the organisation of a horse race with naked hunchbacks during [[Carnival]] is handed down.<ref name=pie798/> During the carnival, Via Giulia hosted several feasts promoted by the Florentines.<ref name=pie7910/>\nIn the [[baroque]] period, other important building projects contributed to the later appearance of the street: the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]],<ref name=pie16/> the ''Carceri Nuove'' (lit. \"New Prisons\"),<ref name=pie7913/> the [[Palazzo Falconieri]] <ref name=pie7944/>, and the churches of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani and [[Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome|Santa Maria del Suffragio]].<ref name=pie56>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 56</ref> The street's character changed little despite the addition of these buildings. Via Giulia was rather left out in Rome's general [[urban development]] plan.\n\n===Development in the 18th and 19th centuries===\nIn the 18th century the Via Giulia remained primarily a place to organise feasts: in 1720 the Sienese held a festival to celebrate the promotion of [[Marc'Antonio Zondadari]] to Grand Master of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of Malta]].<ref name=pie798/> [[Fireworks]] was set off near the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'';<ref name=pie7910/> two triumphal arches were raised above the street: one in Santo Spirito and the other near Palazzo Farnese;<ref name=pie798/><ref name=pie7910/> and the Fountain of the Mascherone poured wine for the people instead of water.<ref name=pie7910/>\n\nUnder [[Pope Clement XI]]'s (r. 1720-1721) rule, the beggars housed in the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' were transferred to the [[San Michele a Ripa]].<ref name=pie7980>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 80</ref> The building was occupied by both poor unmarried girls (''zitelle'' in the [[Romanesco dialect]]) and a congregation made up of 100 priests and 20 clerics; the latter prayed for the souls of deceased priests;<ref name=pie7980/> as such, the building was nicknamed the ''Ospizio dei cento preti'' (\"Hospice of the Hundred Priests\").<ref name=pie7980/>  \n\nIn the 19th century only a few new buildings or restoration projects were realised: among them were the youth prison (Palazzo del Gonfalone) (1825-27), the renovation of the Armenian Hospice next to the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] (1830), the new fa\u00e7ade of the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]] (1853), and the [[Collegio Spagnuolo]] (1853). However, this did not stop the general decline of the street that started in the middle of the 18th century.<ref name=del474>Delli (1988), p. 474</ref> The nobility abandoned the palaces on the street to move to the new center of urban life in the [[Campo Marzio (rione of Rome)|Campo Marzio]], and in their place the road hosted artisans and became less of a centre for festivities.<ref name=ber332>Bertarelli (1925), p. 332</ref>\n\n===Via Giulia since 1870===\nAfter Rome [[Capture of Rome|became the capital]] of the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1870, the Tiber (known for flooding, particularly in ''[[Campus Martius]]'') had its banks worked on in 1873 by constructing [[Lungotevere]]s, which since 1888 were erected along the road and required the church of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani to be torn down.<ref name=pie8110>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 10</ref> The Lungoteveres completely cut off Via Giulia from the Tiber and prevented the [[loggia]]s and gardens of the palaces facing the river, such as the Palazzi Medici-Clarelli, Sacchetti, Varese, and [[Palazzo Falconieri|Falconieri]] from having a view of the river.\nSignificant building demolitions during the fascist period left a large gap between ''Via della Barchetta'' and the ''Vicolo delle Prigioni'', which to this day has only been partially filled by the new building of the ''Liceo Classico Virgilio''.<ref name=pie791822>Pietrangeli (1979), pp. 18-22</ref> The street has regained its status as one of the most prestigious streets in the city.<ref name=nyt/><ref name=pie7910/>\nNumerous events took place in 2008 during its 500th anniversary; some churches and palaces were restored and opened to visitors.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/29/travel/29globe.html|title=A Stroll in Rome With a Papal Pedigree-Via Giulia celebrates its 500th birthday this year|author=Elisabeth Rosenthal|date=29 June 2008|access-date=8 March 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks on Via Giulia==\nVia Giulia extends northwest for about one kilometre from the Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti on the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Piazza dell'Oro in front of the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]. From 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (\"Beggars' Hospice\") marked the southern end of the street.<ref name=pie7976>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 76</ref> Under Paul V's decree in 1613, a fountain that brought the [[Aqua Paola]] to the [[Regola]] ''rione''  was built against its fa\u00e7ade (see engraving by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] above).<ref name=pie7978>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 78</ref> This fountain was demolished together with the hospice in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the Ponte Sisto in what is now Piazza Trilussa [[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n[[File:Via Giulia Roma.svg|400px|center|Map of via Giulia]]\n===1 Palazzina Pateras Pescara (Via Giulia 251)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Pal Pateras Pescara (Consulat de France).jpg|thumb|100px|1 Palazzo Pateras Pescara]]\nThis last building in Via Giulia was built in 1924 by [[Marcello Piacentini]] on behalf of the Avvocato Pateras.<ref name=pie7962>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 62</ref> Today it houses the Consulate of the French Republic in Rome.<ref name=pie7962/>\n===2 Fontana del Mascherone===\n[[File:Fontana del Mascherone Via Giulia.jpg|thumb|100px|2 Fontana del Mascherone]]\nThe fountain diagonally opposite [[Palazzo Farnese]] was built around 1626 by [[Carlo Rainaldi]] and paid for by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]].<ref name=pie7956>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 56</ref> It was planned in 1570 to be a public fountain fed by the ''[[Aqua Virgo]]'' [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] to supply people with clean drinking water.<ref name=pie7956/> However, installation was only possible after Paul V ordered the water pipe to be extended over the [[Ponte Sisto]] in 1612.<ref name=pie7956/><ref name=pie7958>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 58</ref> The fountain consists of an ancient large marble mask (\"Mascherone\") on a background with [[volute]]s in marble, crowned by the symbol of the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]], a metal [[Fleur-de-lis]].<ref name=pie7956/> The fountain was moved against the wall in 1903, losing most of its charm.<ref name=pie7956/> The poet [[Wilhelm Waiblinger]] died in 1830 in the house opposite to it [[:File:Via Giulia Sterbehaus Wilhelm Waiblinger.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===3 Palazzo Farnese (Via Giulia 186)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Farnese}}\n[[File:Palazzo Farnese Gartenseite.jpg|thumb|100px|3 Palazzo Farnese]]\nThe garden fa\u00e7ade of this palace building is oriented towards the Via Giulia. In 1549 it was designed according to [[Vignola]]'s drawings and completed by [[Giacomo della Porta]] in 1589.<ref name=cal213>Callari (1932), p. 213</ref> The garden between the fa\u00e7ade and the Via Giulia was once adorned by the [[Toro Farnese|Farnese bull]] (now in the [[National Archaeological Museum, Naples|National Archaeological Museum]] in [[Naples]]) [[:File:Farnese Bull MAN Napoli Inv6002 n01.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7956/> The palace is now the French Embassy in Italy.\n===3a Camerini Farnesiani (Via Giulia 253-260)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Camerini Farnesiani.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nBehind the row of lower buildings (\"Camerini Farnesiani\") [[:File:Via Giulia 253-260 Palazzetto Farnese.jpg|(Fig.)]], which today belong to the French Embassy, lay a small palace with garden, the Palazzetto Farnese, built around 1603 by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] as his [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]],<ref name=pie7954/> also known as ''Eremo del Cardinale'' (\"Cardinal's hermitage\"). This private retreat of the Cardinal, decorated with murals by [[Giovanni Lanfranco]], was accessible from Palazzo Farnese via a terrace and the Arco Farnese.<ref name=pie7954/> The building and garden was destroyed in the Tiber regulation after 1870.\n\n===4 Arco Farnese===\n[[File:Via Giulia Farnesebogen.jpg|thumb|100px|4 Arco Farnese]]\nThe bridge connects Via Giulia to the [[Palazzo Farnese]]. It was erected in 1603,<ref name=pie7954>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 54</ref> and was used to observe festive processions, games, and horse races in Via Giulia, particularly during [[Carnival]].\n===5 Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte===\n{{Main|Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte}}\nThe church, built in 1575-76, is located in the immediate vicinity of [[Palazzo Farnese]] and belonged to the ''Compagnia della Morte'' (\"Death's Brotherhood\") founded in 1538.<ref name=pie7948>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 48</ref> The fraternity was tasked with burying the dead that were recovered from the river or found in the [[Roman Campagna|area surrounding Rome]]. The building was demolished in 1733 and rebuilt by [[Ferdinando Fuga]] in 1737.<ref name=pie7950>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 50</ref> Its cemetery on the banks of the Tiber was demolished when the river was regulated in 1886.<ref name=pie7948/>\n===6 Palazzo Falconieri also Palazzo Odescalchi Falconieri (Via Giulia 1)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Falconieri}}\n[[File:Regola - via Giulia palazzo Falconieri facciata 1180066.JPG|thumb|100px|6 Palazzo Falconieri]]\nThe original building was built in the 16th century for the Roman noble family of the Ceci and directly adjoins the church of [[Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte]]. It was sold by the Ceci in 1574 to the [[Odescalchi family]] before being passed to the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1606. Eventually the Florentine nobleman [[Orazio Falconieri]] bought it in 1638 for 16,000 scudi.<ref name=pie7944>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 44</ref> From 1646 to 1649 he commissioned the architect [[Francesco Borromini]] to extend the palace.<ref name=pie7944/> The sides of the fa\u00e7ade on Via Giulia are decorated with two [[pilaster]]s in the shape of large [[herma]]s with female breasts and falcon heads.<ref name=pie7946>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 46</ref> The fa\u00e7ade on the [[Tiber]] side features a three-arched [[loggia]] <ref name=pie7946/> dating back to 1646. From 1814 Cardinal [[Joseph Fesch]], uncle of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] lived there, and from 1815 to 1818 he hosted his stepsister [[Laetitia Ramolino]], the emperor's mother.<ref name=pie7946/> In 1927 the Kingdom of Italy ceded the palace to the [[Hungary|Hungarian State]], which established it as the seat of the Hungarian Academy (Accademia d'ungheria). Today, in addition to the Academy, the palace is home to the Hungarian Embassy and the ''Pontificium Institutum Ecclesiasticum Hungaricum in Urbe''.\n\n===7 Palazzo Baldoca-Muccioli (Via Giulia 167)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Baldoca Muccioli.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe history of the palace is closely linked to the neighbouring Palazzo Cisterna.<ref name=pie7940/> Both properties were acquired by the sculptor [[Guglielmo della Porta]].<ref name=pie7940/> In 1540 [[Pope Paul III]] (r. 1534-1549) appointed him as his court artist and entrusted him with the interior decoration of Palazzo Farnese. The sculptor gave the building to the Baldoca family and then to the Muccioli. At the beginning of the 20th century the palace served as the residence of the English ambassador in Rome, Lord Rennel of Rodd, who bought and had it restored in 1928.<ref name=pie7940/>\n===8 Palazzo Cisterna (Via Giulia 163)===\n[[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Rom).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe Palazzo Cisterna was built by [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and served as his residence.<ref name=pie7940/> Above the [[architrave]] of the windows on the first floor the inscription '''FRANCISCVS TANCREDA ET GVILELMVS D(ella) P(orta) ME(ediolanensis) - S(culptor) CI(vis) RO(manus)''' can be read [[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Roma).jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7940/> From a letter to a friend, it appears that the palace was completed in 1575. In 1600 Spanish missionaries acquired the palace and sold it to the Cisterna family at the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=pie7940/> It was sold to the Ducci family in the middle of the 20th century.\n===9 Santa Caterina da Siena in Via Giulia===\n{{Main|Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia}}\n[[File:Regola - S. Caterina da Siena.JPG|thumb|100px|9 Santa Caterina]]\nThe history of this church is closely linked to the [[republic of Siena|Sienese]] Brotherhood.<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref> A community of merchants, bankers and craftsmen from Siena had been living in what was to be Via Giulia, where at that time stood the ''castrum Senense'' since the 14th century.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1519 the Brotherhood was canonically erected by Leo X.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1526 they commissioned [[Baldassare Peruzzi]] to build the church in honour of their saints, an [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]], and a house for the clerics.<ref name=pie7936/> The funds were provided by the Sienese nobility in Rome, particularly by Cardinal [[Giovanni Piccolomini]] and the banker [[Agostino Chigi]]. Since it was in a dilapidated state, it was rebuilt between 1766 and 1768 according to [[Paolo Posi]]'s designs,<ref name=pie7938>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 38</ref> while the interior decor was completed in 1775.<ref name=pie7938/> The [[Archconfraternity]] of the Sienese still owns the building today.<ref name=pie7940>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 40</ref> During Via Giulia's 500th anniversary of the street in 2008 the altarpiece was restored by Girolamo Genga.\n===10 Palazzo Varese (Via Giulia 14-21)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (1).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe palace opposite Santa Caterina da Siena was built between 1617 and 1618 by [[Carlo Maderno]] on behalf of Monsignor Diomede Varese.<ref name=pie7934>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 34</ref> In 1788 Monsignor Giuseppe degli Atti Varese gave the building to the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith|Congregation ''Propaganda Fide'']] when his family line died out.<ref name=pie7934/> After exchanging owners several times the palace finally came into the possession of the [[Mancini family]].<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref>\nThe front consists of two upper floors and a [[mezzanine]]. On the ground floor is the main [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and above it is a balcony on [[console (architecture)|console]]s, flanked by three windows each. A portal opens into the yard with three [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s stacked on one another [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (2).jpg|(Fig.)]]. The yard originally opened to a garden by the river.\n===11 Sant'Eligio degli Orefici (Via di Sant'Eligio 9)===\n{{Main|Sant'Eligio degli Orefici}}\n[[File:Sant' Eligio degli Orefici - Au\u00dfenansicht.jpg|thumb|100px|11 Sant\u2019Eligio]]\nThe small church is off the Via Giulia and serves as the guild church of the Roman gold- and silversmiths.<ref name=pie7930>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 30</ref> Its construction is attributed to [[Raphael]], although it is possible that after the death of the artist it was finished by [[Baldassare Peruzzi]].<ref name=pie7932>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 32</ref>\n===12 Palazzo del Collegio Spagnolo (Via Giulia 151)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Collegio Spagnolo.jpg|thumb|100px|12 Collegio Spagnolo]]\nThe ''Palacio de Monserrat'' by [[Pietro Camporese the Younger|Pietro Camporese]] and [[Antonio Sarti]] was built between 1848 and 1862 and is the Spanish Centre for Higher Ecclesiastical Studies today. The Centre is attached to the Spanish National Church of [[Santa Maria di Monserrato]] on Via di Monserrato behind it. Construction on Via Giulia stopped with the completion of this building complex in the 19th century.\n===13 Liceo Statale Virgilio (Via Giulia No 35 ff.)===\nOne of the most important state school complexes in Rome was built between 1936 and 1939 <ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref> by [[Marcello Piacentini]]. The building complex between Via Giulia and the [[Lungotevere dei Tebaldi]] includes the fa\u00e7ade of [[Palazzo Ghislieri]] [[:File:Via Giulia Collegio Ghisleri.jpg|(Fig.)]], designed by [[Carlo Maderno]] (16th century), and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|church of the Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]].\n===14 Palazzo Ricci (Via Giulia 146)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe present building was originally a cluster of unconnected buildings, built at different times, opposite the Collegio Ghislieri.<ref name=pie7928>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 28</ref> The building complex was merged in 1634 and 1683. The main fa\u00e7ade facing Piazza de'Ricci shows strongly faded remains of a ''[[Graffito (drawing technique)|graffito]]'' by [[Polidoro da Caravaggio]] (16th century). On the side facing Via Giulia, a continuous fa\u00e7ade gave the complex its present uniform appearance [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===15 Santo Spirito dei Napoletani===\n{{Main|Santo Spirito dei Napoletani}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santo Spirito dei Napoletani 1.jpg|thumb|100px|15 Sto. Spirito dei Napoletani]]\nIn the [[Pius V]] catalogue this church is listed under the name of ''Santa Aura in strada Iulia''.<ref name=arm423>Armellini (1891), p. 423</ref> It was dedicated to [[Aurea of Ostia|Saint Aurea]], the patron saint of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]].<ref name=arm423/> A nunnery was attached to the church.<ref name=arm423/> In 1439 the church was restored at the expense of Cardinal [[Guillaume d'Estouteville]].<ref name=arm423/> In 1572 Cardinal Inigo d'Avalos founded in the dilapidated building the ''Confraternita dello Spirito Santo dei Napoletani'' (\"Brotherhood of the Holy Spirit of the Neapolitans\"), who bought it from the nuns in 1574.<ref name=pie7924>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 24</ref> Between 1619 and 1650 a new building was erected, with a project of [[Ottavio Mascherino]] and a fa\u00e7ade by [[Cosimo Fanzago]].<ref name=pie7924/> It was dedicated to the Holy Spirit.<ref name=pie7924/> In the following centuries it was renovated several times, at the beginning of the 18th century by [[Carlo Fontana]] <ref name=pie7924/> and in the middle of the 19th century the fa\u00e7ade was renovated by Antonio Cipolla (1853).<ref name=pie7926>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 26</ref> It was the National Church of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]. The last [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|King of Naples]] [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] and his wife [[Maria Sophie of Bavaria|Marie Sophie Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]], were buried in the church in 1942.<ref name=pie7926/><ref name=del475>Delli (1988), p. 475</ref> After a long period of restoration, the church is open to the public again since 1986. [[:File:Santo Spirito dei Napoletani (Inneres).jpg|(Fig.)]]\n===16 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia===\n[:File:Via Giulia Oratorio San Filippo Neri.jpg|(Fig.)]]\n{{Main|San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\nConstruction of the small church opposite the Carceri Nuove was sponsored by Rutilio Brandi, a glove-maker from Florence, and given to the ''Compagnia delle santissime piaghe'' around 1600. The church was originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> It was connected to a residence for unmarried girls (''zitelle'') and a hospital for sick priests.<ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The church was dedicated to [[San Filippo Neri]] after the saint's death.<ref name=pie7916/> In 1728 [[Filippo Raguzzini]] restored the church on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730).<ref name=pie7918/> The church barely escaped destruction in the early 1940s due to the construction of a large road that should have joined [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]].<ref name=pie7918/> This road was never built due to the [[World War II]].<ref name=pie7918/> It was abandoned after the war before being restored for non-religious purposes.\n\n===17 Carceri Nuove (Via Giulia 52)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove 1.jpg|thumb|100px|17 Carceri Nuove]]\nSince 1430 the [[Savelli family]] had a monopoly on prisons in the city, especially ''Corte Savella'' at 42 Via di Monserrato. The inhumane penal system in the Corte Savella caused [[Pope Innocent X]] (r. 1644-1655)) to withdraw the Savelli's monopoly on the penal system in Rome. As a sign of new ''Justitia Papalis'', he had the new penal institution, the ''Carceri Nuove'', built in Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> This new prison was built between 1652 and 1655 by the architect Antonio del Grande.<ref name=pie7913/><ref>Inscription above the portal: IUSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE SECURIORI AC MITlORI REORUM CUSTODIAE NOVUM CARCEREM INNOCENTIUS X PONT. MAX. POSUIT ANNO DOMINI MDCLV (''Innocent X. P.M. built the new prison in the year of the Lord 1655, for justice, leniency for the safe and humane custody of convicts'')</ref> The Carceri Nuove were considered a model of a humane penitentiary system in their time. The building and its purpose had a rather negative influence on the image of the magnificent street, which led to the suspension of construction in the following years and the [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] character of the street being preserved. The building acted as a prison until the opening of [[Regina Coeli]] in [[Trastevere]] <ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> in 1883, further on until 1931 as a youth prison.<ref name=pie7914/> From 1931 the palace housed the headquarters of the ''Centro di Studi Penitenziari'' (\"Research Institute for Criminal Justice\") and a specialized library.<ref name=pie7914/> Today the building houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Directorate for Anti-Mafia and Anti-Terrorism\").\n\n===17a Palazzo del Gonfalone===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Museo Criminologico.jpg|thumb|100px|17a Palazzo del Gonfalone]]\nThe building between the Vicolo della Scimia and Via del Gonfalone has no entrance from Via Giulia.<ref name=pie64/> It was built between 1825 and 1827 under [[Pope Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) according to plans by [[Giuseppe Valadier]] as a prison for the youth.<ref name=pie64>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 64</ref> Today the building houses the ''Museo Criminologico'' (lit. \"Criminological Museum\").<ref name=pie66>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 66</ref>\n===18 Santa Maria del Suffragio===\n{{Main|Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santa Maria del Suffragio.jpg|thumb|100px|18 S.M. del Suffragio]]\nIn 1592 the ''Confraternita del Suffragio'' (\"Brotherhood of Intercession\") was founded next to the church of [[San Biagio della Pagnotta]] to implore the intercession for the souls of the purgatory.<ref name=pie56/> The Brotherhood was approved by [[Pope Clement VIII]] (r. 1592-1605) in 1594 <ref name=pie56/> and was elevated to the status of ''Arciconfaternita'' (\"Archbishopric Brotherhood\") by [[Paul V]] in 1620. Thanks to several donations, in 1662 the erection of the church began as a project of architect [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie56/> The building was consecrated in 1669, and the fa\u00e7ade was finished in 1680.<ref name=pie56/> The church's interior was renovated in 1869; the frescoes inside the church are by [[Cesare Mariani]] (''[[Coronation of the Virgin]]'') and [[Giuseppe Chiari]] (''[[Nativity of Mary]]'' and ''[[Adoration of the Magi]]'').<ref name=pie58>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 58</ref>\n===19 Palazzo dei Tribunali===\n[[File:Via Giulia Sof\u00e0 (Palazzo dei Tribunali) 1.jpg|thumb|100px|19 Sof\u00e0]]\n[[Julius II]]'s most important planned project in the new street was a central administration building, in which a large part of the city's important offices and courts (\"tribunali\") were to be grouped together.<ref name=pie50/> The Pope's commission to [[Donato Bramante]] (at the time main architect of the new St. Peter's Basilica)<ref name=pie50/> was issued around 1506, and construction in the area between ''Vicolo del Cefalo'' and ''Via del Gonfalone'' began before 1508,<ref name=pie50/> but was interrupted as in 1511 by the ''Pax Romana''.<ref name=tem124/> With the [[Julius II]]'s death in 1513, construction completely stopped. [[Giorgio Vasari]] wrote:\n{{quote|''Onde Bramante diede principio al palazzo ch'a San Biagio su 'l Tevere si vede, nel quale \u00e8 ancora un tempio corinzio non finito, cosa molto rara, et il resto del principio di opera rustica bellissimo che \u00e8 stato gran danno che una s\u00ec onorata et utile e magnifica opra non si sia finita, ch\u00e9 da quelli della professione \u00e8 tenuto il pi\u00f9 bello ordine che si sia visto mai in quel genere.''}}\n{{quote|Bramante therefore began the construction of the palace, which can be seen near San Biagio on the Tiber. In it there is still an unfinished [[corinthian order|Corinthian]] temple, something very rare and the remains of the beginning in beautiful ''[[Rustication (architecture)|Opera Rustica]]''. It is a great pity that such an important, useful and great project has remained unfinished. Experts considered it to be the most beautiful building of its kind ever seen.}} <ref name=vasBra/><ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref><ref name=pie52/>\nSome remains of the mighty [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] walls, called ''sof\u00e0'' by the Roman population, between Via del Gonfalone and Vicolo del Cefalo along Via Giulia, can be seen today.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===20 San Biagio della Pagnotta (San Biagio degli Armeni)===\n{{Main|San Biagio della Pagnotta}}\n[[File:Via Giulia San Biagio della Pagnotta.jpg|thumb|100px|20 San Biagio]]\nThis church was dedicated to [[Saint Blaise]] of [[Sivas|Sebaste]] and is mentioned in the church catalogues of the Middle Ages under the name of ''San Biagio de Cantu Secuta''.<ref name=pie52>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 52</ref> The name \"della pagnotta\" is derived from the Roman word ''pagnotta'' (\"bread roll\"), which was distributed to the faithful on the 3 February (feast of St. Blaise) and thought to protect against throat illnesses.<ref name=pie54>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 54</ref> The church was attached to one of the first abbeys in Rome.<ref name=pie52/> An inscription on the interior commemorates the construction of the church by an abbot Dominicus in 1072.<ref name=arm356>Armellini (1891), p. 356</ref> According to the Bramante's plans, this church was to be included in the construction of the Palazzo dei Tribunali. From 1539 to 1835 it was a [[parish]] church.<ref name=pie54/> In 1826 [[Pope Gregory XVI]] (r. 1831-1846) assigned the church to the [[Armenian people|Armenian]] community of Santa Maria Egiziaca.<ref name=pie54/> Since then it has been called officially ''San Biagio degli Armeni''.<ref name=pie52/>\n===21 Palazzo Ricci-Donarelli (Via Giulia no. 99-105)===\nThe palace is opposite to the Palazzo Sacchetti and was originally a group of residential buildings that first belonged to the [[Ricci family|Ricci]] and later to the Donarelli family.<ref name=pie48>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 48</ref>  The complex was restructured in 1663, possibly by [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref>\n===22 Palazzo Sacchetti (Via Giulia 66)===\n[[File:Palazzo Sacchetti Via Giulia (Rom).jpg|thumb|100px|22 Palazzo Sacchetti]]\n[[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]] built the palace on land bought in 1542 by the Vatican Chapter.<ref name=pie40>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 40</ref> The fa\u00e7ade still bears the chipped [[coat of arms]] of Paul III.<ref name=pie40/> His son Orazio inherited the building and sold it in 1552 to Cardinal [[Giovanni Ricci (bishop)|Giovanni Ricci]] di [[Montepulciano]], who had the palace extended to its current dimensions by the architect [[Nanni di Baccio Bigio]].<ref name=pie40/> An inscription<ref>Inscription [[:File:Ponte - via Giulia palazzo Sacchetti - domus Antonii Sangalli architecti 1160658.JPG|(Fig.)]] on the fa\u00e7ade: DOMVS/ANTONII/SANGALLI/ARCHITECTI/MDLIII (house of the architect Antonio Sangallo 1553)</ref> in the Vicolo del Cefalo's side wall states that the palace was exempted from paying the census tax in 1555.[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Sacchetti Zensus 1555.jpg|(Fig.)]]<ref name=pie46/> The building changed hands several times.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie42>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 42</ref> In 1649 it was bought by the Florentine [[Sacchetti family]], whose name it still bears.<ref name=pie42/> The entrance to Via Giulia is made of marble and flanked on both sides by three large windows with grilles, thresholds, and cornices.<ref name=pie44>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 44</ref> In the left corner of the palace there is a small fountain [[:File:Palazzo Sacchetti Delfinbrunnen.jpg|(Fig.)]] flanked by [[caryatid]]es with two dolphins embedded in the wall;<ref name=pie44/> this refers to the later owners, the Ceuli family, whose coat of arms was chipped.<ref name=pie44/> Notable features inside include the ''Salone dei Mappamondi'' (\"Hall of World Maps\"), designed by [[Francesco de' Rossi (Il Salviati)|Francesco Salviati]],<ref name=pie46>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 46</ref> and the dining room with two [[fresco]]es designed by [[Pietro da Cortona]].<ref name=pie46/> The writer [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] lived in this palazzo in 1973 and died on 17 October 1973.\n===23 Palace with the Farnese coat of arms (Via Giulia 93)===\n[[File:Via Giulia (Rom);Palast mit den Farnese Wappen.jpg|thumb|100px|23 Palazzo with the Farnese coat of arms]]\nThe building is attributed to [[Giacomo della Porta]]. The palazzo takes its name from the three coats of arms of the [[Farnese family]], which were added to the fa\u00e7ade under Paul III. In the centre of the upper floor there is the coat of arms of [[Paul III]] with the papal [[tiara]] and the keys between two [[unicorn]]s. On the left is the coat of arms of Cardinal [[Alessandro Farnese (cardinal)|Alessandro Farnese]] and on the right the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma and Piacenza]] [[Ranuccio I Farnese]].\n===24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Via Giulia 79)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli.jpg|thumb|100px|24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli]]\nAntonio da Sangallo the Younger built this palace as a private residence around 1535-1536.<ref name=pie34>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 34</ref> After Sangallo's death in 1546 the building was owned by the Florentine Migliore Cresci.<ref name=pie34/> An inscription above the main portal [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Inschrift).jpg|(Fig.)]] immortalizes Duke [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]].<ref name=pie34/> The palace for some time belonged to the Tuscan Consulate in Rome.<ref name=pie34/> At the end of the 17th century it was acquired by the Marini Clarelli family. In the 19th century it was used as barracks before being sold to the city of Rome in 1870. The fa\u00e7ade and the portal are lined with rusticated [[ashlar]]s.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> On the sides of the portal there are badly rebuilt large windows on [[Console (architecture)|consoles]].<ref name=pie36/>\n===25 Casa di Raffaello (via Giulia 85)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Casa di Raffaello.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThis palace, erroneously called the House of [[Raphael]], was built after 1525 for the [[Vatican Hill|Vatican]] [[Chapter (religion)|Chapter]] according to a design by the architect Bartolomeo de Ramponibus.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> Raphael originally acquired several plots of land here.<ref name=pie36/> However, he died before the building's construction began. The designs were created by Rafael and Antonio da Sangallo the Younger.<ref name=pie36/> An inscription above the windows of the first floor is dedicated to Raphael: '''POSSEDEVA RAF SANZIO NEL MDXX'''.<ref name=pie36/>\n===26 Quarter of the Florentines===\nIn 1448 Florentine merchants who resided in Rome founded the ''Compagnia della Piet\u00e0'', akin to the Florentine \"Misericordia\".<ref name=pie14>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 14</ref> Both Popes from the [[Medici family]], Leo X and [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] (r. 1523-1534), promoted the influx of Florentines. Since 1515 the Commune of Florence had its own consulate in a palace on ''Via del Consolato''  that was erected in 1541 and demolished in 1888 to build [[Corso Vittorio Emanuele]].<ref name=pie26>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 26</ref> It had its own laws, its own court, and its own prison. Some of the buildings erected towards the end of the 15th century that once belonged to Florentines [[:File:Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (0).jpg|(Fig.)]] are still preserved across from the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]:<ref name=pie24>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 24</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" \"=\"\">\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (1).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (2).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (4).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n</gallery>\n===27 San Giovanni dei Fiorentini===\n{{Main|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini}}\n[[File:San Giovanni dei Fiorentini (Roma).jpg|thumb|200px|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]\nIn 1519 the \"nation\" of the Florentines received the privilege to build a parish church in honour of [[John the Baptist]] from Leo X .<ref name=pie16>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 16</ref> The church stands at the northern end of ''Via Giulia'' in the Florentine quarter.<ref name=pie16/> The church reflects the grandeur and the political self-image of the [[Medici family]], who owned a palazzo right next to the church. It is the largest church on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie16/> It combined the efforts of three of Rome's master builders: [[Giacomo della Porta]], [[Carlo Maderno]], and [[Francesco Borromini]].<ref name=pie16/> The last two artists [[burial|interred]] in the same tomb at the church.<ref name=pie20>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 20</ref> The altarpiece, started by [[Pietro da Cortona]], was continued by Borromini and finished by [[Ciro Ferri]].<ref name=pie20/>\n\n==Trivia==\n[[\u00c9mile Zola]], who visited Rome from 1894 to 1896, gave a description of Via Giulia and Palazzo Sacchetti (Palazzo Boccanera) in his [[travel literature|travelogue]].<ref>\u00c9mile Zola: ''Les trois villes \u2013 Rome''; Volume I, Cap. 3,II; Parigi 1896</ref>\n==References==\n<references/>\n== Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giorgio Vasari\n | authorlink=Giorgio Vasari\n | title=Le vite de\u2019 pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori italiani, da Cimabue insino a' tempi nostri\n | publisher=Giunti\n | location=Firenze\n | year=1568\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giacinto Gigli\n | title = Diario romano, 1608-1670\n | location= Roma\n | publisher= Staderini\n | year= 1958\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Vittorio Bertarelli\n | publisher=Touring Club Italiano\n | location=Milano\n | year=1925\n | title=Roma e dintorni\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Callari\n | title=I Palazzi di Roma\n | publisher=Ugo Sofia-Moretti\n | location=Roma\n | year=1932\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|authorlink1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|author2=Carlo Cecchelli|author3=Gustavo Giovannoni|author4=Mario Zocca| title=Topografia e urbanistica di Roma|publisher=Cappelli|location=Bologna|year=1958|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Paolo Portoghesi\n | authorlink=Paolo Portoghesi\n | title=Roma del Rinascimento\n | publisher=Electa\n | location = Milano\n | ISSN=\n | year=1970\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Ponte (IV)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=3\n | year=1981\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n |author=Sergio Delli\n |title=Le strade di Roma\n |publisher=Newton & Compton\n |location=Roma\n |year=1988\n |language=it\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Laura Gigli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Borgo (I)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | year=1990\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Nicholas Temple\n | title=Renovatio Urbis; Architecture, urbanism and ceremony in the Rome of Julius II\n | publisher=Routledge\n | location=New York\n | year=2011\n | ISBN=978-0-203-81848-0\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Luigi Salerno|author-link=Luigi Salerno |author2=Luigi Spezzaferro |author3=Manfredo Tafuri|title=Via Giulia: una utopia urbanistica del 500|location=Rome|publisher=Staderini|year=1973}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Via Giulia (Roma)|Via Giulia}}\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/index.html#sommario Vincenzo Morelli, ''Omaggio a Via Giulia'']\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/storia.html ''La storia di Via Giulia'']\n\n{{coord|41.8942|N|12.4701|E|source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Rome|Giulia]]\n[[Category:1508 establishments in the Papal States]]\n[[Category:Renaissance architecture in Rome]]\n[[Category:Rome R. VII Regola]]\n[[Category:Rome R. V Ponte]]\n", "name_user": "Alessandro57", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Via Giulia 79)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Via_Giulia"}
{"title_page": "Mark Ward (footballer, born 1982)", "text_new": "{{About|the English footballer born 1982|the English footballer of the same name born 1962|Mark Ward (footballer, born 1962)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n'''Mark Ward''' (born 27 January 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=24729|title=Mark Ward|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref> is an English [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Belper Town F.C.|Belper Town]]. He is the current assistant manager of [Buxton Town fc]\n\nHe began his career with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], where he made two appearances in the [[Football League Championship]] before being released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/sheffutd/sheffutd.html|title=Sheffield United: 1946/47\u20132006/07|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database\n|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref> He has since gone on to play for [[Non-League football|non-League]] teams [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]], [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]], [[Frickley Athletic F.C.|Frickley Athletic]] and [[Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C.|Stocksbridge Park Steels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stocksbridgepsfc.com/playerdetails.php?players_id=29|title=Mark Ward|publisher=Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C.|accessdate=2007-12-19}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Mark}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Worksop Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Frickley Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hucknall Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Belper Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northern Premier League players]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Mansfield managers]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1980s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the English footballer born 1982|the English footballer of the same name born 1962|Mark Ward (footballer, born 1962)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n'''Mark Ward''' (born 27 January 1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=24729|title=Mark Ward|publisher=Soccerbase|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref> is an English [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Belper Town F.C.|Belper Town]]. He is the current assistant manager of [[Hednesford Town F.C.|Hednesford Town]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], where he made two appearances in the [[Football League Championship]] before being released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/sheffutd/sheffutd.html|title=Sheffield United: 1946/47\u20132006/07|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database\n|accessdate=2007-12-19}}</ref> He has since gone on to play for [[Non-League football|non-League]] teams [[Worksop Town F.C.|Worksop Town]], [[Hucknall Town F.C.|Hucknall Town]], [[Frickley Athletic F.C.|Frickley Athletic]] and [[Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C.|Stocksbridge Park Steels]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stocksbridgepsfc.com/playerdetails.php?players_id=29|title=Mark Ward|publisher=Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C.|accessdate=2007-12-19}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Mark}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stocksbridge Park Steels F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Worksop Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Frickley Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hucknall Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Belper Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northern Premier League players]]\n[[Category:A.F.C. Mansfield managers]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1980s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c7:2d00:c100:fd64:2889:1a74:19f9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Ward_(footballer,_born_1982)"}
{"title_page": "Goshen College", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name          = Goshen College\n| image         = Seal-solid-black.png\n| image_size    = 160px\n| caption       = <br /> The Seal of Goshen College\n| motto         = ''Culture for Service''\n| type          = [[private university|Private]] [[liberal arts college]]\n| endowment     = [[United States dollar|$]]112,179,000 (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=2017-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| established   = September 21, 1894<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Goshen College| last = Fisher Miller| first = Susan| title = Culture for Service : A History of Goshen College, 1894\u20131994| location = Goshen, IN| date = 1994|page=11}}</ref>\n| faculty       = 71<ref name=\"NCES\">{{cite web|title=College Navigator \u2013 Goshen College|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=150668|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|date=June 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| president     = Rebecca Stoltzfus\n| city          = [[Goshen, Indiana|Goshen]]\n| state         = [[Indiana]]\n| country       = United States\n| coor          = {{coord|41.5637|-85.8272|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students      = 950<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| undergrad     = 883<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| postgrad      = 67<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| campus        = [[Town|Large town]]: {{convert|135|acre}}, 1,189-[[acre]] natural sanctuary [[Merry Lea]]<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\">{{cite web|title=Quick Facts \u2013 About Goshen College|url=https://www.goshen.edu/about/quick-facts/|publisher=Goshen College|date=June 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| nickname      = Maple Leafs\n| colors        = Purple and White<ref>{{cite web|title=Graphic Standards\u2013A quick reference|url=https://www.goshen.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/61/2013/01/standards_guide_2015-1.pdf|publisher=Goshen College|date=2015|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><br />{{color box|#49176d}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| athletics     = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] Division II \u2013 [[Crossroads League]]\n| sports        = 14 varsity sports teams<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" />\n| mascot        = Maple Leaf\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Mennonite Church USA]]\n| website       = {{URL|www.goshen.edu}}\n| logo          =\n}}\n\n'''Goshen College''' is a private [[liberal arts college]] in [[Goshen, Indiana]]. It was founded in 1894 as the '''Elkhart Institute of Science, Industry and the Arts''', and is affiliated with [[Mennonite Church USA]]. The college is [[school accreditation|accredited]] by the ]]Higher Learning Commission]]. Goshen has an enrollment of 950 students.<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" /> While Goshen maintains a distinctive liberal Mennonite worldview, it admits students of all religions. [[Mennonite]]s make up 43 percent of the student body.<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" />\n\nGoshen College is home to ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]'' and the [[Mennonite Historical Library]], a research library compiling one of the world's most comprehensive collection of [[Anabaptist]] and Mennonite primary source material.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| publisher = American Historical Association| title = Mennonite Historical Library| encyclopedia = American Historical Association Archives Wiki| date = 2013-05-17| url = http://archiveswiki.historians.org/index.php/Mennonite_Historical_Library}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe history of Goshen College (or Goshen, as it is commonly known) is intertwined with that of the history of Mennonites in America,{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} and so Goshen's history is best told in the context of this broader history.{{according to whom|date=August 2016}}{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} \"Old\" Mennonites had traditionally been suspicious of higher education, but by the late 19th century, opinion started to change.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Decades earlier, [[mainline Protestant]] church denominations had begun to found colleges across America, with the hope of developing well-trained clergy for their congregations.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} As more \"Old\" Mennonites sent their children to other Christian colleges, they realized that, without a college of their own, many of their youth would leave the church.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Thus, prompted in part as a reaction to mainline Christianity, the \"Old\" Mennonites started the Elkhart Institute in [[Elkhart, Indiana]] in August 1894, to prepare Mennonite youth for college.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Today,{{when|date=April 2017}} Goshen is open to everyone, but this earlier vision and its historical relationship with the Mennonite Church remains visible: it is home to ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]'', [[Mennonite Historical Library]], [[Mennonite Church USA Archives]], including Mennonite Central Committee archives, offices of \"The Mennonite\", and it has numerous alumni connections with the broader Mennonite Church.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen was the first Mennonite school of higher education in North America to confer a four-year degree.{{according to whom|date=April 2017}}{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}<ref>[[Bethel College (Kansas)|Bethel College]], which was incorporated in 1887 and opened at its present site in 1893, is older, but did not originally grant four-year degrees.{{Original research inline|date=April 2017}}{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}</ref>  H.A. Mumaw, a practicing physician, first led the small operation; in 1894, a group of 15 \"Old\" Mennonite ministers and laymen started a corporation that they named the Elkhart Institute association.<ref>Schlabach, Theron F: ''Peace, Faith, Nation: Mennonites and Amish in Nineteenth Century America'', page 300. Herald Press, 1988</ref>  The first diploma was awarded in 1898.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Lured by businessmen to relocate several miles away to [[Goshen, Indiana]], the Institute moved in September 1903 and added a junior college course list, renaming itself Goshen College.{{when|date=April 2017}}{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} By 1906, the Mennonite Board of Education had taken control of the college, dissolving the Elkhart Institute Association.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} A complete college course was established in 1908, and the first Bachelor of Arts degrees were conferred in 1910.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} After 1910, most of Goshen's students were enrolled in college courses. From 1914 to 1919, partly out of response to its constituents, Goshen College attempted a \"School of Agriculture,\" which sought to prepare Mennonite young people to return to their rural communities; the hope was that such a program would spark a technological revolution among some of the farmers, but it was never a success and was cut after [[World War I]], five years after it began.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} The college-prep academy program of Goshen College was discontinued in 1935.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe school was closed during the 1923\u20131924 school year by the Mennonite Board of Education but reopened the following year. One of many factors in closing the college was denominational tension due to [[Liberal Christianity|modernist]] and [[Christian fundamentalism|fundamentalist Christian]] theologies of the 1920s and their impact on Mennonite theology at the school.<ref>Juhnke, James C: ''Vision, Doctrine, War: Mennonite Identity and Organization in America 1890\u20131930'', page 128. Herald Press, 1989</ref> In response to this crisis, many of Goshen's faculty and dozens of students, angry with the Mennonite Board of Education's decision, relocated to [[Bluffton University|Bluffton College]]. As part of the larger ongoing reaction against liberalism through the early 20th century, [[Hesston College]] and [[Eastern Mennonite University|Eastern Mennonite School]] were formed among \"Old\" Mennonites, although staunch traditionalists realized that no higher education was particularly safe.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nWhen the institution was reopened, it was marked by the new leadership of president [[Sanford Calvin Yoder|S.C. Yoder]] and dean [[Harold S. Bender|Noah Oyer,]] who manifested outstanding abilities. His character was one marked by simplicity, modesty, and refinement, as well as unusual wisdom and insight. Under his leadership the educational program of the College developed rapidly, and much of the strength of the present college program is due to his untiring and wise endeavors. After dean Oyer\u2019s untimely passing in 1931, Harold Bender became dean. He was a man whose influence upon the \"Old\" Mennonites was significant for much of the 20th century. Bender carefully piloted the stormy waters of theology by stating that [[Mennonitism]] was not [[liberalism]]. Bender later went on to say that [[fundamentalism]] also contributed to problems with theology and created ''[[The Anabaptist Vision]]'', a \"third way\" that sought to spell out the direction for the future Mennonite Church. More than arguing doctrine, Bender and a younger group of intellectuals at Goshen College sought to shape the Mennonite faith that was more ideological than institutional. The goal was to articulate a faith that could stand the test of academic scrutiny in broader society while carefully upholding traditional beliefs of the church. Out of this ideology, Bender started ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]''. Throughout this time, Goshen remained the epicenter of \"Old\" Mennonite theology and higher education, and became known as the \"Goshen Historical Renaissance\".<ref>Toews, Paul: ''Mennonites in American Society, 1930\u20131970: Modernity and the Persistence of Religious Community'', page 88. Herald Press, 1996</ref>\n\nDuring the 1940s, Goshen was one of the [[Mennonite Central Committee]]'s key places to form a \"relief training school\" that helped to train volunteers for unpaid jobs in the [[Civilian Public Service]], an alternative to the Army. Many Mennonites chose the civilian service alternative because of their beliefs regarding Biblical pacifism and nonresistance.  Although the young women pacifists were not liable to the draft, they volunteered for unpaid Civilian Public Service jobs to demonstrate their patriotism; many worked in mental hospitals.<ref>Rachel Waltner Goossen, ''Women Against the Good War: Conscientious Objection and Gender on the American Home Front, 1941\u20131947'' (1997) pp 98-111</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the college was granted care of [[Merry Lea Environmental Center|Merry Lea Environmental Learning Center]], a {{convert|1150|acre|km2|adj=mid}} nature preserve that now offers Goshen's master's degree in Environmental Science.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nIn 1993, Harold and Wilma Good, longtime friends of the college, left their estate to Goshen. The estate was estimated at roughly $28 million, the majority in stock of the [[Smuckers|J.M. Smucker Company]]. Wilma was a daughter of the company's founder. The college sold the stock and added the funds to its endowment, more than doubling it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mennoweekly.org/JUNE/06-19-06/ENDOWMENTS06-19.html |title=Mennonite college endowments lag behind |publisher=Mennonite Weekly Review |year=2006 |accessdate=2008-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021020/http://www.mennoweekly.org/JUNE/06-19-06/ENDOWMENTS06-19.html |archivedate=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe campus experienced a building boom in the later half of the 1990s through the present, with an estimated $30 million in new or renovated structures on campus. This included the addition of the Roman Gingerich Recreation-Fitness Center, the Music Center, the Connector, and the renovation of all dormitories. The college is currently working on a new campus master plan and strategic plan that will define the college's priorities for the years ahead. Today, more than 20,000 Goshen College alumni have been counted, residing in more than 85 countries. The Goshen campus has flourished from less than {{convert|50|acre|m2}} to {{convert|135|acre|km2}} with 18 major buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/aboutgc/history.php |title=History of Goshen College |publisher=Goshen College |accessdate=2008-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225641/http://www.goshen.edu/aboutgc/history.php |archivedate=2007-09-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nGoshen College offers 41 majors and 47 minors for undergraduates.<ref name=\"Majors and Minors\">{{cite web|title=Majors and Minors|url=http://www.goshen.edu/academics/majors-minors/|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>  Some of the most popular programs are nursing, biology, business, communication, education, [[American Sign Language]] and environmental science. The college also offers a [[Master of Arts]] in Environmental Education, a master's degree in intercultural leadership, and a master's degree in nursing with two tracks: family nurse practitioner and clinical nurse leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/news/pressarchive/10-11-06-enviro-ed.html |title=Goshen College to launch first master's degree program, in environmental education |website=Goshen.edu |date=2006-10-11 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref> In 2014, Goshen College partnered with Eastern Mennonite University and Bluffton University to launch the Collaborative MBA program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emu.edu/now/news/2014/03/unique-collaborative-mba-program-launched-from-platform-of-three-mennonite-institutions/ |title=Unique Collaborative MBA program launched from platform of three Mennonite institutions \u2013 EMU News &#124; Eastern Mennonite University |website=Emu.edu |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year is divided into two semester terms, with an additional May term.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Study-Service Term ===\n\nIntercultural education is a requirement for all students at Goshen College.  To fulfill the requirement, students will either spend a semester abroad or complete an intercultural experience in the [[United States]].  Goshen College's ''Study-Service Term'' (SST) is a program which approximately 80 percent of students participate in to complete their intercultural study requirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/intercultural-requirement/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 Intercultural Requirement|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref> Students typically study the language and culture for six weeks, usually in the capital city, then do some sort of service work in a more remote area for the remaining six weeks. Service may include working at a hospital, nursing home, [[Guadeloupe|kindergarten]], or missionary service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/destinations/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 What is SST?|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref> The college has in the past also offered a domestic SST to immerse students in the Latino culture and community in northern Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/destinations/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 Destinations|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2017}}\n\n=== Clubs and organizations ===\n[[File:Beach volleyball @ Goshen.JPG|thumb|left|260px|Goshen College intramural volleyball]]\nGoshen College has no official fraternities or sororities, however, many different types of clubs and organizations exist to help facilitate campus life.  Clubs that play a significant part in campus life include: Black Student Union (BSU), Latino Student Union (LSU), International Student Club (ISC), Advocates, GC Players, Nursing Student Association, Hymn Club, Voices and Harmony, Social Work Action Association (SWAA), Art Club, Pre-Med Club, Goshen Student Women's Association (GSWA), PAX and Eco-PAX.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nCampus Activities Council, or CAC, is the primary extracurricular organization on campus that hosts a variety of weekend activities and events. CAC is responsible for \"Kick Off,\" a talent show held at the beginning of the fall semester. CAC also hosts \"Hour After\" shows, where talented students on campus perform music, comedy, or dancing for the audience.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==== International students ====\nThe International Students Club (ISC) hosts the Coffeehouse every year, an event during which international students demonstrate their artistic talents. Students are also given the opportunity, through Global Citizenship, to individually talk about their culture, and have it published by the Goshen College newspaper.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==== Intramural athletics ====\nIntramural athletics are also offered.  Throughout the year, students can participate in the coed sports of outdoor soccer, volleyball, sand volleyball, kickball, touch football, ultimate frisbee, and wiffleball, as well as basketball, indoor soccer, and 3-on-3 basketball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intramurals|url=https://www.goshen.edu/campuslife/intramurals/|website=Goshen College|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Media ===\n\nGoshen College has its own school newspaper, ''The Record'' and its own radio station, [[WGCS]], branded as 91.1FM The Globe. On March 12, 2011, The Globe was named the Best College Station in the Nation, winning first place at the 71st Annual Conference of the Intercollegiate Broadcasting System (IBS) in New York City. On March 2, 2013, The Globe was again named Best College Station in the Nation, making it the first college to win the award twice. Since then, 91.1 the Globe has been awarded \"Radio Station of the Year\" by the Indiana Association of State Broadcasters six time, their most recent in March of 2020.\nGlobe Media also produces a monthly news show, \"The Globe News Report\", which covers campus and community news, along with a weekly sports show, \"The Globe Sports Corner\", covering Goshen College Athletics. It has also been involved in several larger projects, including the broadcast of the school's annual Festival of Carols on [[WNIT (TV)|WNIT]]. In the summer of 2011, the Goshen College communication department launched FiveCore Media, a video production company aimed at providing services for both on-campus and off-campus clients. Globe Media also produces a weekly sports show, \"The Globe Sports Corner\", featuring athlete and coaches interviews, along with an in-depth story highlighting athletes and teams across campus.\n\n=== Performing arts ===\n[[File:Goshen College Music Center.JPG|thumb|250px|left|The Goshen College Music Center]]\nGoshen College students have a variety of shows to attend in the Music Center's Sauder Concert Hall or Rieth Recital Hall or the Umble Center, Goshen's theater. With the addition of the Music Center to campus, the college has offered a Performing Arts Series of nationally renowned artists from across the country. Previous guests include [[Garrison Keillor]] and [[A Prairie Home Companion]], [[Indigo Girls]], [[The Wailin' Jennys]], [[Nickel Creek]], [[Colm Wilkinson]], [[Chanticleer (ensemble)|Chanticleer]], [[Canadian Brass]], [[Tokyo String Quartet]], [[Seraphic Fire]], and [[Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra]] with [[Wynton Marsalis]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Spiritual life ===\nBecause Goshen is a Christian college, spirituality plays an important part of campus life.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}  Although Goshen maintains that people of different faiths are welcome to the college, the school emphasizes [[Judeo-Christian]] values in regard to operation, justice, and teaching. All faculty members at the school are Christian, with at least eighty percent adhering to Mennonite convictions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}  The college holds convocations or chapels every Wednesday, with occasional special events, such as Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Day. Students are required to attend half of these services per semester.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen College operates a campus ministries team, headed by the campus pastor. The team includes an assistant campus minister and student leaders who help guide and plan spiritual life on campus for the school year. Activities include managing the network of Goshen's small groups, spiritual friendship, leading campus worship, and planning chapels. Campus worship night is a voluntary praise and reflection time held every Wednesday night. Students also hold a [[Taiz\u00e9]] prayer service once a month on Sunday nights at 9:00. Because service is an important aspect of Christian faith, volunteerism ties in with spiritual life on campus.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Volunteerism ===\nEvery September, Goshen College participates in an activity called Celebrate Service Day (CSD). Students team with professors and administrative faculty and go out into the larger Goshen community for a day of service. First-year students go with their colloquium advisers, while other students go with their dormitory floor or small group. Aside from CSD, many students donate their time to work at local kindergartens, elementary schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Athletics ==\nGoshen College athletic teams are known as the \"Maple Leafs,\" chosen due to the city of Goshen being referred to as ''\"The Maple City.\"''{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen is a member of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] and competes in the [[Crossroads League]] (formerly known as the [[Mid-Central College Conference]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Name and Logo|url=http://www.crossroadsleague.com/f/Name_and_Logo.php|website=Crossroads League|publisher=Crossroads League|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>).  However, men's volleyball competes in the [http://www.whac.net/ Wolverine-Hoosier Athletic Conference](WHAC). Men's sports include baseball, basketball, cross country, soccer, tennis, track & field, and volleyball; while women's sports include basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, track & field, and volleyball.<ref>{{cite web|title=GoLeafs.net| url=http://www.goleafs.net/|website=GoLeafs.net|publisher=Goshen College Athletics|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Campus facilities ==\nGoshen College has four [[Dormitory|dormitories]], apartment living, and several small group houses.  Outside the original quadrangle, Goshen's current campus has not been the result of a single master plan; rather the campus has evolved eclectically from building to building as the institution grew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a%3Dd%26d%3Dp690 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 18, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191930/http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a=d&d=p690 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/p2l_main.php Residence life] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807195403/http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/p2l_main.php |date=August 7, 2009 }}</ref> Four-year residency was typical until the mid-1970s, when a growing student enrollment prompted school officials to forgo building new dormitories and allow upperclassmen to live off campus. In 2005, Goshen College announced its plan to return to four-year residency. With more students on campus, the school has spent over $10 million building and renovating dorms.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe Roman Gingerich Recreation and Fitness Center is a $7 million facility constructed in 1994 with three full-sized basketball courts, four racquetball courts, a 200-meter indoor track, (formerly) swimming pool (for recreational swimming only) and hot tub, climbing wall, and weight room. The fitness center is open to all students and staff, and is used by community members as well.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe $24 million Music Center, completed in October 2002, has become regionally renowned for its design and acoustics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/ |title=Goshen College Music Center |publisher=GC Music Center |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/construction.php Construction] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928024741/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/construction.php |date=September 28, 2006 }}</ref> The Music Center consists of several main sections: Sauder Concert Hall, Rieth Recital Hall, the Art Gallery, and various classrooms, practice rooms and offices. Several highlights are a central recording studio, MIDI labs, and Taylor and Boody Opus 41, a 1600-pipe [[Tracker action|tracker]] [[pipe organ]], the first in the world with [[Well-Tempered Clavier|tempering]] based on alumnus Bradley Lehman's research of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s notation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/special.features/organ.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208130336/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/special.features/organ.php |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>  The facility was designed by Mathes Brierre Architects (design architects), Schmidt Associates (architects of record), and TALASKE (acoustics and audio consultants).<ref>[http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/index.php Goshen College Music Center website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070731003011/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/index.php |date=July 31, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn September of 2019, Goshen College completed the renovation and remodeling of their Union Center. The Union Center holds the Leaf Raker Cafe, as well as adding the new Juanita Lark Welcome Center.\n\n=== Sustainability ===\n<!--UNLESS YOU ARE REFERRING TO EMISSIONS FROM HUMANS OR LIVESTOCK, SUSTAINABILITY IS IN REFERENCE TO THE PHYSICAL PLANT AND OPERATIONS OF THE SCHOOL, I.E., A CATEGORY RELATED TO CAMPUS FACILITIES, AND NOT A STAND-ALONE TOPIC.-->\n\nIn 2007, then Goshen College President Jim Brenneman became a charter signatory to the [[American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment]] joining with leaders of 175 other higher education institutions that have agreed to neutralize [[greenhouse gas emissions]] on their campuses.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In 2008, Rieth Village at [[Merry Lea Environmental Learning Center]] of Goshen College became the first platinum-rated [[LEED building]] in Indiana.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In the spring of 2013, the college took the further step of purchasing 100 percent of its electricity from renewable sources through the procurement of [[renewable energy credits]]. A computerized building temperature regulation system, [[motion light sensors]] for indoor and outdoor lighting and open loop [[ground-source heat pump]]s further reduce energy consumption on campus. The campus has also converted nearly 20 percent of its lawn space to native plants and [[prairie restoration]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Goshen College students and staff have developed a food composting system, planted a community garden, built a [[solar hot water]] collection system and continued to reduce energy consumption campus-wide.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In 2014, the college earned a silver rating from the Sustainability Tracking, Assessment and Rating System (STARS) report for its sustainability efforts. Through an aggressive energy reduction program and efficiency upgrades, Goshen College has reduced electric consumption by 25 percent and gas consumption by 23 percent since 2007.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Small Group Housing ===\n\nSmall Group Housing (SGH) is an option for juniors and seniors on Goshen's campus. Started in the 1970s, SGH offers students the opportunity to live in a house arrangement, with common kitchen and living spaces. The purpose of SGH is for students to develop another living experience alternative to dormitory life. This same idea was carried out with the construction of the Apartments. Goshen College maintains that SGH living is a privilege, and students must apply as a group to live in a residence. An application board consisting of resident directors, spiritual life, and physical plant review all potential candidates in the spring for the next school year. Each group must create a housing plan, division of responsibility, show examples of volunteerism, and a commitment to better the Goshen campus, as well as resolve conflict. Other factors considered in the application process include house cumulative GPA, extracurricular involvement, median age of the group, and personal faculty recommendations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/apply/SGH.php |title=Small Group Housing |publisher=Goshen College |accessdate=2008-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225653/http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/apply/SGH.php |archivedate=September 26, 2007 }}</ref> Houses are then rewarded to applying groups who exemplify high academic, moral, and volunteer efforts, based on objective and subjective review.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen College students have also lived in local housing not associated with the college.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Satellite facilities ===\n[[File:Sunset viewed from Layton, Florida.jpg|thumbnail|Long Key sunset seen across the street from Goshen College Marine Biology lab]]\nGoshen College maintains [[Merry Lea Environmental Center]] in Indiana,{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} and the J.N. Roth Marine Biology Station in [[Layton, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/academics/biology/facilities/marine-biology/|title=J.N. Roth Marine Biology Station \u2013 Facilities \u2013 Goshen College|publisher=|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther properties maintained by Goshen College include: Brunk's Cabin, a retreat property complete with a sledding hill in [[Cass County, Michigan]], Witmer Woods,<ref>[http://www.goshen.edu/bio/Woods/NewWoods.html Witmer Wood's Goshen College website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528122402/http://www.goshen.edu/bio/Woods/NewWoods.html |date=May 28, 2010 }}</ref> a {{convert|13|acre|m2|adj=on}} arboretum with over 100 native Indiana species, and the adjacent property College Cabin (Reservoir Place),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a%3Dd%26d%3Dp696 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191625/http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a=d&d=p696 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> used for special events, along the [[Elkhart River]] and [[millrace]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n=== National anthem ===\nOn January 21, 2010, The President's Council announced a change to Goshen's long-standing policy, and thus allowing an instrumental version of the national anthem to be played prior to some college sporting events.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eyder Peralta |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/06/08/137031395/goshen-college-bans-national-anthem-at-sporting-events |title=Goshen College Bans National Anthem At Sporting Events : The Two-Way |publisher=NPR |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Anthem\" /> This decision led to numerous complaints from students, faculty and alumni.  College art professor, John Blosser, was quoted saying, \u201cIt\u2019s obviously about a battle.  It\u2019s rather violent. It\u2019s about using violence to conquer and that would be something that many people here would have problems with.\u201d<ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/06/07/national-anthem-banned-at-mennonite-colleges-sporting-events-sparking-outcry/ |work=Fox News|last=Starnes|first=Todd|title=National Anthem Banned at Mennonite College's Sporting Events, Sparking Outcry|date=June 7, 2011}}</ref> In response, Goshen's Board of Directors reversed the President's Council decision on June 6, 2011, after seeking extensive input from the college community.<ref name=\"Anthem\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/anthem/ |title=National Anthem at Goshen College &#124; News & Events &#124; GC |website=Goshen.edu |date= |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe incident thrust Goshen College into the national limelight that June when several reports on Fox News publicized the fact that the college refused to play the national anthem, \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]],\" at its athletic events.  Two Goshen city councilmen publicly criticized the college, with one referring to the decision as \"[[anti-American]]\" and stating that \"instead of living here in Goshen, they should go down and live in Cuba or Iran, then have them come back and see if their attitude has changed.\"<ref name=\"foxnews.com\" />  The college, loosely affiliated with Mennonite Church USA, which is traditionally a [[Peace churches|peace church]], published an online fact sheet stating that \"historically, playing the national anthem has not been among Goshen College's practices because of our Christ-centered core value of compassionate peacemaking seeming to be in conflict with the anthem\u2019s militaristic language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/06/07/national-anthem-banned-at-mennonite-colleges-sporting-events-sparking-outcry/ |title=National Anthem Banned at Mennonite College's Sporting Events, Sparking Outcry |publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://nation.foxnews.com/national-anthem/2011/08/26/college-bans-too-violent-national-anthem |work=Fox News | title=College Bans 'Too Violent' National Anthem \u2013 National Anthem \u2013 Fox Nation |date=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Starnes|first=Todd|title=College Bans National Anthem|url=http://radio.foxnews.com/2011/06/07/college-bans-national-anthem/|publisher=Fox News Radio |accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe college's then president, Dr. James E. Brenneman, announced on August 19, 2011 that as an alternative, \"[[America the Beautiful]]\" would be played before select athletic events.<ref name=\"Anthem\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/17/us/pacifist-goshen-college-reconsiders-the-national-anthem.html | work=The New York Times | first=Mark | last=Oppenheimer | title=Pacifist Goshen College Reconsiders the National Anthem | date=September 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Same-sex marriage ===\nGoshen, along with sister school [[Eastern Mennonite University]], created a stir within the Christian college community in July 2015, when the two became the first [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]] (CCCU) member schools to add \"sexual orientation\" to their anti-discrimination policy, clearing the way for the hiring of openly gay employees.  The decision created a rift in the CCCU, which lobbies among other things, on behalf of the rights of Christian schools to hire employees who adhere to orthodox Christian teachings on marriage.<ref name=\"AllowSameSex\">{{cite news|author1=Smietana, Bob|author2=Lee, Morgan|author3=Zylstra, Sarah Eekhoff|title=Two CCCU Colleges to Allow Same-Sex Married Faculty|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/gleanings/2015/july/cccu-goshen-college-eastern-mennonite-university-same-sex-m.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|issue=online|publisher=Christianity Today|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>  Two CCCU member-schools \u2013 [[Union University]] and [[Oklahoma Wesleyan University]] (OKWU) \u2013 had already resigned from the organization in protest, and up to forty other member schools were poised to follow the lead of Union and OKWU, before Goshen and EMU voluntarily withdrew their membership from the organization.<ref name=AllowSameSex /><ref name=\"PeaceChurchOut\">{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Jeremy|title=Peace Church Out: Mennonite Schools Leave CCCU to Avoid Same-Sex Marriage Split|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/gleanings/2015/september/cccu-emu-goshen-college-okwu-union-membership-status.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|publisher=Christianity Today|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of Goshen College people}}\nGoshen's motto, \"Culture for Service\" is evident in many graduates and faculty.  Below is a partial list of notable people who have been associated with the College:\n\n*[[Philip A. Beachy]] Professor at [[Stanford University School of Medicine]], and an Associate at Stanford's Institute of Stem Cell Biology and Regenerative Medicine.\n* [[Roger N. Beachy]] (1966) \u2013 Director of the National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA).\n* [[Harold S. Bender]] \u2013 Author, Professor, College Dean, founder of ''Mennonite Quarterly Review''.\n* Douglas Schwartzentruber (1978) \u2013 Medical Director of the Goshen Center for Cancer Care and named to the TIME Magazine's 2010 list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1984685_1984745_1984778,00.html | work=Time | title=The 2010 Time 100 | date=2010-04-29}}</ref>\n* Dale J. Kempf \u2013 Distinguished Research Fellow and Dir., Antiviral Research, [[Abbvie]]; Scientific Advisory Committee, [[Drugs for Neglected Diseases initiative]]; and [[American Chemical Society|ACS]] Heroes of Chemistry Awardee and [[Intellectual Property Owners Association|IPOA]]\u2013National Inventor of the Year (as co-inventor of the [[Norvir]] and [[Kaletra]] HIV protease inhibitors).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dndi.org/about-dndi/our-people/scientific-advisory-committee/dalekempf/|title=Dale Kempf \u2013 DNDi|website=www.dndi.org|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[David P. Bartel]] (1982) \u2013 professor of biology at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].\n* [[Sofia Samatar]] (1993) \u2013 award-winning author of ''A Stranger in Olondria''.\n* Rebecca Stoltzfus ( B.A. 1984 Chemistry), professor & vice provost at [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.human.cornell.edu/bio.cfm?netid=rjs62|title=Rebecca Stoltzfus|website=Cornell College of Human Ecology|accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref>\n* [[James C. Strouse]] (1999) \u2013 screenwriter and director.\n* [[Errick McCollum]] \u2013 American professional basketball player who plays for [[Anadolu Efes S.K.|Anadolu Efes]] of the [[Turkish Basketball Super League]] and the [[EuroLeague]].\n* [[Carrie Newcomer]] \u2013 American singer, songwriter and author who has received numerous awards for her music and related charitable activities.\n* [[Rudy Wiebe]] - Canadian novelist\n*[[Stephen Ainlay]]- 18th president of [[Union College]].\n*[[Katie Sowers]]- NFL football coach\n\n== Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning ==\nOn October 25, 2006, Goshen College announced that it was the recipient of a $12.5 million [[Lilly Endowment|Lilly grant]] to create the Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning (CITL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citl.goshen.edu|title=Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning|accessdate=2007-12-25|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708145338/http://citl.goshen.edu/|archive-date=2012-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Aquirre>Aguirre, Richard: \"Access, Transformation & Research\", Bulletin: The magazine of Goshen College, Winter/Spring 2007, pp. 11-12</ref> The purpose of this grant was to research challenges that come with changing demographics in rural towns with small colleges. Goshen College is located in Elkhart County which had a large and rapidly growing Latino population at the time (12.6 percent of the population in 2006).<ref name=Aquirre /> Despite growing minority populations, Indiana's minority enrollment in its colleges and universities has only increased two percent.<ref name=Aquirre />\n\n== Traditions ==\n* Goshen's motto, \"Culture for Service,\" was coined by president Noah E. Byers in 1903.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* Goshen's school colors, purple and white, were modeled after [[Northwestern University]], where President Byers attended and after which he wanted to model Goshen.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* One of the college's many traditions is \"sampling\" sap from the city of Goshen's official Maple Tree, located on campus, and \"testing\" how many more weeks of winter there will be. Professors from the science department bring out their equipment with much fanfare to determine the official length of winter. In 2006, the maple tree was removed because of disease rotting the hardwood and was replaced by a new tree, now the official maple tree of Goshen. In 2007, new president Jim Brenneman replaced this tradition (which probably resulted in the early death of the maple) with \"Weather or Not Day\"; a day celebrating Northern Indiana's fickle weather.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* Early (1925) advertisements for the college were refreshingly direct. One said \"Goshen [is] not the best college in the United States. But it is better than the rest for Mennonite young people.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegevalues.org/diaries.cfm?id%3D233%26a%3D1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010123/http://www.collegevalues.org/diaries.cfm?id=233&a=1 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n=== College seal ===\nGoshen College seal signifies the book that all alumni have signed since graduation, and the lamp signifies the enlightenment that comes with education. As a Christian school, the book also signifies the importance of word, as well as God's call for his people to be \"light to the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/news/bulletin/03june/01_year.php|title=One remarkable year: 1903\u20131904|publisher=Goshen College|year=2003|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Kulp.JPG|Kulp dormitory and Adelphian fountain -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Recfit.JPG|Roman Gingerich Recreation and Fitness Center -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Theconnector.JPG|The connector connecting Kratz, Miller, and Yoder underclassmen dorms -->\nFile:GC facing east.JPG|Goshen College in late summer\nFile:Goshen Quad.JPG|Goshen College's Quadrangle in early morning fog\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Good Library.JPG|Schrock Plaza and Harold and Wilma Good Library -->\nFile:KratzMiller.JPG|Kratz and Miller dormitories\nFile:Coffman dorm.JPG|Coffman dormitory\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.goshen.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{Goshen College}}\n{{Crossroads League navbox}}\n{{Indiana Colleges and Universities}}\n\n[[Category:Goshen College| ]]\n[[Category:Education in Elkhart County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Goshen, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Mennonite Church]]\n[[Category:Crossroads League]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Elkhart County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Mennonitism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in Indiana]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name          = Goshen College\n| image         = Seal-solid-black.png\n| image_size    = 160px\n| caption       = <br /> The Seal of Goshen College\n| motto         = ''Culture for Service''\n| type          = [[private university|Private]] [[liberal arts college]]\n| endowment     = [[United States dollar|$]]112,179,000 (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=2017-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| established   = September 21, 1894<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Goshen College| last = Fisher Miller| first = Susan| title = Culture for Service : A History of Goshen College, 1894\u20131994| location = Goshen, IN| date = 1994|page=11}}</ref>\n| faculty       = 71<ref name=\"NCES\">{{cite web|title=College Navigator \u2013 Goshen College|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=150668|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|date=June 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| president     = Rebecca Stoltzfus\n| city          = [[Goshen, Indiana|Goshen]]\n| state         = [[Indiana]]\n| country       = United States\n| coor          = {{coord|41.5637|-85.8272|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students      = 950<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| undergrad     = 883<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| postgrad      = 67<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| campus        = [[Town|Large town]]: {{convert|135|acre}}, 1,189-[[acre]] natural sanctuary [[Merry Lea]]<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\">{{cite web|title=Quick Facts \u2013 About Goshen College|url=https://www.goshen.edu/about/quick-facts/|publisher=Goshen College|date=June 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| nickname      = Maple Leafs\n| colors        = Purple and White<ref>{{cite web|title=Graphic Standards\u2013A quick reference|url=https://www.goshen.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/61/2013/01/standards_guide_2015-1.pdf|publisher=Goshen College|date=2015|accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><br />{{color box|#49176d}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| athletics     = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] Division II \u2013 [[Crossroads League]]\n| sports        = 14 varsity sports teams<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" />\n| mascot        = Maple Leaf\n| religious_affiliation   = [[Mennonite Church USA]]\n| website       = {{URL|www.goshen.edu}}\n| logo          =\n}}\n\n'''Goshen College''' is a private [[liberal arts college]] in [[Goshen, Indiana]]. It was founded in 1894 as the '''Elkhart Institute of Science, Industry and the Arts''', and is affiliated with [[Mennonite Church USA]]. The college is [[school accreditation|accredited]] by the ]]Higher Learning Commission]]. Goshen has an enrollment of 950 students.<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" /> While Goshen maintains a distinctive liberal Mennonite worldview, it admits students of all religions. [[Mennonite]]s make up 43 percent of the student body.<ref name=\"GC Quick Facts\" />\n\nGoshen College is home to ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]'' and the [[Mennonite Historical Library]], a research library compiling one of the world's most comprehensive collection of [[Anabaptist]] and Mennonite primary source material.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia| publisher = American Historical Association| title = Mennonite Historical Library| encyclopedia = American Historical Association Archives Wiki| date = 2013-05-17| url = http://archiveswiki.historians.org/index.php/Mennonite_Historical_Library}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe history of Goshen College (or Goshen, as it is commonly known) is intertwined with that of the history of Mennonites in America,{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} and so Goshen's history is best told in the context of this broader history.{{according to whom|date=August 2016}}{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} \"Old\" Mennonites had traditionally been suspicious of higher education, but by the late 19th century, opinion started to change.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Decades earlier, [[mainline Protestant]] church denominations had begun to found colleges across America, with the hope of developing well-trained clergy for their congregations.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} As more \"Old\" Mennonites sent their children to other Christian colleges, they realized that, without a college of their own, many of their youth would leave the church.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Thus, prompted in part as a reaction to mainline Christianity, the \"Old\" Mennonites started the Elkhart Institute in [[Elkhart, Indiana]] in August 1894, to prepare Mennonite youth for college.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Today,{{when|date=April 2017}} Goshen is open to everyone, but this earlier vision and its historical relationship with the Mennonite Church remains visible: it is home to ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]'', [[Mennonite Historical Library]], [[Mennonite Church USA Archives]], including Mennonite Central Committee archives, offices of \"The Mennonite\", and it has numerous alumni connections with the broader Mennonite Church.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen was the first Mennonite school of higher education in North America to confer a four-year degree.{{according to whom|date=April 2017}}{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}<ref>[[Bethel College (Kansas)|Bethel College]], which was incorporated in 1887 and opened at its present site in 1893, is older, but did not originally grant four-year degrees.{{Original research inline|date=April 2017}}{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}</ref>  H.A. Mumaw, a practicing physician, first led the small operation; in 1894, a group of 15 \"Old\" Mennonite ministers and laymen started a corporation that they named the Elkhart Institute association.<ref>Schlabach, Theron F: ''Peace, Faith, Nation: Mennonites and Amish in Nineteenth Century America'', page 300. Herald Press, 1988</ref>  The first diploma was awarded in 1898.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Lured by businessmen to relocate several miles away to [[Goshen, Indiana]], the Institute moved in September 1903 and added a junior college course list, renaming itself Goshen College.{{when|date=April 2017}}{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} By 1906, the Mennonite Board of Education had taken control of the college, dissolving the Elkhart Institute Association.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} A complete college course was established in 1908, and the first Bachelor of Arts degrees were conferred in 1910.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} After 1910, most of Goshen's students were enrolled in college courses. From 1914 to 1919, partly out of response to its constituents, Goshen College attempted a \"School of Agriculture,\" which sought to prepare Mennonite young people to return to their rural communities; the hope was that such a program would spark a technological revolution among some of the farmers, but it was never a success and was cut after [[World War I]], five years after it began.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} The college-prep academy program of Goshen College was discontinued in 1935.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe school was closed during the 1923\u20131924 school year by the Mennonite Board of Education but reopened the following year. One of many factors in closing the college was denominational tension due to [[Liberal Christianity|modernist]] and [[Christian fundamentalism|fundamentalist Christian]] theologies of the 1920s and their impact on Mennonite theology at the school.<ref>Juhnke, James C: ''Vision, Doctrine, War: Mennonite Identity and Organization in America 1890\u20131930'', page 128. Herald Press, 1989</ref> In response to this crisis, many of Goshen's faculty and dozens of students, angry with the Mennonite Board of Education's decision, relocated to [[Bluffton University|Bluffton College]]. As part of the larger ongoing reaction against liberalism through the early 20th century, [[Hesston College]] and [[Eastern Mennonite University|Eastern Mennonite School]] were formed among \"Old\" Mennonites, although staunch traditionalists realized that no higher education was particularly safe.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nWhen the institution was reopened, it was marked by the new leadership of president [[Sanford Calvin Yoder|S.C. Yoder]] and dean [[Harold S. Bender|Noah Oyer,]] who manifested outstanding abilities. His character was one marked by simplicity, modesty, and refinement, as well as unusual wisdom and insight. Under his leadership the educational program of the College developed rapidly, and much of the strength of the present college program is due to his untiring and wise endeavors. After dean Oyer\u2019s untimely passing in 1931, Harold Bender became dean. He was a man whose influence upon the \"Old\" Mennonites was significant for much of the 20th century. Bender carefully piloted the stormy waters of theology by stating that [[Mennonitism]] was not [[liberalism]]. Bender later went on to say that [[fundamentalism]] also contributed to problems with theology and created ''[[The Anabaptist Vision]]'', a \"third way\" that sought to spell out the direction for the future Mennonite Church. More than arguing doctrine, Bender and a younger group of intellectuals at Goshen College sought to shape the Mennonite faith that was more ideological than institutional. The goal was to articulate a faith that could stand the test of academic scrutiny in broader society while carefully upholding traditional beliefs of the church. Out of this ideology, Bender started ''[[The Mennonite Quarterly Review]]''. Throughout this time, Goshen remained the epicenter of \"Old\" Mennonite theology and higher education, and became known as the \"Goshen Historical Renaissance\".<ref>Toews, Paul: ''Mennonites in American Society, 1930\u20131970: Modernity and the Persistence of Religious Community'', page 88. Herald Press, 1996</ref>\n\nDuring the 1940s, Goshen was one of the [[Mennonite Central Committee]]'s key places to form a \"relief training school\" that helped to train volunteers for unpaid jobs in the [[Civilian Public Service]], an alternative to the Army. Many Mennonites chose the civilian service alternative because of their beliefs regarding Biblical pacifism and nonresistance.  Although the young women pacifists were not liable to the draft, they volunteered for unpaid Civilian Public Service jobs to demonstrate their patriotism; many worked in mental hospitals.<ref>Rachel Waltner Goossen, ''Women Against the Good War: Conscientious Objection and Gender on the American Home Front, 1941\u20131947'' (1997) pp 98-111</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the college was granted care of [[Merry Lea Environmental Center|Merry Lea Environmental Learning Center]], a {{convert|1150|acre|km2|adj=mid}} nature preserve that now offers Goshen's master's degree in Environmental Science.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nIn 1993, Harold and Wilma Good, longtime friends of the college, left their estate to Goshen. The estate was estimated at roughly $28 million, the majority in stock of the [[Smuckers|J.M. Smucker Company]]. Wilma was a daughter of the company's founder. The college sold the stock and added the funds to its endowment, more than doubling it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mennoweekly.org/JUNE/06-19-06/ENDOWMENTS06-19.html |title=Mennonite college endowments lag behind |publisher=Mennonite Weekly Review |year=2006 |accessdate=2008-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021020/http://www.mennoweekly.org/JUNE/06-19-06/ENDOWMENTS06-19.html |archivedate=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe campus experienced a building boom in the later half of the 1990s through the present, with an estimated $30 million in new or renovated structures on campus. This included the addition of the Roman Gingerich Recreation-Fitness Center, the Music Center, the Connector, and the renovation of all dormitories. The college is currently working on a new campus master plan and strategic plan that will define the college's priorities for the years ahead. Today, more than 20,000 Goshen College alumni have been counted, residing in more than 85 countries. The Goshen campus has flourished from less than {{convert|50|acre|m2}} to {{convert|135|acre|km2}} with 18 major buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/aboutgc/history.php |title=History of Goshen College |publisher=Goshen College |accessdate=2008-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225641/http://www.goshen.edu/aboutgc/history.php |archivedate=2007-09-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nGoshen College offers 41 majors and 47 minors for undergraduates.<ref name=\"Majors and Minors\">{{cite web|title=Majors and Minors|url=http://www.goshen.edu/academics/majors-minors/|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>  Some of the most popular programs are nursing, biology, business, communication, education, [[American Sign Language]] and environmental science. The college also offers a [[Master of Arts]] in Environmental Education, a master's degree in intercultural leadership, and a master's degree in nursing with two tracks: family nurse practitioner and clinical nurse leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/news/pressarchive/10-11-06-enviro-ed.html |title=Goshen College to launch first master's degree program, in environmental education |website=Goshen.edu |date=2006-10-11 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref> In 2014, Goshen College partnered with Eastern Mennonite University and Bluffton University to launch the Collaborative MBA program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emu.edu/now/news/2014/03/unique-collaborative-mba-program-launched-from-platform-of-three-mennonite-institutions/ |title=Unique Collaborative MBA program launched from platform of three Mennonite institutions \u2013 EMU News &#124; Eastern Mennonite University |website=Emu.edu |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year is divided into two semester terms, with an additional May term.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Study-Service Term ===\n\nIntercultural education is a requirement for all students at Goshen College.  To fulfill the requirement, students will either spend a semester abroad or complete an intercultural experience in the [[United States]].  Goshen College's ''Study-Service Term'' (SST) is a program which approximately 80 percent of students participate in to complete their intercultural study requirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/intercultural-requirement/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 Intercultural Requirement|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref> Students typically study the language and culture for six weeks, usually in the capital city, then do some sort of service work in a more remote area for the remaining six weeks. Service may include working at a hospital, nursing home, [[Guadeloupe|kindergarten]], or missionary service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/destinations/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 What is SST?|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref> The college has in the past also offered a domestic SST to immerse students in the Latino culture and community in northern Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/sst/destinations/|title=Study-Service Term \u2013 Destinations|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2017}}\n\n=== Clubs and organizations ===\n[[File:Beach volleyball @ Goshen.JPG|thumb|left|260px|Goshen College intramural volleyball]]\nGoshen College has no official fraternities or sororities, however, many different types of clubs and organizations exist to help facilitate campus life.  Clubs that play a significant part in campus life include: Black Student Union (BSU), Latino Student Union (LSU), International Student Club (ISC), Advocates, GC Players, Nursing Student Association, Hymn Club, Voices and Harmony, Social Work Action Association (SWAA), Art Club, Pre-Med Club, Goshen Student Women's Association (GSWA), PAX and Eco-PAX.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nCampus Activities Council, or CAC, is the primary extracurricular organization on campus that hosts a variety of weekend activities and events. CAC is responsible for \"Kick Off,\" a talent show held at the beginning of the fall semester. CAC also hosts \"Hour After\" shows, where talented students on campus perform music, comedy, or dancing for the audience.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==== International students ====\nThe International Students Club (ISC) hosts the Coffeehouse every year, an event during which international students demonstrate their artistic talents. Students are also given the opportunity, through Global Citizenship, to individually talk about their culture, and have it published by the Goshen College newspaper.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==== Intramural athletics ====\nIntramural athletics are also offered.  Throughout the year, students can participate in the coed sports of outdoor soccer, volleyball, sand volleyball, kickball, touch football, ultimate frisbee, and wiffleball, as well as basketball, indoor soccer, and 3-on-3 basketball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intramurals|url=https://www.goshen.edu/campuslife/intramurals/|website=Goshen College|publisher=Goshen College|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Media ===\n\nGoshen College has its own school newspaper, ''The Record'' and its own radio station, [[WGCS]], branded as 91.1FM The Globe. On March 12, 2011, The Globe was named the Best College Station in the Nation, winning first place at the 71st Annual Conference of the Intercollegiate Broadcasting System (IBS) in New York City. On March 2, 2013, The Globe was again named Best College Station in the Nation, making it the first college to win the award twice. Since then, 91.1 the Globe has been awarded \"Radio Station of the Year\" by the Indiana Association of State Broadcasters six time, their most recent in March of 2020.\nGlobe Media also produces a monthly news show, \"The Globe News Report\", which covers campus and community news, along with a weekly sports show, \"The Globe Sports Corner\", covering Goshen College Athletics. It has also been involved in several larger projects, including the broadcast of the school's annual Festival of Carols on [[WNIT (TV)|WNIT]]. In the summer of 2011, the Goshen College communication department launched FiveCore Media, a video production company aimed at providing services for both on-campus and off-campus clients. Globe Media also produces a weekly sports show, \"The Globe Sports Corner\", featuring athlete and coaches interviews, along with an in-depth story highlighting athletes and teams across campus.\n\n=== Performing arts ===\n[[File:Goshen College Music Center.JPG|thumb|250px|left|The Goshen College Music Center]]\nGoshen College students have a variety of shows to attend in the Music Center's Sauder Concert Hall or Rieth Recital Hall or the Umble Center, Goshen's theater. With the addition of the Music Center to campus, the college has offered a Performing Arts Series of nationally renowned artists from across the country. Previous guests include [[Garrison Keillor]] and [[A Prairie Home Companion]], [[Indigo Girls]], [[The Wailin' Jennys]], [[Nickel Creek]], [[Colm Wilkinson]], [[Chanticleer (ensemble)|Chanticleer]], [[Canadian Brass]], [[Tokyo String Quartet]], [[Seraphic Fire]], and [[Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra]] with [[Wynton Marsalis]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Spiritual life ===\nBecause Goshen is a Christian college, spirituality plays an important part of campus life.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}  Although Goshen maintains that people of different faiths are welcome to the college, the school emphasizes [[Judeo-Christian]] values in regard to operation, justice, and teaching. All faculty members at the school are Christian, with at least eighty percent adhering to Mennonite convictions.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}  The college holds convocations or chapels every Wednesday, with occasional special events, such as Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Day. Students are required to attend half of these services per semester.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen College operates a campus ministries team, headed by the campus pastor. The team includes an assistant campus minister and student leaders who help guide and plan spiritual life on campus for the school year. Activities include managing the network of Goshen's small groups, spiritual friendship, leading campus worship, and planning chapels. Campus worship night is a voluntary praise and reflection time held every Wednesday night. Students also hold a [[Taiz\u00e9]] prayer service once a month on Sunday nights at 9:00. Because service is an important aspect of Christian faith, volunteerism ties in with spiritual life on campus.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Volunteerism ===\nEvery September, Goshen College participates in an activity called Celebrate Service Day (CSD). Students team with professors and administrative faculty and go out into the larger Goshen community for a day of service. First-year students go with their colloquium advisers, while other students go with their dormitory floor or small group. Aside from CSD, many students donate their time to work at local kindergartens, elementary schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Athletics ==\nGoshen College athletic teams are known as the \"Maple Leafs,\" chosen due to the city of Goshen being referred to as ''\"The Maple City.\"''{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen is a member of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] and competes in the [[Crossroads League]] (formerly known as the [[Mid-Central College Conference]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Name and Logo|url=http://www.crossroadsleague.com/f/Name_and_Logo.php|website=Crossroads League|publisher=Crossroads League|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>).  Men's sports include baseball, basketball, cross country, soccer, tennis, track & field, and volleyball; while women's sports include basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, track & field, and volleyball.<ref>{{cite web|title=GoLeafs.net| url=http://www.goleafs.net/|website=GoLeafs.net|publisher=Goshen College Athletics|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Campus facilities ==\nGoshen College has four [[Dormitory|dormitories]], apartment living, and several small group houses.  Outside the original quadrangle, Goshen's current campus has not been the result of a single master plan; rather the campus has evolved eclectically from building to building as the institution grew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a%3Dd%26d%3Dp690 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 18, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191930/http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a=d&d=p690 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/p2l_main.php Residence life] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807195403/http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/p2l_main.php |date=August 7, 2009 }}</ref> Four-year residency was typical until the mid-1970s, when a growing student enrollment prompted school officials to forgo building new dormitories and allow upperclassmen to live off campus. In 2005, Goshen College announced its plan to return to four-year residency. With more students on campus, the school has spent over $10 million building and renovating dorms.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe Roman Gingerich Recreation and Fitness Center is a $7 million facility constructed in 1994 with three full-sized basketball courts, four racquetball courts, a 200-meter indoor track, (formerly) swimming pool (for recreational swimming only) and hot tub, climbing wall, and weight room. The fitness center is open to all students and staff, and is used by community members as well.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nThe $24 million Music Center, completed in October 2002, has become regionally renowned for its design and acoustics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/ |title=Goshen College Music Center |publisher=GC Music Center |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2016-04-22}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/construction.php Construction] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928024741/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/construction.php |date=September 28, 2006 }}</ref> The Music Center consists of several main sections: Sauder Concert Hall, Rieth Recital Hall, the Art Gallery, and various classrooms, practice rooms and offices. Several highlights are a central recording studio, MIDI labs, and Taylor and Boody Opus 41, a 1600-pipe [[Tracker action|tracker]] [[pipe organ]], the first in the world with [[Well-Tempered Clavier|tempering]] based on alumnus Bradley Lehman's research of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s notation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/special.features/organ.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208130336/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/special.features/organ.php |archivedate=February 8, 2007 }}</ref>  The facility was designed by Mathes Brierre Architects (design architects), Schmidt Associates (architects of record), and TALASKE (acoustics and audio consultants).<ref>[http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/index.php Goshen College Music Center website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070731003011/http://www.gcmusiccenter.org/php/facility/about/index.php |date=July 31, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn September of 2019, Goshen College completed the renovation and remodeling of their Union Center. The Union Center holds the Leaf Raker Cafe, as well as adding the new Juanita Lark Welcome Center.\n\n=== Sustainability ===\n<!--UNLESS YOU ARE REFERRING TO EMISSIONS FROM HUMANS OR LIVESTOCK, SUSTAINABILITY IS IN REFERENCE TO THE PHYSICAL PLANT AND OPERATIONS OF THE SCHOOL, I.E., A CATEGORY RELATED TO CAMPUS FACILITIES, AND NOT A STAND-ALONE TOPIC.-->\n\nIn 2007, then Goshen College President Jim Brenneman became a charter signatory to the [[American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment]] joining with leaders of 175 other higher education institutions that have agreed to neutralize [[greenhouse gas emissions]] on their campuses.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In 2008, Rieth Village at [[Merry Lea Environmental Learning Center]] of Goshen College became the first platinum-rated [[LEED building]] in Indiana.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In the spring of 2013, the college took the further step of purchasing 100 percent of its electricity from renewable sources through the procurement of [[renewable energy credits]]. A computerized building temperature regulation system, [[motion light sensors]] for indoor and outdoor lighting and open loop [[ground-source heat pump]]s further reduce energy consumption on campus. The campus has also converted nearly 20 percent of its lawn space to native plants and [[prairie restoration]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} Goshen College students and staff have developed a food composting system, planted a community garden, built a [[solar hot water]] collection system and continued to reduce energy consumption campus-wide.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} In 2014, the college earned a silver rating from the Sustainability Tracking, Assessment and Rating System (STARS) report for its sustainability efforts. Through an aggressive energy reduction program and efficiency upgrades, Goshen College has reduced electric consumption by 25 percent and gas consumption by 23 percent since 2007.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Small Group Housing ===\n\nSmall Group Housing (SGH) is an option for juniors and seniors on Goshen's campus. Started in the 1970s, SGH offers students the opportunity to live in a house arrangement, with common kitchen and living spaces. The purpose of SGH is for students to develop another living experience alternative to dormitory life. This same idea was carried out with the construction of the Apartments. Goshen College maintains that SGH living is a privilege, and students must apply as a group to live in a residence. An application board consisting of resident directors, spiritual life, and physical plant review all potential candidates in the spring for the next school year. Each group must create a housing plan, division of responsibility, show examples of volunteerism, and a commitment to better the Goshen campus, as well as resolve conflict. Other factors considered in the application process include house cumulative GPA, extracurricular involvement, median age of the group, and personal faculty recommendations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/apply/SGH.php |title=Small Group Housing |publisher=Goshen College |accessdate=2008-04-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225653/http://www.goshen.edu/studentlife/apply/SGH.php |archivedate=September 26, 2007 }}</ref> Houses are then rewarded to applying groups who exemplify high academic, moral, and volunteer efforts, based on objective and subjective review.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nGoshen College students have also lived in local housing not associated with the college.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n=== Satellite facilities ===\n[[File:Sunset viewed from Layton, Florida.jpg|thumbnail|Long Key sunset seen across the street from Goshen College Marine Biology lab]]\nGoshen College maintains [[Merry Lea Environmental Center]] in Indiana,{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}} and the J.N. Roth Marine Biology Station in [[Layton, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goshen.edu/academics/biology/facilities/marine-biology/|title=J.N. Roth Marine Biology Station \u2013 Facilities \u2013 Goshen College|publisher=|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther properties maintained by Goshen College include: Brunk's Cabin, a retreat property complete with a sledding hill in [[Cass County, Michigan]], Witmer Woods,<ref>[http://www.goshen.edu/bio/Woods/NewWoods.html Witmer Wood's Goshen College website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528122402/http://www.goshen.edu/bio/Woods/NewWoods.html |date=May 28, 2010 }}</ref> a {{convert|13|acre|m2|adj=on}} arboretum with over 100 native Indiana species, and the adjacent property College Cabin (Reservoir Place),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a%3Dd%26d%3Dp696 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724191625/http://puka.cs.waikato.ac.nz/cgi-bin/cic/library?a=d&d=p696 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> used for special events, along the [[Elkhart River]] and [[millrace]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n== Controversy ==\n\n=== National anthem ===\nOn January 21, 2010, The President's Council announced a change to Goshen's long-standing policy, and thus allowing an instrumental version of the national anthem to be played prior to some college sporting events.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eyder Peralta |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/06/08/137031395/goshen-college-bans-national-anthem-at-sporting-events |title=Goshen College Bans National Anthem At Sporting Events : The Two-Way |publisher=NPR |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Anthem\" /> This decision led to numerous complaints from students, faculty and alumni.  College art professor, John Blosser, was quoted saying, \u201cIt\u2019s obviously about a battle.  It\u2019s rather violent. It\u2019s about using violence to conquer and that would be something that many people here would have problems with.\u201d<ref name=\"foxnews.com\">{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/06/07/national-anthem-banned-at-mennonite-colleges-sporting-events-sparking-outcry/ |work=Fox News|last=Starnes|first=Todd|title=National Anthem Banned at Mennonite College's Sporting Events, Sparking Outcry|date=June 7, 2011}}</ref> In response, Goshen's Board of Directors reversed the President's Council decision on June 6, 2011, after seeking extensive input from the college community.<ref name=\"Anthem\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/anthem/ |title=National Anthem at Goshen College &#124; News & Events &#124; GC |website=Goshen.edu |date= |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe incident thrust Goshen College into the national limelight that June when several reports on Fox News publicized the fact that the college refused to play the national anthem, \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]],\" at its athletic events.  Two Goshen city councilmen publicly criticized the college, with one referring to the decision as \"[[anti-American]]\" and stating that \"instead of living here in Goshen, they should go down and live in Cuba or Iran, then have them come back and see if their attitude has changed.\"<ref name=\"foxnews.com\" />  The college, loosely affiliated with Mennonite Church USA, which is traditionally a [[Peace churches|peace church]], published an online fact sheet stating that \"historically, playing the national anthem has not been among Goshen College's practices because of our Christ-centered core value of compassionate peacemaking seeming to be in conflict with the anthem\u2019s militaristic language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/06/07/national-anthem-banned-at-mennonite-colleges-sporting-events-sparking-outcry/ |title=National Anthem Banned at Mennonite College's Sporting Events, Sparking Outcry |publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=June 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://nation.foxnews.com/national-anthem/2011/08/26/college-bans-too-violent-national-anthem |work=Fox News | title=College Bans 'Too Violent' National Anthem \u2013 National Anthem \u2013 Fox Nation |date=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Starnes|first=Todd|title=College Bans National Anthem|url=http://radio.foxnews.com/2011/06/07/college-bans-national-anthem/|publisher=Fox News Radio |accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe college's then president, Dr. James E. Brenneman, announced on August 19, 2011 that as an alternative, \"[[America the Beautiful]]\" would be played before select athletic events.<ref name=\"Anthem\" /><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/17/us/pacifist-goshen-college-reconsiders-the-national-anthem.html | work=The New York Times | first=Mark | last=Oppenheimer | title=Pacifist Goshen College Reconsiders the National Anthem | date=September 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Same-sex marriage ===\nGoshen, along with sister school [[Eastern Mennonite University]], created a stir within the Christian college community in July 2015, when the two became the first [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]] (CCCU) member schools to add \"sexual orientation\" to their anti-discrimination policy, clearing the way for the hiring of openly gay employees.  The decision created a rift in the CCCU, which lobbies among other things, on behalf of the rights of Christian schools to hire employees who adhere to orthodox Christian teachings on marriage.<ref name=\"AllowSameSex\">{{cite news|author1=Smietana, Bob|author2=Lee, Morgan|author3=Zylstra, Sarah Eekhoff|title=Two CCCU Colleges to Allow Same-Sex Married Faculty|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/gleanings/2015/july/cccu-goshen-college-eastern-mennonite-university-same-sex-m.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|issue=online|publisher=Christianity Today|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>  Two CCCU member-schools \u2013 [[Union University]] and [[Oklahoma Wesleyan University]] (OKWU) \u2013 had already resigned from the organization in protest, and up to forty other member schools were poised to follow the lead of Union and OKWU, before Goshen and EMU voluntarily withdrew their membership from the organization.<ref name=AllowSameSex /><ref name=\"PeaceChurchOut\">{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Jeremy|title=Peace Church Out: Mennonite Schools Leave CCCU to Avoid Same-Sex Marriage Split|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/gleanings/2015/september/cccu-emu-goshen-college-okwu-union-membership-status.html|accessdate=August 19, 2016|publisher=Christianity Today|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of Goshen College people}}\nGoshen's motto, \"Culture for Service\" is evident in many graduates and faculty.  Below is a partial list of notable people who have been associated with the College:\n\n*[[Philip A. Beachy]] Professor at [[Stanford University School of Medicine]], and an Associate at Stanford's Institute of Stem Cell Biology and Regenerative Medicine.\n* [[Roger N. Beachy]] (1966) \u2013 Director of the National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA).\n* [[Harold S. Bender]] \u2013 Author, Professor, College Dean, founder of ''Mennonite Quarterly Review''.\n* Douglas Schwartzentruber (1978) \u2013 Medical Director of the Goshen Center for Cancer Care and named to the TIME Magazine's 2010 list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1984685_1984745_1984778,00.html | work=Time | title=The 2010 Time 100 | date=2010-04-29}}</ref>\n* Dale J. Kempf \u2013 Distinguished Research Fellow and Dir., Antiviral Research, [[Abbvie]]; Scientific Advisory Committee, [[Drugs for Neglected Diseases initiative]]; and [[American Chemical Society|ACS]] Heroes of Chemistry Awardee and [[Intellectual Property Owners Association|IPOA]]\u2013National Inventor of the Year (as co-inventor of the [[Norvir]] and [[Kaletra]] HIV protease inhibitors).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dndi.org/about-dndi/our-people/scientific-advisory-committee/dalekempf/|title=Dale Kempf \u2013 DNDi|website=www.dndi.org|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n* [[David P. Bartel]] (1982) \u2013 professor of biology at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].\n* [[Sofia Samatar]] (1993) \u2013 award-winning author of ''A Stranger in Olondria''.\n* Rebecca Stoltzfus ( B.A. 1984 Chemistry), professor & vice provost at [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.human.cornell.edu/bio.cfm?netid=rjs62|title=Rebecca Stoltzfus|website=Cornell College of Human Ecology|accessdate=29 November 2018}}</ref>\n* [[James C. Strouse]] (1999) \u2013 screenwriter and director.\n* [[Errick McCollum]] \u2013 American professional basketball player who plays for [[Anadolu Efes S.K.|Anadolu Efes]] of the [[Turkish Basketball Super League]] and the [[EuroLeague]].\n* [[Carrie Newcomer]] \u2013 American singer, songwriter and author who has received numerous awards for her music and related charitable activities.\n* [[Rudy Wiebe]] - Canadian novelist\n*[[Stephen Ainlay]]- 18th president of [[Union College]].\n*[[Katie Sowers]]- NFL football coach\n\n== Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning ==\nOn October 25, 2006, Goshen College announced that it was the recipient of a $12.5 million [[Lilly Endowment|Lilly grant]] to create the Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning (CITL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citl.goshen.edu|title=Center for Intercultural Teaching and Learning|accessdate=2007-12-25|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708145338/http://citl.goshen.edu/|archive-date=2012-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Aquirre>Aguirre, Richard: \"Access, Transformation & Research\", Bulletin: The magazine of Goshen College, Winter/Spring 2007, pp. 11-12</ref> The purpose of this grant was to research challenges that come with changing demographics in rural towns with small colleges. Goshen College is located in Elkhart County which had a large and rapidly growing Latino population at the time (12.6 percent of the population in 2006).<ref name=Aquirre /> Despite growing minority populations, Indiana's minority enrollment in its colleges and universities has only increased two percent.<ref name=Aquirre />\n\n== Traditions ==\n* Goshen's motto, \"Culture for Service,\" was coined by president Noah E. Byers in 1903.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* Goshen's school colors, purple and white, were modeled after [[Northwestern University]], where President Byers attended and after which he wanted to model Goshen.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* One of the college's many traditions is \"sampling\" sap from the city of Goshen's official Maple Tree, located on campus, and \"testing\" how many more weeks of winter there will be. Professors from the science department bring out their equipment with much fanfare to determine the official length of winter. In 2006, the maple tree was removed because of disease rotting the hardwood and was replaced by a new tree, now the official maple tree of Goshen. In 2007, new president Jim Brenneman replaced this tradition (which probably resulted in the early death of the maple) with \"Weather or Not Day\"; a day celebrating Northern Indiana's fickle weather.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n* Early (1925) advertisements for the college were refreshingly direct. One said \"Goshen [is] not the best college in the United States. But it is better than the rest for Mennonite young people.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegevalues.org/diaries.cfm?id%3D233%26a%3D1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010123/http://www.collegevalues.org/diaries.cfm?id=233&a=1 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n=== College seal ===\nGoshen College seal signifies the book that all alumni have signed since graduation, and the lamp signifies the enlightenment that comes with education. As a Christian school, the book also signifies the importance of word, as well as God's call for his people to be \"light to the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goshen.edu/news/bulletin/03june/01_year.php|title=One remarkable year: 1903\u20131904|publisher=Goshen College|year=2003|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Kulp.JPG|Kulp dormitory and Adelphian fountain -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Recfit.JPG|Roman Gingerich Recreation and Fitness Center -->\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Theconnector.JPG|The connector connecting Kratz, Miller, and Yoder underclassmen dorms -->\nFile:GC facing east.JPG|Goshen College in late summer\nFile:Goshen Quad.JPG|Goshen College's Quadrangle in early morning fog\n<!-- Deleted image removed: File:Good Library.JPG|Schrock Plaza and Harold and Wilma Good Library -->\nFile:KratzMiller.JPG|Kratz and Miller dormitories\nFile:Coffman dorm.JPG|Coffman dormitory\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.goshen.edu/ Official website]