{"title_page": "Critical consumerism", "text_new": "'''Critical consumption''' is the conscious choice of buying or not buying a specific product according to ethical and political beliefs. The critical [[consumerism|consumer]] recognizes the importance of considering some characteristics of the product and its realization, such as environmental [[sustainability]] and respect of workers\u2019 rights. Indeed, critical consumers take full responsibility for the [[environmental impact|environmental]], social and political effects of their choices. The critical consumer can sympathize with certain [[social movement]] goals and contributes towards them through modifying their consumption behavior.\n\nWork on critical consumption has differed in the terms used to refer to boycotting and buycotting actions. The more prominent include [[Ethical consumerism|ethical consumption]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=it&lr=&id=iFtkiRK8ZoMC&oi=fnd&pg=PT1&dq=Harrison,+R.,+Newholm,+T.+and+Shaw,+D.+(2005)+The+Ethical+Consumer,+London:+Sage.&ots=5pr9vRtHho&sig=SVmSshVUkiRyKAVBhWGtd__r9cA#v=onepage&q=Harrison%2C%20R.%2C%20Newholm%2C%20T.%20and%20Shaw%2C%20D.%20(2005)%20The%20Ethical%20Consumer%2C%20London%3A%20Sage.&f=false Harrison, R., Newholm, T. and Shaw, D. (2005) The Ethical Consumer, London: Sage.]</ref> and [[political consumerism]],<ref>Micheletti, M. (2003) Political Virtue and Shopping, New York: Palgrave Macmillan.</ref> while [[sustainable consumption]], more linked with policy, has also increased in usage.<ref>Spaargaren, G. (2003) \u2018Sustainable consumption: A theoretical and environmental policy perspective\u2019, Society and Natural Resources 16: 687/701.</ref>\n\nOften consumer and citizen are considered as different because consumers only show self-interest, whereas citizens denote expanded self-interest. The general idea is that, consumers \u2018buy what they want\u2014or what they have been persuaded to want\u2014within the limits of what they can get.<ref>[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10460-005-6042-4 Berry, W. (1989). The pleasures of eating. The Journal of Gastronomy, 5, 125\u2013131.]</ref> [[Citizenship]], on the other hand, carries duties or responsibilities along with various rights.<ref>[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.662.5395&rep=rep1&type=pdf Wilkins, J. F. (2005). Eating right here: Moving from consumer to food citizen. Agriculture and Human Values, 22, 269\u2013273]</ref> Since consumers are seen also as citizens they have to behave in a community-oriented, moral and political way, rather than as a self-interested one.\n\n== Political use of consumption ==\n\nA specificity of critical consumption is the political use of consumption, which is the consumers\u2019 choice of \u201c''producers and products with the aim of changing ethically or politically objectionable institutional or market practices''\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bridgingdifferences.mcgill.ca/en/Youth.pdf |title=Micheletti, M., Stolle, D. \"Concept of Political Consumerism\" in ''Youth Activism - An International Encyclopedia'' (2006), Lonnie R. Sherrod (ed.), Westport: Greenwood Publishing. |access-date=2016-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104192116/http://bridgingdifferences.mcgill.ca/en/Youth.pdf |archive-date=2015-01-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their choices depend on different factors as non economic issues that concern personal and family well-being, issue of fairness, justice, ethical or political assessment. Main forms and tools of political use of consumption are [[boycotting]], \"buycotting\" ([[anti-boycott]]ing) and also [[culture jamming]] or [[adbusting]].\n\nPolitical consumerism can be considered as an alternative form of political engagement, especially for young generations. In addition, market-based political strategies of young citizens go beyond boycotting and \u201cbuycotting\u201d; they also started to participate in [[internet campaign]]s becoming active consumers. Their individual choices become political movements able to challenge political and economic powers.<ref>[http://www.naomiklein.org/no-logo/publication-info Klein, N. (2000), No Logo, Knopf Canada: Picador.]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VidaCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA227&lpg=PA227&dq=Merlucci,+A.+(1988),+\u2018\u2018Social+Movements+and+the+Democratization+of+Everyday+life\u2019\u2019+in+J.+Keane+(ed.)&source=bl&ots=A2pidAlVOu&sig=DZHNKpWdu42Y08WYjNckh2NDNKk&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtoPj-3 Merlucci, A. (1988), \u2018\u2018Social Movements and the Democratization of Everyday life\u2019\u2019 in J. Keane (ed.), Civil Society and the State: New European Perspective, London: Verso.]</ref> Therefore, as a political actor, the consumer \u201cis seen as directly responsible not only for him or herself but also for the world\u201d.<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Critical-consumerism-BrewerTrentmann-2006.pdf Sassatelli, R. (2006) \"Virtue, Responsibility and Consumer Choice. Framing Critical Consumerism\"]</ref> The phenomenon of political consumerism takes into account social transformations like globalization, the ever-increasing role of the market and individualization.\n\nStudies from the [[UK]] (Harrison et al. 2005,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=it&lr=&id=iFtkiRK8ZoMC&oi=fnd&pg=PT1&dq=Harrison,+R.,+T.+Newholm,+et+al.+(2005).+The+ethical+consumer.+London+%3B+Thousand+Oaks,+Sage.&ots=5pr9vQBNmh&sig=mHI_dUXoAfOoRIWaQcKWPpzU3e4#v=onepage&q&f=false Harrison, R., T. Newholm, et al. (2005). The ethical consumer. London ; Thousand Oaks, Sage.]</ref> Varul and Wilson-Kovacs 2008,<ref>[http://people.exeter.ac.uk/mzv201/FT%20Results.pdf Varul, M. Z. and D. Wilson-Kovacs (2008). Fair Trade Consumerism as an Everyday Ethical Practice - A Comparative Perspective. University of Exeter, Economic and Social Research Council.]</ref> Zaccai 2007<ref>[http://homepages.ulb.ac.be/~ezaccai/ Zaccai, E.], Ed. (2007). Sustainable Consumption, Ecology and Fair Trade. London, Routledge.</ref>), [[Germany]] (Baringhorst et al. 2007;<ref>[http://www.transcript-verlag.de/978-3-8376-1047-5/political-campaigning-on-the-web Baringhorst, S., V. Kneip, et al., Eds. (2007). Politik mit dem Einkaufswagen. Medienumbr\u00fcche. Bielefeld, transcript Verlag.]</ref> Lamla and Neckel 2006<ref>Lamla, J. and [https://www.wiso.uni-hamburg.de/fachbereich-sowi/professuren/neckel/team/neckel-sighard/publikationen.html S. Neckel], Eds. (2006). Politisierter Konsum - konsumierte Politik. Soziologie der Politik. Wiesbaden, VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaft.</ref>), [[Italy]] (Forno 2006,<ref>[http://coreslab.wikispaces.com/Pubblicazioni+Forno Forno, F. (2006).] La protesta nei consumi: nuove forme (e luoghi) di partecipazione. Consumi e partecipazione politica. Tra azione individuale e mobilitazione colletiva. S. Tosi. Milano, FrancoAngeli.</ref> Tosi 2006,<ref>[http://www.sociologia.unimib.it/DATA/photo/Simone%20Tosi%20CV.pdf Tosi, S.], Ed. (2006). Consumi e partecipazione politica. Tra azione individuale e mobilitazione collettiva. Milano, FrancoAngeli</ref> Sassatelli 2010<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Davolio-Journal-of-Consumer-Culture.pdf Sassatelli, R. and F. Davolio (2010). \"Consumption, Pleasure and Politics: Slow food and the politico- aesthetic problematization of food.\" Journal of Consumer Culture 10(2): 202-232.]</ref>), [[France]] (Chessel and Cochoy 2004,<ref>Chessel, M.-E. and F. Cochoy (2004). \"March\u00e9 et politique. Autour de la consommation engag\u00e9e \" Sciences de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9(62): 3-14.</ref> Dubuisson-Queller 2009<ref>[http://www.cso.edu/cv_equipe.asp?per_id=91 Dubuisson-Quellier, S.] (2009). La consommation engag\u00e9e. Paris, Presses de Sciences Po.</ref>), North America (Johnston et al. 2011,<ref>[https://joseejohnston.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/johnston-szabo-rodney-jcc-2011.pdf Johnston, J., M. Szabo, et al. (2011). \"Good food, good people: Understanding the cultural repertoire of ethical eating.\" Journal of Consumer Culture 11(3): 293-318.]</ref> Johnston and Bauman 2009,<ref>Johnston, J. and S. Baumann (2009) Tension in the Kitchen. Explicit and Implicit Politics in the Gourmet Foodscape. Sociologica Volume, DOI:</ref> Johnston 2008<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227277260_The_Citizen-Consumer_Hybrid_Ideological_Tensions_and_the_Case_of_Whole_Foods_Market Johnston, J. (2008). \"The citizen-consumer hybrid: ideological tensions and the case of Whole Foods Market.\" Theory and Society 37(3): 229-270.]</ref>) and [[Scandinavia]] (Micheletti et al. 2004)<ref>Micheletti, M. (2004). Why more women? Issues of gender and political consumerism. Politics, Products and Markets, Exploring Political Consumerism Past and Present. M. Micheletti, A. Follesdal and D. Stolle. New Brunswick, Transaction Publishers.</ref> argued that consumes are becoming increasingly politicized according to the boycott and buycott principles. In particular, Scandinavian people seems to be more committed in political consumerism, for example [[Sweden]] increased his average of boycotting episodes from 15 percent in 1987 to 29 percent in 1997.<ref>Petersson, Olof, Hermansson, J6rgen, Micheletti, Michele, Teorell, Jan and Westholm, Anders (1998). Demokrati och medborgarskap.Stockholm: SNS.</ref>\n\nNevertheless, it is important to consider that even if a growing number of citizens are turning to the market to express their political and moral concerns,  it is difficult to assess whether political consumerism can also be considered as a meaningful or effective form of political participation.<ref>[http://profs-polisci.mcgill.ca/stolle/Data_files/FinalIJPS2005.pdf Micheletti, M., Stolle, D., Hooghe, M, (2005) Politics in the Supermarket: Political consumerism as form of political participation. International Political Science review]</ref>\n\n== Historical Background ==\n\n[[File:Boston Tea Party.jpg|thumb|The [[Boston Tea Party]] was an important example of boycotting against England |253x253px]]\nThe chase for a fair consumption has deep roots in consumption history, starting for example with the [[American Revolution]]. Sympathizers of the American cause, in those years, refused to buy English goods, to support colons rebellion. This act of conscious choice can be seen as the beginning of both critical and political consumption. Traces of these two concepts can be found at the turn of the nineteenth century, in the [[United States]], where the [[National Consumers League|National Consumer League]] promoted the so-called \u201c[[Whitelist]]s\u201d, in which all the companies that treated fairly their employees were listed.\n\nAt the end of the century, also the first forms of political activism in consumption took place in the United States and Europe, like the \u201cDont Buy Jewish\u201d boycotts. Several organizations were born in those times and in the following centuries, asking the consumers to join the mobilizations as active subjects.\n\nA variety of discourses about the \u201cduty\u201d and the \u201cresponsibilities\u201d of social actors arose after the 1999 [[World Trade Organization]] protests in [[Seattle]]. People were explicitly asked to think that to shop is to vote.<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Critical-consumerism-BrewerTrentmann-2006.pdf Sassatelli, R. (2006) Virtue, Responsibility and Consumer Choice. Framing Critical Consumerism, 219]</ref>\n\n== Boycotting and \"Buycotting\" ==\n[[Boycott]]ing and \"buycotting\" ([[Anti-boycott]]), as a particularly self-conscious form of consumption, are expressions of an individual\u2019s political, ethical or environmental stance. Both boycotting and \"buycotting\" are discrete acts of critical consumption and they are mutually contingent. In fact, if the use-value or utility of a product is important, then it is difficult to view them as separate actions.\n[[File:La2-buynothing.jpg|thumb|240x240px|[[Buy Nothing Day|Buy Nothing Day (BND)]] demonstration in San Francisco, November 2000]]\n'''Boycotting''' refers to abstaining from buying, avoiding specific products or brands to punish companies for undesirable policies or business practices. \"'''Buycotting'''\" is a term coined by Friedman (1996); it refers to \u201cpositive buying\u201d that aims to foster corporations that represent values \u2013 fair trade, environmentalism, sustainable development \u2013 that consumers choose to support.\n\nWhen one boycotts a product or service, it does not mean that he abstains from consuming at all, but that he may select an alternative product or service. Equally, a choice to \"buycott\" could be understood as including a rejection or boycott of the non-ethical alternative. This interdependence is useful to explain the traditional pairing of boycotting and \"buycotting\" in much analysis of consumer politics.\n\nOne of the rising types of boycotting is the ad hoc one, which underlines the importance of consumers as political subjects. These initiatives show that critical consumption is really impacting in special occasions, gaining much more visibility than everyday boycotts. An example of this type of events is the [[Buy Nothing Day|Buy Nothing Day (BND)]].\n\n== Sustainability ==\nThe notion of [[sustainability]] has both a temporal dimension demonstrated by the trade-off between present and future generations, and a justice dimension which considers the different distribution of harm and benefit.<ref>Gamborg, C., &Sand\u00f8e, P. (2005a). Applying the notion of sustainability\u2014Dilemmas and the need for dialogue. In S. Holm & J. Gunning (Eds.), Ethics, Law and Society (pp. 123\u2013130). Hants: Ashgate.</ref> Under the term sustainability, notions of sustainable [[resource consumption]] by [[recycling]], [[environmental protection]], [[animal welfare]], [[social justice]], and climate responsibilities are gathered.<ref>Gamborg, C., &Sand\u00f8e, P. (2005b). Sustainability in farm animal breeding. A review. Animal Production Science, 92(3), 221\u2013231.</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nAlthough the \"good\" purposes of critical consumerism there are some critics and pitfalls connected to this practice of consumption: \n* [[Fair trade]] protocols invite to respect all the communities and their cultures, workers\u2019 rights and so on. At the same time, however, it appears as a hegemonic tool to impose a western culture of which the right standards must be.\n* It requires a huge production of green and ethical products, but it is difficult to realize in the small-scale local production.\n* People live in an asymmetrical world in terms of information. They take decisions just with the use of few elements.\n* \u201cA \u2018paradox of sustainability\u2019 arises because more substantive approaches to sustainability may be too complex to effectively motivate appropriate social responses.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/23760319/Agricultural_sustainability_what_it_is_and_what_it_is_not Thompson, P. B. (2007). Agricultural sustainability: What it is and what it is not. International Journal of Agricultural Sustainability, 51, 5\u201316.]</ref> Moreover, all human food consumption has some kind of impact\u2014hence there will always be some kind of prioritization\u201d.\n\n=== Criticism related to political use of consumption ===\n\n* The idea that every person could be a potential political consumer is not true: ethical products can cost much more than traditional ones and people may not afford so expensive products (e.g. [[organic products]]).\n* It is important to consider that people often buy products to express themselves. People who don\u2019t care about ethical consumption will keep on buying products they like, not depending on political consumption.<ref>[http://www.persee.fr/doc/assr_0335-5985_1992_num_80_1_1564_t1_0249_0000_3 De Certeau, M. (1990). L'invention du quotidien, 1. Arts de faire. Paris, Gallimard.]</ref>\n* According to Shaw and Newholm,<ref>[http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/mar.10008/abstract Shaw, D. and T. Newholm (2002). \"Voluntary Simplicity and the Ethics of Consumption.\" Psychology and Marketing 19(2): 167-185.]</ref> even though single individuals take decisions and choices, political consumption can also be seen as a mass phenomenon. Consumes depend on consumers\u2019 social environment. Moreover, [[Pierre Bourdieu|Bourdieu]]<ref>[https://monoskop.org/images/e/e0/Pierre_Bourdieu_Distinction_A_Social_Critique_of_the_Judgement_of_Taste_1984.pdf Bourdieu, P. (1984). Distinction: a social critique of the judgement of taste. Cambridge, Mass., Harvard University Press]</ref> asserts that consumption is determined by the belonging to a specific [[social class]] which determines our [[habit]]s and what we like.\n\n== Examples ==\nThere are many examples of critical consumerism:\n[[File:Rosaparks.jpg|thumb|235x235px|[[Rosa Parks]] with [[Martin Luther King, Jr.|Martin Luther King]], 1955]]\n* Montgomery boycott was a political and social protest campaign against the policy of [[racial segregation]] on the public transit system of Montgomery, [[Alabama]]. The campaign started on December 5, 1955 - when [[Rosa Parks]], an African American woman, was arrested for refusing to leave her seat to a white person. After that episode, boycotters organized a system of carpools, with car owners volunteering their vehicles or themselves driving people to various destinations.\n* A well-known effective boycott took place against [[Nestl\u00e9]] (1977\u201384) for its marketing campaign of breast milk substitute or infant formula, in the third world. This boycott mobilized consumers on a global-scale and it brought Nestl\u00e8 to the [[World Health Organization]] and United Nations International Children Emergency Fund ([[UNICEF]]) negotiating table. In 1981, the International Code of Marketing of Breastmilk Substitutes was adopted. However, political consumerist groups were not satisfied with the Code implementation and reinstated the boycott in 1988.<ref>Bar-Yam, Naomi Bromberg (1995). \"The Nestle Boycott: The Story of the WHO/UNICEF Code for Marketing Breastmilk Substitutes,\" Mothering (winter): 56-63.</ref>\n* [[Nike, Inc.|Nike inc.]] has been accused for many years of exploiting children labour to produce [[footwear]] and [[apparel]], even though the company has always denied such charge. However, the brand has been highly damaged by both political consumption activism and the publicity it has received on the media. [[Watchdog group|Watchdog groups]] have forced Nike to raise wage levels, changing its sourcing of soccer balls to avoid child labor, raising the minimum age of its factory workers abroad, and insist that all outsourced footwear suppliers adopt US occupational safety and health standards for indoor air quality.<ref>Locke, Richard M. (2003). \"The Promise and Perils of Globalization: The Case of Nike\", MIT IPC Working Paper 02-008. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</ref>\n* There are also several examples of culture consumption association. One of the best known is the \u201c[[No Sweat (organisation)|No Sweat]]\" movement that is a broad-based no-profit organization which fights for the protection of [[sweatshop]] labourers, fights against child labour, forced overtime, poverty wages, unsafe conditions, harassment of women workers and intimidation of trade unionist, not only in developing countries, but also in Britain and the United States.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nike sweatshops]]\n* [[Ethical consumerism]]\n* [[Consumerism]]\n* [[Boycotting]]\n* [[Anti-boycott|Anti-Boycott]]\n* [[Adbusting]]\n* [[Culture jamming]]\n* [[Sustainability]]\n* [[Guilt-Free Consumption]]\n* [[Organic food culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Bellotti, E. and Mora E., (2014) Networks of Practices in Critical Consumption, Sage\n* Sandling, J.A. (2004), Consumerism, Consumption and a Critical Consumer Education for Adults, Wiley Periodicals\n\n[[Category:Consumerism]]\n[[Category:Ethical consumerism]]\n[[Category:Culture]]\n", "text_old": "'''Critical consumption''' is the conscious choice of buying or not buying a specific product according to ethical and political beliefs. The critical [[consumerism|consumer]] recognizes the importance of considering some characteristics of the product and its realization, such as environmental [[sustainability]] and respect of workers\u2019 rights. Indeed, critical consumers take full responsibility for the [[environmental impact|environmental]], social and political effects of their choices. The critical consumer can sympathize with certain [[social movement]] goals and contributes towards them through modifying their consumption behavior.\n\nWork on critical consumption has differed in the terms used to refer to boycotting and buycotting actions. The more prominent include [[Ethical consumerism|ethical consumption]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=it&lr=&id=iFtkiRK8ZoMC&oi=fnd&pg=PT1&dq=Harrison,+R.,+Newholm,+T.+and+Shaw,+D.+(2005)+The+Ethical+Consumer,+London:+Sage.&ots=5pr9vRtHho&sig=SVmSshVUkiRyKAVBhWGtd__r9cA#v=onepage&q=Harrison%2C%20R.%2C%20Newholm%2C%20T.%20and%20Shaw%2C%20D.%20(2005)%20The%20Ethical%20Consumer%2C%20London%3A%20Sage.&f=false Harrison, R., Newholm, T. and Shaw, D. (2005) The Ethical Consumer, London: Sage.]</ref> and [[political consumerism]],<ref>Micheletti, M. (2003) Political Virtue and Shopping, New York: Palgrave Macmillan.</ref> while [[sustainable consumption]], more linked with policy, has also increased in usage.<ref>Spaargaren, G. (2003) \u2018Sustainable consumption: A theoretical and environmental policy perspective\u2019, Society and Natural Resources 16: 687/701.</ref>\n\nOften consumer and citizen are considered as different because consumers only show self-interest, whereas citizens denote expanded self-interest. The general idea is that, consumers \u2018buy what they want\u2014or what they have been persuaded to want\u2014within the limits of what they can get.<ref>[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10460-005-6042-4 Berry, W. (1989). The pleasures of eating. The Journal of Gastronomy, 5, 125\u2013131.]</ref> [[Citizenship]], on the other hand, carries duties or responsibilities along with various rights.<ref>[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.662.5395&rep=rep1&type=pdf Wilkins, J. F. (2005). Eating right here: Moving from consumer to food citizen. Agriculture and Human Values, 22, 269\u2013273]</ref> Since consumers are seen also as citizens they have to behave in a community-oriented, moral and political way, rather than as a self-interested one.\n\n== Political use of consumption ==\n\nA specificity of critical consumption is the political use of consumption, which is the consumers\u2019 choice of \u201c''producers and products with the aim of changing ethically or politically objectionable institutional or market practices''\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bridgingdifferences.mcgill.ca/en/Youth.pdf |title=Micheletti, M., Stolle, D. \"Concept of Political Consumerism\" in ''Youth Activism - An International Encyclopedia'' (2006), Lonnie R. Sherrod (ed.), Westport: Greenwood Publishing. |access-date=2016-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104192116/http://bridgingdifferences.mcgill.ca/en/Youth.pdf |archive-date=2015-01-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their choices depend on different factors as non economic issues that concern personal and family well-being, issue of fairness, justice, ethical or political assessment. Main forms and tools of political use of consumption are [[boycotting]], \"buycotting\" ([[anti-boycott]]ing) and also [[culture jamming]] or [[adbusting]].\n\nPolitical consumerism can be considered as an alternative form of political engagement, especially for young generations. In addition, market-based political strategies of young citizens go beyond boycotting and \u201cbuycotting\u201d; they also started to participate in [[internet campaign]]s becoming active consumers. Their individual choices become political movements able to challenge political and economic powers.<ref>[http://www.naomiklein.org/no-logo/publication-info Klein, N. (2000), No Logo, Knopf Canada: Picador.]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VidaCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA227&lpg=PA227&dq=Merlucci,+A.+(1988),+\u2018\u2018Social+Movements+and+the+Democratization+of+Everyday+life\u2019\u2019+in+J.+Keane+(ed.)&source=bl&ots=A2pidAlVOu&sig=DZHNKpWdu42Y08WYjNckh2NDNKk&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtoPj-3 Merlucci, A. (1988), \u2018\u2018Social Movements and the Democratization of Everyday life\u2019\u2019 in J. Keane (ed.), Civil Society and the State: New European Perspective, London: Verso.]</ref> Therefore, as a political actor, the consumer \u201cis seen as directly responsible not only for him or herself but also for the world\u201d.<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Critical-consumerism-BrewerTrentmann-2006.pdf Sassatelli, R. (2006) \"Virtue, Responsibility and Consumer Choice. Framing Critical Consumerism\"]</ref> The phenomenon of political consumerism takes into account social transformations like globalization, the ever-increasing role of the market and individualization.\n\nStudies from the [[UK]] (Harrison et al. 2005,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=it&lr=&id=iFtkiRK8ZoMC&oi=fnd&pg=PT1&dq=Harrison,+R.,+T.+Newholm,+et+al.+(2005).+The+ethical+consumer.+London+%3B+Thousand+Oaks,+Sage.&ots=5pr9vQBNmh&sig=mHI_dUXoAfOoRIWaQcKWPpzU3e4#v=onepage&q&f=false Harrison, R., T. Newholm, et al. (2005). The ethical consumer. London ; Thousand Oaks, Sage.]</ref> Varul and Wilson-Kovacs 2008,<ref>[http://people.exeter.ac.uk/mzv201/FT%20Results.pdf Varul, M. Z. and D. Wilson-Kovacs (2008). Fair Trade Consumerism as an Everyday Ethical Practice - A Comparative Perspective. University of Exeter, Economic and Social Research Council.]</ref> Zaccai 2007<ref>[http://homepages.ulb.ac.be/~ezaccai/ Zaccai, E.], Ed. (2007). Sustainable Consumption, Ecology and Fair Trade. London, Routledge.</ref>), [[Germany]] (Baringhorst et al. 2007;<ref>[http://www.transcript-verlag.de/978-3-8376-1047-5/political-campaigning-on-the-web Baringhorst, S., V. Kneip, et al., Eds. (2007). Politik mit dem Einkaufswagen. Medienumbr\u00fcche. Bielefeld, transcript Verlag.]</ref> Lamla and Neckel 2006<ref>Lamla, J. and [https://www.wiso.uni-hamburg.de/fachbereich-sowi/professuren/neckel/team/neckel-sighard/publikationen.html S. Neckel], Eds. (2006). Politisierter Konsum - konsumierte Politik. Soziologie der Politik. Wiesbaden, VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaft.</ref>), [[Italy]] (Forno 2006,<ref>[http://coreslab.wikispaces.com/Pubblicazioni+Forno Forno, F. (2006).] La protesta nei consumi: nuove forme (e luoghi) di partecipazione. Consumi e partecipazione politica. Tra azione individuale e mobilitazione colletiva. S. Tosi. Milano, FrancoAngeli.</ref> Tosi 2006,<ref>[http://www.sociologia.unimib.it/DATA/photo/Simone%20Tosi%20CV.pdf Tosi, S.], Ed. (2006). Consumi e partecipazione politica. Tra azione individuale e mobilitazione collettiva. Milano, FrancoAngeli</ref> Sassatelli 2010<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Davolio-Journal-of-Consumer-Culture.pdf Sassatelli, R. and F. Davolio (2010). \"Consumption, Pleasure and Politics: Slow food and the politico- aesthetic problematization of food.\" Journal of Consumer Culture 10(2): 202-232.]</ref>), [[France]] (Chessel and Cochoy 2004,<ref>Chessel, M.-E. and F. Cochoy (2004). \"March\u00e9 et politique. Autour de la consommation engag\u00e9e \" Sciences de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9(62): 3-14.</ref> Dubuisson-Queller 2009<ref>[http://www.cso.edu/cv_equipe.asp?per_id=91 Dubuisson-Quellier, S.] (2009). La consommation engag\u00e9e. Paris, Presses de Sciences Po.</ref>), North America (Johnston et al. 2011,<ref>[https://joseejohnston.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/johnston-szabo-rodney-jcc-2011.pdf Johnston, J., M. Szabo, et al. (2011). \"Good food, good people: Understanding the cultural repertoire of ethical eating.\" Journal of Consumer Culture 11(3): 293-318.]</ref> Johnston and Bauman 2009,<ref>Johnston, J. and S. Baumann (2009) Tension in the Kitchen. Explicit and Implicit Politics in the Gourmet Foodscape. Sociologica Volume, DOI:</ref> Johnston 2008<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/227277260_The_Citizen-Consumer_Hybrid_Ideological_Tensions_and_the_Case_of_Whole_Foods_Market Johnston, J. (2008). \"The citizen-consumer hybrid: ideological tensions and the case of Whole Foods Market.\" Theory and Society 37(3): 229-270.]</ref>) and [[Scandinavia]] (Micheletti et al. 2004)<ref>Micheletti, M. (2004). Why more women? Issues of gender and political consumerism. Politics, Products and Markets, Exploring Political Consumerism Past and Present. M. Micheletti, A. Follesdal and D. Stolle. New Brunswick, Transaction Publishers.</ref> argued that consumes are becoming increasingly politicized according to the boycott and buycott principles. In particular, Scandinavian people seems to be more committed in political consumerism, for example [[Sweden]] increased his average of boycotting episodes from 15 percent in 1987 to 29 percent in 1997.<ref>Petersson, Olof, Hermansson, J6rgen, Micheletti, Michele, Teorell, Jan and Westholm, Anders (1998). Demokrati och medborgarskap.Stockholm: SNS.</ref>\n\nNevertheless, it is important to consider that even if a growing number of citizens are turning to the market to express their political and moral concerns,  it is difficult to assess whether political consumerism can also be considered as a meaningful or effective form of political participation.<ref>[http://profs-polisci.mcgill.ca/stolle/Data_files/FinalIJPS2005.pdf Micheletti, M., Stolle, D., Hooghe, M, (2005) Politics in the Supermarket: Political consumerism as form of political participation. International Political Science review]</ref>\n\n== Historical Background ==\n\n[[File:Boston Tea Party.jpg|thumb|The [[Boston Tea Party]] was an important example of boycotting against England |253x253px]]\nThe chase for a fair consumption has deep roots in consumption history, starting for example with the [[American Revolution]]. Sympathizers of the American cause, in those years, refused to buy English goods, to support colons rebellion. This act of conscious choice can be seen as the beginning of both critical and political consumption. Traces of these two concepts can be found at the turn of the nineteenth century, in the [[United States]], where the [[National Consumers League|National Consumer League]] promoted the so-called \u201c[[Whitelist]]s\u201d, in which all the companies that treated fairly their employees were listed.\n\nAt the end of the century, also the first forms of political activism in consumption took place in the United States and Europe, like the \u201cDont Buy Jewish\u201d boycotts. Several organizations were born in those times and in the following centuries, asking the consumers to join the mobilizations as active subjects.\n\nA variety of discourses about the \u201cduty\u201d and the \u201cresponsibilities\u201d of social actors arose after the 1999 [[World Trade Organization]] protests in [[Seattle]]. People were explicitly asked to think that to shop is to vote.<ref>[http://users2.unimi.it/rsassatelli/wp-content/uploads/Sassatelli-Critical-consumerism-BrewerTrentmann-2006.pdf Sassatelli, R. (2006) Virtue, Responsibility and Consumer Choice. Framing Critical Consumerism, 219]</ref>\n\n== Boycotting and \"Buycotting\" ==\n[[Boycott]]ing and \"buycotting\" ([[Anti-boycott]]), as a particularly self-conscious form of consumption, are expressions of an individual\u2019s political, ethical or environmental stance. Both boycotting and \"buycotting\" are discrete acts of critical consumption and they are mutually contingent. In fact, if the use-value or utility of a product is important, then it is difficult to view them as separate actions.\n[[File:La2-buynothing.jpg|thumb|240x240px|[[Buy Nothing Day|Buy Nothing Day (BND)]] demonstration in San Francisco, November 2000]]\n'''Boycotting''' refers to abstaining from buying, avoiding specific products or brands to punish companies for undesirable policies or business practices. \"'''Buycotting'''\" is a term coined by Friedman (1996); it refers to \u201cpositive buying\u201d that aims to foster corporations that represent values \u2013 fair trade, environmentalism, sustainable development \u2013 that consumers choose to support.\n\nWhen one boycotts a product or service, it does not mean that he abstains from consuming at all, but that he may select an alternative product or service. Equally, a choice to \"buycott\" could be understood as including a rejection or boycott of the non-ethical alternative. This interdependence is useful to explain the traditional pairing of boycotting and \"buycotting\" in much analysis of consumer politics.\n\nOne of the rising types of boycotting is the ad hoc one, which underlines the importance of consumers as political subjects. These initiatives show that critical consumption is really impacting in special occasions, gaining much more visibility than everyday boycotts. An example of this type of events is the [[Buy Nothing Day|Buy Nothing Day (BND)]].\n\n== Sustainability ==\nThe notion of [[sustainability]] has both a temporal dimension demonstrated by the trade-off between present and future generations, and a justice dimension which considers the different distribution of harm and benefit.<ref>Gamborg, C., &Sand\u00f8e, P. (2005a). Applying the notion of sustainability\u2014Dilemmas and the need for dialogue. In S. Holm & J. Gunning (Eds.), Ethics, Law and Society (pp. 123\u2013130). Hants: Ashgate.</ref> Under the term sustainability, notions of sustainable [[resource consumption]] by [[recycling]], [[environmental protection]], [[animal welfare]], [[social justice]], and climate responsibilities are gathered.<ref>Gamborg, C., &Sand\u00f8e, P. (2005b). Sustainability in farm animal breeding. A review. Animal Production Science, 92(3), 221\u2013231.</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\nAlthough the \"good\" purposes of critical consumerism there are some critics and pitfalls connected to this practice of consumption: \n* [[Fair trade]] protocols invite to respect all the communities and their cultures, workers\u2019 rights and so on. At the same time, however, it appears as a hegemonic tool to impose a western culture of which the right standards must be.\n* It requires a huge production of green and ethical products, but it is difficult to realize in the small-scale local production.\n* People live in an asymmetrical world in terms of information. They take decisions just with the use of few elements.\n* \u201cA \u2018paradox of sustainability\u2019 arises because more substantive approaches to sustainability may be too complex to effectively motivate appropriate social responses.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/23760319/Agricultural_sustainability_what_it_is_and_what_it_is_not Thompson, P. B. (2007). Agricultural sustainability: What it is and what it is not. International Journal of Agricultural Sustainability, 51, 5\u201316.]</ref> Moreover, all human food consumption has some kind of impact\u2014hence there will always be some kind of prioritization\u201d.\n\n=== Criticism related to political use of consumption ===\n\n* The idea that every person could be a potential political consumer is not true: ethical products can cost much more than traditional ones and people may not afford so expensive products (e.g. [[organic products]]).\n* It is important to consider that people often buy products to express themselves. People who don\u2019t care about ethical consumption will keep on buying products they like, not depending on political consumption.<ref>[http://www.persee.fr/doc/assr_0335-5985_1992_num_80_1_1564_t1_0249_0000_3 De Certeau, M. (1990). L'invention du quotidien, 1. Arts de faire. Paris, Gallimard.]</ref>\n* According to Shaw and Newholm,<ref>[http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/mar.10008/abstract Shaw, D. and T. Newholm (2002). \"Voluntary Simplicity and the Ethics of Consumption.\" Psychology and Marketing 19(2): 167-185.]</ref> even though single individuals take decisions and choices, political consumption can also be seen as a mass phenomenon. Consumes depend on consumers\u2019 social environment. Moreover, [[Pierre Bourdieu|Bourdieu]]<ref>[https://monoskop.org/images/e/e0/Pierre_Bourdieu_Distinction_A_Social_Critique_of_the_Judgement_of_Taste_1984.pdf Bourdieu, P. (1984). Distinction: a social critique of the judgement of taste. Cambridge, Mass., Harvard University Press]</ref> asserts that consumption is determined by the belonging to a specific [[social class]] which determines our [[habit]]s and what we like.\n\n== Examples ==\nThere are many examples of critical consumerism:\n[[File:Rosaparks.jpg|thumb|235x235px|[[Rosa Parks]] with [[Martin Luther King, Jr.|Martin Luther King]], 1955]]\n* Montgomery boycott was a political and social protest campaign against the policy of [[racial segregation]] on the public transit system of Montgomery, [[Alabama]]. The campaign started on December 5, 1955 - when [[Rosa Parks]], an African American woman, was arrested for refusing to leave her seat to a white person. After that episode, boycotters organized a system of carpools, with car owners volunteering their vehicles or themselves driving people to various destinations.\n* A well-known effective boycott took place against [[Nestl\u00e9]] (1977\u201384) for its marketing campaign of breast milk substitute or infant formula, in the third world. This boycott mobilized consumers on a global-scale and it brought Nestl\u00e8 to the [[World Health Organization]] and United Nations International Children Emergency Fund ([[UNICEF]]) negotiating table. In 1981, the International Code of Marketing of Breastmilk Substitutes was adopted. However, political consumerist groups were not satisfied with the Code implementation and reinstated the boycott in 1988.<ref>Bar-Yam, Naomi Bromberg (1995). \"The Nestle Boycott: The Story of the WHO/UNICEF Code for Marketing Breastmilk Substitutes,\" Mothering (winter): 56-63.</ref>\n* [[Nike, Inc.|Nike inc.]] has been accused for many years of exploiting children labour to produce [[footwear]] and [[apparel]], even though the company has always denied such charge. However, the brand has been highly damaged by both political consumption activism and the publicity it has received on the media. [[Watchdog group|Watchdog groups]] have forced Nike to raise wage levels, changing its sourcing of soccer balls to avoid child labor, raising the minimum age of its factory workers abroad, and insist that all outsourced footwear suppliers adopt US occupational safety andhealth standards for indoor air quality.<ref>Locke, Richard M. (2003). \"The Promise and Perils of Globalization: The Case of Nike\", MIT IPC Working Paper 02-008. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</ref>\n* There are also several examples of culture consumption association. One of the best known is the \u201c[[No Sweat (organisation)|No Sweat]]\" movement that is a broad-based no-profit organization which fights for the protection of [[sweatshop]] labourers, fights against child labour, forced overtime, poverty wages, unsafe conditions, harassment of women workers and intimidation of trade unionist, not only in developing countries, but also in Britain and the United States.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nike sweatshops]]\n* [[Ethical consumerism]]\n* [[Consumerism]]\n* [[Boycotting]]\n* [[Anti-boycott|Anti-Boycott]]\n* [[Adbusting]]\n* [[Culture jamming]]\n* [[Sustainability]]\n* [[Guilt-Free Consumption]]\n* [[Organic food culture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Bellotti, E. and Mora E., (2014) Networks of Practices in Critical Consumption, Sage\n* Sandling, J.A. (2004), Consumerism, Consumption and a Critical Consumer Education for Adults, Wiley Periodicals\n\n[[Category:Consumerism]]\n[[Category:Ethical consumerism]]\n[[Category:Culture]]\n", "name_user": "Daask", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix whitespace", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Critical_consumerism"}
{"title_page": "Tolgus Mount", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|static_image_name        = The Murdoch Flyer - geograph.org.uk - 98782.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = The Murdoch Flyer\n|official_name            = Tolgus Mount\n|cornish_name             =\n|coordinates              = {{coord|50.2405|-5.2481|display=inline,title}}\n|civil_parish             = Redruth\n|population               =\n|population_ref           =\n|unitary_england          = [[Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england      = [[Cornwall]]\n|country                  = England\n|region                   = South West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Camborne and Redruth (UK Parliament constituency)|Camborne and Redruth]]\n|post_town                = REDRUTH\n|postcode_district        = TR15\n|postcode_area            = TR\n|dial_code                = 01209\n|os_grid_reference        = SW684428\n}}\n\n'''Tolgus Mount''' (also Tolgus or Tolgoose<ref name=\"Polsue1872\">{{cite book|last=Polsue|first=Joseph|title=A complete parochial history of the county of Cornwall: compiled from the best authorities & corrected and improved from actual survey ; illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRwiAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1872|publisher=W. Lake}}</ref>) is a village, valley, and district in the parish of [[Redruth]] in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. It is located to the northwest of town of Redruth across the [[A30 road]]. Historically there were several mines in the area, mining tin and copper.\n\n==History==\nHistorically Tolgus was known for its tin mining and there were several mines in the area including West, East and South Tolgus.<ref name=\"Britain)1983\">{{cite book|author=Newcomen Society (Great Britain)|title=Industrial archaeology: the journal of the history of industry and technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wsG6AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1983|publisher=Lambarde Press.|page=94}}</ref> The area produced several hundred tons of black tin between 1847 and 1869 and 57 tons between 1847 and 1863 in the East Tolgus Mine and many more tons of [[copper ore]].<ref name=\"Collins1912\"/> The South Tolgus Mine was 157 fathoms deep, the West Tolgus Mine 135 fathoms deep and the Great South Tolgus 80 fathoms deep as reported in 1922.<ref name=\"Britain1922\">{{cite book|author=Geological Survey of Great Britain|title=Special reports on the mineral resources of Great Britain ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2dIRAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1922|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=157}}</ref> In 1884 the manor of Tolgus reportedly consisted of 212 tenements and 1006 acres.<ref name=\"Bond\">{{cite book|last=Bond|first=Chris|title=An Index to the Historical Place Names of Cornwall \u2013 Volume 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IR6v7hOdAucC&pg=PA281|accessdate=19 January 2012|publisher=Cornovia Press|isbn=978-0-9522064-3-9|page=281}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:The A30 road crosses the stream near West Tolgus - geograph.org.uk - 85177.jpg|thumb|left|The A30 road crosses the stream near West Tolgus]]\nTolgus forms a valley to the northwest of Redruth.<ref name=\"Commons1879\">{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|title=Reports from commissioners|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QyxcAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1879|publisher=House of Commons|page=257}}</ref> It lies in the parish of [[Redruth]] to the northwest across the [[A30 road]] and is spread over an area which is known as Tolgus with parts such as [[West Tolgus]], South Tolgus, East Tolgus.<ref name=\"Collins1912\">{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Joseph Henry|title=Observations on the west of England mining region: being an account of the mineral deposits and economic geology of the region, and forming vol. XIV of the transactions of the Royal Geological Society of Cornwall|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqJBAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1912|publisher=Author}}</ref><ref name=\"Roma2000\">{{cite book|title=The Journal of European economic history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T56zAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=2000|publisher=Banco di Roma.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Mining and smelting magazine\">{{cite book|title=The Mining and smelting magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kV4AAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA318|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1862|publisher=The Office|page=318}}</ref> [[Paynter's Lane End]] lies to the northwest and the hamlet of North Country to the northeast. There is a stream running in the area which runs under the A30.\n\n==Notable landmarks==\nThe Cornish Goldsmith's Centre lies the old mill at Tolgus today, although this northern part of the village is closest to North Country and often considered part of it. Tolgus Tin, covering 20 acres, is now a working museum, showcasing the old mining machinery.<ref name=\"Western miner\">{{cite book|title=Western miner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q08SAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1975|page=37}}</ref> The land surrounding this mill forms part of [[West Cornwall Bryophytes]] [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref name=SSSI>{{cite web|title=West Cornwall Bryophytes|url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/2000365.pdf|publisher=[[Natural England]]|accessdate=31 January 2012|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nThere is a candle factory at Tolgus Mount \"where the path leads towards the Old Portreath Road\".<ref name=\"Michell1978\">{{cite book|last=Michell|first=Frank|title=Annals of an ancient Cornish town: being notes on the history of Redruth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JStWAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1978|publisher=Dyllansow Truran}}</ref> There is a house called Tolgus House in the village, occupied by Edmund Percival James in the 1960s.<ref name=\"The electrical review\">{{cite book|title=The electrical review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FKIiAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1955|publisher=Electrical Review, Ltd.|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"The Medical directory ...: London, provinces, Wales, Scotland, Ireland, abroad, navy, army & air force\">{{cite book|title=The Medical directory ...: London, provinces, Wales, Scotland, Ireland, abroad, navy, army & air force|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IA4gAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1968|publisher=J. & A. Churchill, ltd.|page=1190}}</ref> Other features in the area include Brunton's arsenic calciner, Tehidy Holiday Park, Tricky's Hotel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-commercial.co.uk/news/new-instructions/1580-trickys-tolgus-mount-redruth|title=Tricky's, Tolgus Mount, Redruth|publisher=Miller Commercial|accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref> Tolgus Cottage and Dalgover House. There is a full-scale replica of a steam carriage which [[William Murdoch]] built as a working model in 1784 called \"The Murdoch Flyer\" situated in the centre of Tolgus roundabout on the other side of the A30 on the outskirts of Redruth. The road from there leads across the A30 to Tolgus.<ref name=OS>Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 203 ''Land's End'' {{ISBN|978-0-319-23148-7}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Tolgus Mill - geograph.org.uk - 321463.jpg|Tolgus Mill\nFile:Tolgus mill water hammer - geograph.org.uk - 321472.jpg|Tolgus mill water hammer\nFile:Donkeys near Great South Tolgus Mine - geograph.org.uk - 1185489.jpg|Donkeys near Great South Tolgus Mine\nFile:Brunton's arsenic calciner - geograph.org.uk - 290146.jpg|Brunton's arsenic calciner\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Redruth]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|static_image_name        = The Murdoch Flyer - geograph.org.uk - 98782.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = The Murdoch Flyer\n|official_name            = Tolgus Mount\n|cornish_name             =\n|coordinates              = {{coord|50.2405|-5.2481|display=inline,title}}\n|civil_parish             = Redruth\n|population               =\n|population_ref           =\n|unitary_england          = [[Cornwall]]\n|lieutenancy_england      = [[Cornwall]]\n|country                  = England\n|region                   = South West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Camborne and Redruth (UK Parliament constituency)|Camborne and Redruth]]\n|post_town                = REDRUTH\n|postcode_district        = TR15\n|postcode_area            = TR\n|dial_code                = 01209\n|os_grid_reference        = SW684428\n}}\n\n'''Tolgus Mount''' (also Tolgus or Tolgoose<ref name=\"Polsue1872\">{{cite book|last=Polsue|first=Joseph|title=A complete parochial history of the county of Cornwall: compiled from the best authorities & corrected and improved from actual survey ; illustrated|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRwiAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1872|publisher=W. Lake}}</ref>) is a village, valley, and district in the parish of [[Redruth]] in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. It is located to the northwest of town of Redruth across the [[A30 road]]. Historically there were several mines in the area, mining tin and copper.\n\n==History==\nHistorically Tolgus was known for its tin mining and there were several mines in the area including West, East and South Tolgus.<ref name=\"Britain)1983\">{{cite book|author=Newcomen Society (Great Britain)|title=Industrial archaeology: the journal of the history of industry and technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wsG6AAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1983|publisher=Lambarde Press.|page=94}}</ref> The area produced several hundred tons of black tin between 1847 and 1869 and 57 tons between 1847 and 1863 in the East Tolgus Mine and many more tons of [[copper ore]].<ref name=\"Collins1912\"/> The South Tolgus Mine was 157 fathoms deep, the West Tolgus Mine 135 fathoms deep and the Great South Tolgus 80 fathoms deep as reported in 1922.<ref name=\"Britain1922\">{{cite book|author=Geological Survey of Great Britain|title=Special reports on the mineral resources of Great Britain ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2dIRAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1922|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|page=157}}</ref> In 1884 the manor of Tolgus reportedly consisted of 212 tenements and 1006 acres.<ref name=\"Bond\">{{cite book|last=Bond|first=Chris|title=An Index to the Historical Place Names of Cornwall \u2013 Volume 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IR6v7hOdAucC&pg=PA281|accessdate=19 January 2012|publisher=Cornovia Press|isbn=978-0-9522064-3-9|page=281}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:The A30 road crosses the stream near West Tolgus - geograph.org.uk - 85177.jpg|thumb|left|The A30 road crosses the stream near West Tolgus]]\nTolgus forms a valley to the northwest of Redruth.<ref name=\"Commons1879\">{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|title=Reports from commissioners|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QyxcAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1879|publisher=House of Commons|page=257}}</ref> It lies in the parish of [[Redruth]] to the northwest across the [[A30 road]] and is spread over an area which is known as Tolgus with parts such as [[West Tolgus]], South Tolgus, East Tolgus.<ref name=\"Collins1912\">{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Joseph Henry|title=Observations on the west of England mining region: being an account of the mineral deposits and economic geology of the region, and forming vol. XIV of the transactions of the Royal Geological Society of Cornwall|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqJBAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1912|publisher=Author}}</ref><ref name=\"Roma2000\">{{cite book|title=The Journal of European economic history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T56zAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=2000|publisher=Banco di Roma.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Mining and smelting magazine\">{{cite book|title=The Mining and smelting magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kV4AAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA318|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1862|publisher=The Office|page=318}}</ref> [[Paynter's Lane End]] lies to the northwest and the hamlet of North Country to the northeast. There is a stream running in the area which runs under the A30.\n\n==Notable landmarks==\nThe Cornish Goldsmith's Centre lies the old mill at Tolgus today, although this northern part of the village is closest to North Country and often considered part of it. Tolgus Tin, covering 20 acres, is now a working museum, showcasing the old mining machinery.<ref name=\"Western miner\">{{cite book|title=Western miner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q08SAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1975|page=37}}</ref> The land surrounding this mill forms part of [[West Cornwall Bryophytes]] [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref name=SSSI>{{cite web|title=West Cornwall Bryophytes|url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/2000365.pdf|publisher=[[Natural England]]|accessdate=31 January 2012|year=1999}}</ref>\n\nThere is a candle factory at Tolgus Mount \"where the path leads towards the Old Portreath Road\".<ref name=\"Michell1978\">{{cite book|last=Michell|first=Frank|title=Annals of an ancient Cornish town: being notes on the history of Redruth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JStWAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1978|publisher=Dyllansow Truran}}</ref> There is a house called Tolgus House in the village, occupied by Edmund Percival James in the 1960s.<ref name=\"The electrical review\">{{cite book|title=The electrical review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FKIiAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1955|publisher=Electrical Review, Ltd.|page=146}}</ref><ref name=\"The Medical directory ...: London, provinces, Wales, Scotland, Ireland, abroad, navy, army & air force\">{{cite book|title=The Medical directory ...: London, provinces, Wales, Scotland, Ireland, abroad, navy, army & air force|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IA4gAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=19 January 2012|year=1968|publisher=J. & A. Churchill, ltd.|page=1190}}</ref> Other features in the area include Brunton's arsenic calciner, Tehidy Holiday Park, Tricky's Hotel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miller-commercial.co.uk/news/new-instructions/1580-trickys-tolgus-mount-redruth|title=Tricky's, Tolgus Mount, Redruth|publisher=Miller Commercial|accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref> Tolgus Cottage and Dalgover House. There is a full-scale replica of a steam carriage which [[William Murdoch]] built as a working model in 1784 called \"The Murdoch Flyer\" situated in the centre of Tolgus roundabout on the other side of the A30 on the outskirts of Redruth. The road from there leads across the A30 to Tolgus.<ref name=OS>Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 203 ''Land's End'' {{ISBN|978-0-319-23148-7}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Tolgus Mill - geograph.org.uk - 321463.jpg|Tolgus Mill\nFile:Tolgus mill water hammer - geograph.org.uk - 321472.jpg|Tolgus mill water hammer\nFile:Donkeys near Great South Tolgus Mine - geograph.org.uk - 1185489.jpg|Donkeys near Great South Tolgus Mine\nFile:Brunton's arsenic calciner - geograph.org.uk - 290146.jpg|Brunton's arsenic calciner\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Mining in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Redruth]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tolgus_Mount"}
